<FIRST>r a PM-People-Friars-Women     10-17 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Friars-Women,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Extra, Extra: Willis Roasted, Women Watch</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was a typical Friars Club roast: celebrity
victim (Bruce Willis); dais thick with cigar smoke (thanks, Uncle
Miltie); air blue with obscene jokes (sorry, not printable). But
this time, for the first time, women were permitted to share in the
fun.
   ``They have caved in to reality, surrendered to reality. ...
They have to enter the 20th century,'' said attorney Gloria Allred,
whose complaint about the Friars' no-women roast policy opened the
doors Tuesday for about two dozen females at the Willis affair.
   Ms. Allred entered after a brief but nasty exchange with a Friar
who told her, ``You're yesterday's news, lady. We don't care about
you.'' Ms. Allred, proclaiming ``sexism is yesterday's news,''
walked past him.
   ``I feel it should have been done a long time ago,'' said
Marilyn Haft, an entertainment lawyer who attended the roast. ``But
it's sexism, and it takes time to change sexism.''
   Ms. Allred arrived at the Sheraton Centre shortly before the
noon roast, anticipating a fight to get in. But other female guests
already had entered the roasting room, preventing a repeat of the
Ernest Borgnine affair she was ejected from last year.
   The Friars, founded in 1904, have banned women from their roasts
with only a few exceptions: Lucille Ball and Phyllis Diller have
been roastees. Never before were women allowed in the audience.
   Despite the presence of the ladies, the roasters promised the
usual raunchy routines would not be toned down.
   ``After my five minutes, Bruce will be convicted of a felony,
I'm sure,'' said comedian Rick Ducommon. ``He might get a light
sentence, being such a big star, but he'll be convicted.''
   The Friars seemed to take the new policy in stride. Even Henny
Youngman, who engaged in a much-publicized argument with Ms. Allred
last year over the club's lunch policy banning women, appeared
kinder and gentler.
   ``Nobody bothers me any more. I got money saved,'' said Youngman.
   Comic Gilbert Gottfried felt the admission of women, while a
good thing, would not be personally rewarding.
   ``They could allow millions of women in here, and it still
wouldn't help me,'' said Gottfried. ``I'd still end up going home
with Henny Youngman.''
</TEXT>
