<FIRST>u w AM-SFEarthquake-Predictions 1stLd-Writethru   10-17 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SF Earthquake-Predictions, 1st Ld-Writethru,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>This Quake a Warning of a Larger One, USGS Chief Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf: ``The committee,'' to insert 30-year time frame
for 50 percent estimate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The San Francisco earthquake Tuesday was ``a
good warning,'' the head of the U.S. Geological Survey said.
   `The question is not whether a big earthquake is coming. The
question is when,'' said Dallas Peck, director of the service, in
an interview.
   Tuesday's quake was ``not a trivial earthquake, but it was not a
1906 earthquake,'' Peck said.
   The survey's geologists estimated the magnitude of Tuesday's
tremor at anywhere from 6.2 to 6.9 on the Richter scale _ ``we'll
pin that down,'' Peck said _ while the 1906 quake has been
estimated at up to 8.3.
   Tuesday's quake ``is telling us we've got a lot to learn and to
do better,'' strenghtening buildings and other structures to
withstand a major quake, Peck said.
   At present there is no way of warning of a specific quake at a
specific time _ but odds can be calculated. ``There was no
warning'' of Tuesday's, Peck noted.
   In July 1988, a committee of experts convened by the Geological
Survey was more worried about Southern California than the San
Francisco area.
   The committee estimated that a major quake _ one measuring 7.0
on the Richter scale _ had a 50 percent chance of occuring in the
San Francisco area along the San Andreas Fault, the fault involved
in Tuesday's shocks, during the next 30 years.
   That committee said the chance of such a quake in the following
10 years was about one in five.
   But a repetition of the 1906 quake was given odds of less than
one in 10 during the next 30 years.
   The San Andreas Fault runs along the western side of San
Francisco Bay. The Hayward Fault runs along the eastern side, and
the committee gave the same odds for a quake there.
   Southern California was seen at more risk.
   The committee said there was a 60 percent chance of a
7.5-magnitude quake along the Southern California segments of the
San Andreas Fault, and a 50 percent chance of one of magnitude 8.0
or greater.
   Elsewhere in Southern California, the committee put the chance
of a 6.5 quake on the Imperial Fault at 50 percent over 30 years,
and the chance of a 6.5 to 7.0 quake on the San Jacinto Fault near
SAn Bernardino-Riverside at at the same 50 percent during 30 years.
</TEXT>
