<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     10-17 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0625</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAND ISLAND, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The telephone was ringing off the hook
at a company that specializes in belly dancers and ``exotic apes,''
courtesy of some unexpected advertising on ``Monday Night
Football.''
   The ABC telecast pitting the Los Angeles Rams and Buffalo Bills
showed a classified ad placed last week in the Buffalo News
designed to recharge the Bills' sluggish defense.
   But the camera shot also took in the ad that appeared just above
it: ``BELLY &amp; hula dancers, exotic apes, male dancers, 773-2433.''
   ABC announcers Frank Gifford and Dan Dierdorf joked about the
belly dancers and emphasized they weren't advising people to call
the number. That, of course, caught the attention of a nationwide
audience looking for some thrills during what had been a dull game
up to that point.
   As of Tuesday, at least 75 people had telephoned the Showbiz
Entertainment Service run by Nick and Marlene Sidoti out of their
home in Grand Island, just north of Buffalo.
   ``For a $4 ad, I got myself $75,000 or $100,000 worth of
advertising,'' Sidoti said. ``Thank you, ABC.''
   ``They were asking if we could send entertainment over for
halftime,'' Sidoti said. ``One guy said, `Why did you put the ad
on? Why didn't you just put the belly dancers on?'''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHIPPEWA FALLS, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Axel Hanson capped a perfect driving
career with what officials called a rare act: voluntarily giving up
his driver's license at age 88.
   ``I figured at my age I might make a wrong move sometime or
other,'' Hanson said. ``I thought it was a good idea to give up my
license for my own safety and for other people, too. I would hate
to be the cause of an accident.''
   Officials at the state driver's license examiners office in Eau
Claire said Hanson's decision was nearly as rare as his excellent
driving record _ no accidents or citations in 72 years on the road.
   ``In my 24 years as an examiner I maybe have seen six such
cases,'' said examiner Eldon Lustig. ``It's very rare when they
come in out of the blue and give up their license such as Mr.
Hanson did.''
   Hanson said he began driving at age 16. The first car he bought
was a 1921 Ford Roadster; the last was a 1966 Plymouth Valiant sold
to him 11 years ago by his son Wayne.
   Wayne Hanson accompanied his father to the examiners' office.
``I let Dad drive those last few blocks to the office and he was as
good as ever,'' the younger said.
   ``Now I'll just walk, I guess,'' his father said, ``and it will
be Wayne's turn to take us on Sunday afternoon drives.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>YPSILANTI, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Just the thought of eating fried chicken
at 8:30 a.m. might send some folks running for a sweet roll and
coffee.
   Not Orville Dickerson. He wouldn't miss being first in line for
the famous 50-cent anniversary chicken dinners at Haab's restaurant
in downtown Ypsilanti.
   It's the eighth time Dickerson has been first in line since
Haab's began celebrating its anniversary eight years ago with
prices from its original 1934 menu.
   Dickerson, 60, joined 2,139 other people who took advantage of
Haab's 55th anniversary feast Monday.
   Haab's co-owner Mike Kabat said 1,720 people ordered the chicken
dinner, which regularly sells for $7.45, about 260 ordered the
40-cent spaghetti plate and 151 ate 20-cent barbecued sandwiches.
   ``It's nice it only comes once a year, but it's nice to be able
to do something like this for people,'' said Nancy Hyde, after
spending five hours waiting on tables.
</TEXT>
