<DOCNO> AP891017-0011 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-89 0020EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-HanfordWaste     10-17 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hanford Waste,400</SECOND>
<UNK>Report Says Explosive</UNK>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tanks of radioactive waste at the government's
nuclear reservation in Washington state contain a potentially
explosive mixture, according to a five-year-old consultant's report.
   The report, never made public, was compiled by Batelle Northwest
Laboratories for the operators of the Hanford Nuclear Reservation
in 1984, Rockwell International Corp., according to a congressional
expert who described its contents Monday night on condition he not
be identified.
   The report estimated the potential explosive power of the
mixture at 37 tons of TNT if all the worst-case assumptions
underlying its analysis turned out to be true. Such an explosion
would not be a nuclear blast but could scattered radioactivity
widely.
   The explosion of a similar tank at Kyshtym in the Soviet Union
in 1957 or 1958 scattered intense radioactivity over an area the
size of Rhode Island, killing hundreds of people and forcing such
an extensive resettlement program that 30 villages simply
disappeared from maps.
   Environmental groups have said similar tanks at the Savannah
River site in South Carolina also pose a threat of explosion.
   The Hanford mixture could explode if it got too hot, and as long
as the waste is kept sufficiently moist, ``I don't think
realistically you can expect these tanks to blow up tomorrow,'' the
expert said.
   He said the tank mixtures are at about 100 to 200 degrees
Fahrenheit, while a realistic explosive danger would not arise
until the temperature reached 300 to 400 degrees.
   The expert said he obtained the report through state officials.
The Energy Department considered the report a draft which did not
have to be released, he said.
   Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio, has said he will raise the report at a
confirmation hearing Tuesday for the first members of the Energy
Department's Defense Nuclear Facilities Safety Board, the expert
said. Glenn was the author of the law that established the
five-member board last year.
   According to this expert's description, from 1954 to 1975
ferrocyanide was added to the liquid waste stream to precipitate
radioactive cesium and radioactive stronitum, two metals.
   The resulting less-radioactive liquid was dumped in the ground
and the two metals were removed while the ferrocyanide built up in
14 of 149 single-shelled waste tanks, he said.
   In all, 140 metric tons, about 154 U.S. tons, of ferrocyanide
waste accumulated in the tanks, and as much as 30 metric tons could
be in one tank, the expert said.
   The mushy waste complex also contains nitrate compounds that
could explode and is generating explosive hydrogen and methane
cases which have to be vented to the atmosphere, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
