<FIRST>r a PM-BoxOffice     10-17 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Box Office,0520</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Look Who's Talking' Heads Box Office</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sometimes funny ``Look Who's Talking'' made
its debut as the nation's biggest moneymaker last weekend. ``Black
Rain'' dropped to fifth after three weeks at the top.
   Woody Allen's latest movie ``Crimes and Misdemeanors'' earned a
fair $14,000 per screen in limited release in its first weekend.
   ``Look Who's Talking,'' starring John Travolta, Kirstie Alley
and Bruce Willis, collected $12.1 million, the biggest opening for
any fall film, said Deborah Stein, a spokeswoman for its producer,
Management Company Entertainment Group.
   The previous fall record was set earlier this year by ``Sea of
Love.''
   In second last weekend was the latest dead teen-ager sequel
``Halloween V: The Revenge of Michael Myers.'' The slasher film
grossed $5.1 million in its debut.
   ``Sea of Love,'' the romantic thriller starring Al Pacino as a
detective whose chief murder suspect (Ellen Barkin) is also his
lover, sold $3.611 million worth of tickets to come in third.
   In fourth was Tom Selleck's prison drama ``An Innocent Man,''
earning $3.605 million. ``Black Rain,'' the international crime
caper starring Michael Douglas, earned $3.4 million last weekend.
   ``The Fabulous Baker Boys,'' the stylish comedy-drama featuring
Jeff and Beau Bridges as a struggling lounge act, opened in sixth
with $3.3 million in a limited release on 858 screens.
   In seventh was the family comedy ``Parenthood,'' with income of
$1.7 million. It was followed by the babysitting farce ``Uncle
Buck'' in eighth with $1.54 million.
   Rounding out the top 10 were the romantic comedy ``When Harry
Met Sally ...'' in ninth with $1.2 million, and ``Crimes and
Misdemeanors'' with $911,385. Allen's movie was released to only 66
theaters.
   Jane Fonda's and Gregory Peck's ``Old Gringo'' fell out of the
top 10 after just one week. In grossing only $501,810 last weekend,
``Old Gringo'' looks to be dead.
   Here are the top movies for the weekend as tallied by Exhibitor
Relations Co.:
   1. ``Look Who's Talking,'' Tri-Star, $12.1 million weekend
gross, 1,208 screens, $10,023 per screen, $12.1 million total
gross, one week in release.
   2. ``Halloween V: The Revenge of Michael Myers,'' Galaxy, $5.1
million, 1,483 screens, $3,435 per screen, $5.1 million, one week.
   3. ``Sea of Love,'' Universal, $3.611 million, 1,439 screens,
$2,510 per screen, $42.3 million, five weeks.
   4. ``An Innocent Man,'' Disney, $3.605 million, 1,560 screens,
$2,310 per screen, $11.5 million, two weeks.
   5. ``Black Rain,'' Paramount, $3.4 million, 1,760 screens,
$1,955 per screen, $32.4 million, four weeks.
   6. ``The Fabulous Baker Boys,'' 20th Century Fox, $3.3 million,
858 screens, $3,862 per screen, $3.3 million, one week.
   7. ``Parenthood,'' Universal, $1.7 million, 1,314 screens,
$1,285 per screen, $87.5 million, 11 weeks.
   8. ``Uncle Buck,'' Universal, $1.54 million, 1,370 screens,
$1,130 per screen, $58.6 million, nine weeks.
   9. ``When Harry Met Sally ...,'' Columbia, $1.2 million, 1,162
screens, $1,058 per screen, $85.1 million, 14 weeks.
   10. ``Crimes and Misdemeanors,'' Orion, $911,385, 66 screens,
$13,808 per screen, $911,385, one week.
</TEXT>
