<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-89 0138EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Royals     10-17 0702</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Royals,0723</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pregnant Daughter of Queen's Cousin Publicizes Family Rift</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BEN DOBBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marina Ogilvy is two months pregnant and refuses
to marry the father until the child is born. She says her parents
are demanding they marry now or have an abortion.
   It is a sad and commonplace tale of modern morality, but it is
also an uncommonly public royal scandal: Miss Ogilvy is 24th in
line to the throne, her mother being the first cousin of Queen
Elizabeth II.
   The royal family recently suffered the breakup of the marriage
of Princess Anne, the queen's daughter. Now, royal-watchers say,
Miss Ogilvy, 23, has broken palace taboos by going public in lurid
detail about her estrangement from her parents, Sir Angus Ogilvy
and Princess Alexandra.
   The affair took on bigger dimensions Monday when Miss Ogilvy,
clutching the hand of boyfriend Paul Mowatt, broadcast a tearful
plea to her mother over BBC-TV.
   ``I want you to really stand by me and love me as a mother,''
she said in the taped interview with host Robert Kilroy-Silk.
   ``We believe we are doing the right thing and it's what we want
to do,'' Miss Ogilvy said.
   ``I don't agree that Marina should be pushed up the aisle into,
as such, a shotgun wedding,'' Mowatt said. They said the baby is
due in May and they plan to marry sometime afterward.
   Miss Ogilvy said in an interview published Oct. 9 in Today, a
London tabloid, that her parents had tried to trick her into an
abortion, disowned her, and cut off her $160,000 trust fund and
$450 monthly allowance.
   Her parents, in brief statements from their official St. James's
Palace residence, denied being ``cut off'' from their daughter.
They also have a son, James.
   ``Marina's parents sadly do not know where she is but Marina has
their (telephone) numbers and they would love her to get in touch
with them,'' said a statement issued Sunday night.
   Kilroy-Silk duly obliged by asking one of his talk show guests,
a royal-watching journalist who knows Miss Ogilvy, to give her
parents the phone number.
   The parents are making an official tour to India and Nepal later
this week and ``at the moment the tour has to proceed,'' said their
spokeswoman.
   Buckingham Palace, the queen's residence, declined to comment.
   Princess Alexandra, 52, receives $230,000 annually from the
money the state gives the queen, and it pays mainly for official
duties. Ogilvy, a commoner businessman, refused a royal title when
he married Alexandra in 1963.
   Mowatt, a 26-year-old free-lance photographer, says he did not
know Miss Ogilvy had royal connections until after their affair
began. Miss Ogilvy says that when she and Mowatt visited her
parents at their Richmond Park mansion in west London on Sept. 29,
they issued an ultimatum ``that you both get married before you
have the child or you have an abortion. If you don't do that we
don't really want anything to do with you.''
   ``I expected them to say ... whatever decision you come to, I
want you to know we will stand by you,'' she said.
   Andrew Morton, author of seven books on royalty, was quoted in
The Sunday Times as saying Miss Ogilvy had committed ``an act of
betrayal. ... No member of the royal family has ever done anything
as bitter as this.''
   Harold Brooks-Baker, publishing director of the British
bluebloods' bible, Burke's Peerage, said he was dismayed by Miss
Ogilvy's public antics.
   ``The strength of the royal family is that they've always closed
ranks and stuck together,'' he said. ``Disagreements always
happened behind palace walls.''
   He described Princess Alexandra as ``probably the most
compassionate person the royal family ever produced. ... No child
should act that way even toward parents who are less perfect than
these (the Ogilvys) are.''
   ``She has exposed the Achilles heel of the royal family to the
world,'' he said. ``If we're going to look at every single human
foible that people in the royal family have and decide the post is
no longer useful, the monarchy will disappear.
   ``It's of great interest to the public but not in the public
interest,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891017-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-89 0132EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Israel-Rodeo     10-17 0699</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Rodeo,0718</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cowpokes, Ponies Arrive in Holy Land</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEVE ILAN, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anthony Lipschitz lifted himself into
the silver-trimmed saddle atop the gray Arabian, pulled down his
black cowboy hat and rode into the corral to start the first rodeo
ever seen in these here parts.
   The rocky hills west of Jerusalem seem an unlikely spot for a
rodeo, but Lipschitz and his partner, Doobi Solomon, on Monday
managed to draw a crowd of several hundred to watch the horseplay,
eat corn on the cob, and listen to songs such as ``You Are My
Sunshine.''
   Riders from the Galilee, the Golan and even the occupied West
Bank roped calves, pushed their steeds around barrels and made mad
leaps onto galloping horses in the pony express ride, much to the
delight of younsters in skullcaps packing plastic pistols.
   ``I've got horses in my blood,'' Lipschitz said when asked why
he started a rodeo and riding school near Jerusalem, whose stony
slopes are more associated with biblical shepherds than cowboys of
the Old West.
   He and Solomon are unlikely cowpokes. Lipschitz is from South
Africa, his partner from Rosh Pina in northern Israel. Both fell in
love with rodeos from seeing them in the United States.
   Lipschitz, 48, said he has always loved horses _ his father
raised thoroughbreds _ but it was in Texas and Arizona that he
``got bitten by the rodeo bug'' about seven years ago.
   When he decided to open a riding school in Israel in 1987, he
went to Scotland to buy purebred Arabians originally from lands to
the east that Israel has been at war with since its founding in
1948. He calls his horse Shades of Silver.
   Solomon, 33, spent two years in Oklahoma and California learning
rodeo tricks from Reg Camarillo, brother of world champion cowboy
Leo Camarillo, before he returned to his native northern Israel to
start a horse ranch.
   ``He was a good teacher, I was a good student,'' the bearded
Solomon said after he had put on a show roping dogies.
   There have been other rodeos in northern Israel, where there are
real, working cowboys, but Solomon said none had ever been
organized around Jerusalem.
   He said he hoped soon to have a full American-style rodeo but
that Neve Ilan, nestled in the hills above the Arab village of Abu
Gosh 10 miles west of Jerusalem, did not yet have the facilities
for bucking broncos and bull riding.
   ``You need a higher fence,'' he said.
   Even without the more dangerous rodeo rides, the crowd seemed
happy. Many bought straw cowboy-style hats made in Hong Kong, for
$5 apiece, and tapped their feet to a trio of fiddle, guitar and
banjo.
   ``I'm from out West, the West Bronx,'' fiddler Bruce Brill
replied when asked where he learned to play. His guitar-playing
friend, Dave Mencher, is from another New York City borough,
Brooklyn, and banjo player Sid Singer is from Liverpool, England.
   Steve Berger, who shoes the horses for Lipschitz's riding school
and comes from Pottstown, Pa., said he was not surprised at the
crowd's enthusiasm or size.
   ``Horses are really popular in Israel,'' he said. ``There are
thousands of them. Every week there are jumping shows. There are
races with all breeds, even though they're not regulated yet.''
   Around him stood men and women in chaps, fringed leather vests
and broad-brimmed, sweat-stained hats. But there were reminders
that this was Israel 1989, not Texas 100 years ago.
   One of the door prizes for the rodeo was special glass plating
for the winner's car to protect against stone throwers who've been
attacking Israelis in the West Bank and Gaza Strip during the
22-month Palestinian uprising.
   Some of the pistols tucked into belts were quite real and up to
date, worn by Jewish settlers who live in the territories that
Israel captured in the 1967 Middle East war and still occupies.
   ``We should never need the guns,'' said Natie Charles,
originally from Livingston, N.J., whose pistol rested in his belt
next to the fringe of his Jewish prayer shawl. ``But it's better to
have them, just like life insurance.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
