<FIRST>r i PM-EastGermanRock     10-17 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-East German Rock,0484</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rock Concert in East Berlin Shows Fervor of Growing Opposition</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chanting in English ``We are here to stay,'' more
than 4,000 young people jammed into an East Berlin church for a
rock concert by musicians from across the land whose works bitingly
lampooned Communist leaders.
   While East Germany's opposition leaders have long flocked to the
relative safety of Lutheran churches, the concert symbolized the
new fervor of the growing movement to open up a tightly-controlled
society.
   Young and inspired by the zeal that carried along the 1960s
protest movements in the United States and Europe, the supporters
of East Germany's opposition movement are vowing to push for
changes from within.
   They do not want to join the refugee exodus.
   Rock bands and folk singers from across East Germany put on
Sunday's benefit at the Church of the Redeemer in East Berlin to
raise money for protesters who face trial after being arrested at
recent huge street demonstrations.
   Balladeers ridiculed the Communist government's sudden professed
willingness for dialogue, and the crowd sang along in English as a
band played John Lennon's ``Give Peace a Chance.''
   A folk singer from Leipzig parodied the rapid transformation
last week of the Communist Party's orthodox ideology chief, Kurt
Hager, from hard-liner to advocate of dialogue.
   ``Now Kurt Hager has invented dialogue,'' went one refrain,
followed by the sarcastic ``Reforms, we can start those tomorrow.''
   Opposition groups believe the hard-line Communist government is
attempting to sidetrack growing public calls for reforms by
promising a limited dialogue with opposition groups it has long
suppressed.
   The protests and the exodus of tens of thousands of East Germans
to the West in recent months have forced the government to be more
conciliatory to growing demands for change.
   But Communist leader Erich Honecker has rejected any talks with
opposition groups.
   Speakers at Sunday's benefit also talked of the brutal treatment
some protesters received after their arrest during demonstrations
in East Berlin.
   ``A man was forced to stand for 16 hours at a police station
before he collapsed,'' said one of the speakers. ``Two policemen
beat him until he pulled himself up.''
   During the more than three-hour event, representatives of
several opposition and reform-minded artistic groups announced new
protest plans and initiatives.
   Members of the Working Theater Federation vowed to hold a march
demanding press freedoms on Nov. 4, for example.
   Others called for reforms in the nation's closely supervised
education system and an independent investigation into the behavior
of state security forces during protests in cities across the
nation.
   Police have used force to end many demonstrations.
   Students groups declared their intention to form independent
federations and university officials demanded authorities not
aexpel students for taking part in the demonstrations.
</TEXT>
