<FIRST>r a PM-CentenarianCitizen     10-17 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Centenarian Citizen,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Immigrant Gets U.S. Citizenship at Age 102</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ROGERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 102-year-old Lithuanian immigrant waited 39
years to become a U.S. citizen, but he isn't going to waste any
time going about his civic duty.
   ``The first thing I'm going to do is support the Republican
party,'' Kazimieras Bandzevicius said after being sworn in as a
citizen Monday.
   The former banker and car dealer in Lithuania got special
attention when he swore the oath in a nearly inaudible voice before
U.S. District Judge Terry Hatter.
   ``Welcome sir,'' Hatter said. ``It's never too late to become a
citizen.''
   Bandzevicius, a balding man with close-cropped gray hair who
squints through thick glasses and walks slowly with a cane, beamed
when he was called to pick up his citizenship certificate. Then, he
kissed the hand of his attorney, Kaye Evans.
   ``I feel really good today because I'm planning to live for a
long time,'' he said later in Russian translated by his
granddaughter, Olga Goodman, 46. ``The good Lord gave me good
health.''
   Becoming an American is the latest move in an eventful life.
   Born in rural Lithuania, he moved to Russian city of St.
Petersburg _ now Leningrad _ to get an education at age 9 or 10. He
eventually got university degrees in physics and mathematics, and
still has the honorary cross he received from the czar for his
scholastic achievements.
   He fled back to Lithuania during the Bolshevik Revolution of
1917 and then left his homeland for Germany in 1940. He came to the
United States 10 years later, moving first to Chicago and then to
Los Angeles in 1953.
   In this country, he worked as a machinist until failing eyesight
forced him to retire.
   Along the way he married Anna, the widow of a friend who was
executed during the revolution, and adopted her son and two
daughters. She died eight years ago.
   Bandzevicius said he draws hope from Soviet leader Mikhail
Gorbachev's reforms, but the restructuring of Soviet society causes
him concern.
   ``He's afraid the country won't have the strength to change,''
Mrs. Goodman translated. If Gorbachev succeeds, Bandzevicius added,
he hopes it will someday mean independence for Lithuania.
</TEXT>
