<FIRST>u a AM-NASA-DivingDeath     10-17 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NASA-Diving Death,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Dies on NASA Ship After Diving Accident</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Anneta in 2nd graf is cq.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A scuba diver left unconscious after
an underwater accident died Monday night in a decompression chamber
aboard NASA's rocket booster recovery vessel, a Coast Guard
spokeswoman said.
   Keith Seigal, 34, of Cocoa Beach was pronounced dead at 10 p.m.,
said Petty Officer Anneta Culver of the Coast Guard's Mayport
station. He had been taken aboard the ship nearly five hours
earlier.
   The incident was not related to any protests of Tuesday's
scheduled space shuttle launch, said Culver, who noted that it was
Seigal's third diving accident. The second occurred just three
months ago.
   ``The first one there was nerve damage,'' she said. ``The second
accident, he refused medical treatment.''
   The Coast Guard picked up a frantic distress call from Seigal's
fiancee shortly after 4 p.m. Monday. Their 23-foot pleasure boat,
``C U Later Bye,' was anchored 20 miles southeast of Cape Canaveral.
   Seigal, who was diving alone at a depth of 140 feet, 4 feet from
the ocean floor, had lost consciousness after coming up from a
second dive, and was bleeding from the mouth and nose, Culver said.
   NASA's vessel, Freedom Star, was about three miles away, waiting
to recover the solid rocket booster after the launch of shuttle
Atlantis. Crew members offered the use of its decompression chamber
and the Coast Guard quickly transported Seigal to the ship in a
helicopter.
</TEXT>
