<FIRST>r a PM-RecruitSuicide     10-17 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Recruit Suicide,0557</SECOND>
<HEAD>End of a Dream: Failed Police Recruit a Suicide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All Danny Morales ever wanted was to become a
police officer _ so much so that he never considered college or
another career in his 21 years.
   When the dream began to slip away, he took the revolver he had
hoped to use as an officer and killed himself Friday in front of
his instructor on the Police Training Academy shooting range.
   ``Ever since first grade he has wanted to be a police officer,''
said Linda Zwier, 21, his girlfriend. ``It was the only dream that
he had ever had and he never talked about college, he never talked
about doing anything else.''
   ``He was very focused and dedicated, much more than most
people,'' said an uncle, Mark Morales of Louisville, Ky. ``I admire
the fact that he knew what he wanted to do with his life. There are
people who spend all of their lives searching for that.''
   His father and four uncles among them won six city high school
wrestling championships and three state championships. When
Morales' turn came, he didn't disappoint, winning two city
conference championships.
   After graduating from Milwaukee Tech High School, Morales got a
job as a police aide. He studied police science at Milwaukee Area
Technical College, biding his time until he turned 21, old enough
to apply to the department.
   He was accepted to the recruit class that started training Aug.
20. But a month later, his grasp on his future started to slip.
   He failed a firing range test and then failed the retest and
resigned from the academy Sept. 29.
   Then, he found out he was nearsighted, got glasses and appealed
his resignation. Trainers gave him another chance to take the test.
   On Friday, after a week of remedial training and full of renewed
hope, he returned to the range to retake the test.
   ``Danny felt real good and felt confident,'' said Geary Morales
of St. Francis, Minn., another uncle.
   But it quickly became clear the glasses hadn't helped.
   Morales needed a score of 210 of 300 in three rounds of shooting.
   He scored a poor 62 in the first round, and 66 in the second. He
needed an 82 in the third round, and it was clear he couldn't get
it.
   With one shot left, Morales turned his gun on himself, according
to the Milwaukee County medical examiner's report.
   Family and friends preparing for Morales' burial today said
suicide was completely out of character.
   ``I think the environment he was in, alone in that firing range,
didn't give him an opportunity to talk to someone for a few
minutes, and the fear was overwhelming,'' said Geary Morales,
adding he wasn't criticizing the police department.
   Police Lt. Peter Pochowski, who was Morales' supervisor when he
worked as an police aide, said: ``I believe it was a split-second
decision. It was not part of his life plan that day. In that one
second he saw his whole world collapse and he couldn't face what
had happened. ...''
   ``I just assumed he would do well in whatever he did,''
Pochowski said. ``He was a blue chipper. He was going to be one
hell of a cop.''
</TEXT>
