<FIRST>r w PM-Iran-Contra     10-17 0535</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-Contra,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Justice Department Accused of Delaying Fernandez Iran-Contra Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh is coming
under criticism from the Iran-Contra prosecutor for delaying the
criminal trial of a former CIA station chief.
   Independent counsel Lawrence Walsh said Monday that Thornburgh,
for ``no legitimate reason,'' is using court appeals to sidetrack
the prosecution of Joseph Fernandez.
   Fernandez was scheduled to go on trial in July, but the Justice
Department went to the appeals court after U.S. District Court
Judge Claude Hilton in Alexandria, Va., said Fernandez was entitled
to disclose certain government secrets.
   Last week, without notifying Walsh at the time, the Justice
Department asked the appeals court for another month to consider
whether to seek a rehearing. The motion was granted on Friday.
   Fernandez, who assisted Oliver North's Contra resupply network,
is accused of obstructing the Tower Commission and the CIA
inspector general's offices and making false statements.
   Thornburgh has ``repeatedly thwarted'' the prosecution ``by
last-minute, unannounced procedural maneuvers designed only to tie
this case in a knot of endless litigation,'' Walsh said.
   Walsh said Thornburgh ``has asserted no legitimate reason for
delay'' and that ``there is every reason to proceed promptly.''
   Asked about Walsh's arguments, Justice Department spokesman
Daniel Eramian said, ``We won't respond unless the court asks us
to.''
   After the appeals court ruled against the Justice Department,
said Walsh, Assistant Attorney General Edward Dennis on Oct. 2
reported the department probably would not seek further court
review. Dennis, head of the department's criminal division, said
Thornburgh probably would file an affidavit prohibiting disclosure
of the information at the Fernandez trial, said Walsh's court
papers.
   Such a step could result in the charges against Fernandez being
dismissed.
   In addition, said Walsh, a Justice Department criminal division
attorney indicated last Wednesday the division had sent a memo to
the solicitor general recommending against seeking further appeals
court review. The criminal division attorney said it was ``a
virtual certainty'' the solicitor general would concur with the
recommendation, Walsh's court papers said.
   Walsh complained the attorney general provided no notice he had
decided to file the request for an extension. The Justice
Department and Walsh's office have worked closely on secrecy issues
for three years. In this instance, the Justice Department mailed
Walsh a copy of his request, depriving the independent counsel of
an opportunity to respond before the court acted, the court papers
stated.
   The department's request for the extension was prepared last
Wednesday, the day Justice Department spokesman David Runkel
assured reporters in a memo that ``there are no new developments in
the Fernandez case.''
   Asked on Friday about the discrepancy between his statement and
the department's actions, Runkel said he was unaware that
government lawyers were preparing to file the request for the
extension.
   Walsh said the information Thornburgh seeks to protect ``is
widely known to the public,'' such as the existence of CIA stations
in Latin America.
   The appeals court said in a decision Sept. 29 that Thornburgh's
only recourse in protecting the information is to file an affidavit
which would prohibit its use at Fernandez's trial. Such a step
could lead to dropping the criminal charges against the ex-CIA
officer.
</TEXT>
