<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-89 0211EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Markets-Gameplan     10-17 0652</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Markets-Gameplan,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Game Plan on Stock Markets Included Distancing From White House</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Markets-Fed, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration's game plan for trying
to keep last Friday's stock market dip from becoming an avalanche
included distancing the issue from the White House, officials say.
   ``It was not a crisis in any sense of White House involvement,''
said White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater after the stock market
rebounded from Friday's 190-point tumble with a 88.3 point gain on
Monday.
   ``We didn't want to say anything that would cause anxiety. The
president said he wasn't worried. Things have worked out,''
Fitzwater continued.
   Still, despite the outward calm evidenced by Bush and his
lieutenants on Monday, there were intensive and frequent
behind-the-scenes consultations beginning Friday among the White
House and other U.S. agencies, Wall Street officials and foreign
allies, sources said.
   With Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady taking the lead for the
administration, a strategy of containment evolved over the weekend
_ an effort to keep the situation from getting any worse and to
profit from missteps made by U.S. officials during the October 1987
market crash.
   Bush, at the presidential retreat at Camp David, Md., was kept
posted on developments by phone calls through the weekend from
Brady and chief White House economist Michael Boskin, officials
said.
   The evolving strategy was accompanied by a clear early signal by
the Federal Reserve that it would flood the nation's banking system
with money if needed _ as it had done, somewhat belatedly, in the
1987 plunge.
   In fact, the Fed on Monday pumped some $2 billion into the
system, making it easier for banks to continue to provide credit to
hard-pressed brokerage houses and securities firms.
   And, sources said, the strategy also called for closer economic
coordination with the so-called G-7 group of economic allies _
Japan, Britain, France, West Germany, Canada and Italy in addition
to the United States _ than took place last time.
   In fact, comments by then-Treasury Secretary James A. Baker III,
now the secretary of state, publicly criticizing Germany for not
doing more to lower interest rates to stimulate its economy on Oct.
18, 1987, were cited by some analysts as one factor in the record
508-point drop the next day.
   This time around, the White House voiced reassuring comments on
the underlying strength of the economy, even when the stock market
appeared to be continuing to fall. Bush asserted ``I'm not
worried'' about an hour after markets opened Monday, at a time when
stock prices were posting an initial plunge.
   Brady chaired the presidential commission which studied the
October 1987 crash and recommended ways for dealing with future
market crashes. Some of his recommendations are now law, including
automatic triggers that suspend trading when price swings exceed a
specified level.
   The administration and some Wall Street analysts credited some
of those reforms with helping put a damper on trading volatility on
Monday.
   White House officials wanted to make sure it was clear Brady was
dealing with the issue, along with the Fed and the SEC, and that it
had not reached a level of crisis where the White House should get
involved.
   Brady himself drove this point home, making an unscheduled
appearance at a White House staff meeting to urge that an upbeat
face be put on the situation and to caution against any suggestion
of a crisis atmosphere.
   Later, asked if there was a master crisis management plan,
presidential spokesman Fitzwater said no, because there wasn't a
crisis. ``Mainly we rely on the Treasury and the Fed and the SEC.
... We have full confidence in their ability to deal with any
situation,'' he said.
   Also, there is a limit to what the government can do to
influence the stock market _ beyond rhetoric and pump-priming by
the Fed or, in extreme cases, an emergency declaration by the
president halting trading.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
