<FIRST>r w PM-FetalTissue     10-17 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fetal Tissue,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former NIH Director Wants Ban on Fetal Tissue Research Ended</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former director of the National Institutes
of Health says he is disappointed in the Bush administration's
reported decision to extend a ban on federal financing of medical
experiments using fetal tissue.
   James Wyngaarden, former director of NIH and now in the White
House Office of Science and Technology Policy, had recommended the
ban be lifted.
   ``There are medical opportunities that might be addressed by the
transplantation of fetal tissue,'' he said. ``And I thought one
could decide on the use of fetal tissue without involving the
abortion issue, since in this country that's a legal procedure.''
   Scientists say transplanting fetal tissue into adults may be
effective in treating diabetes and Parkinson's disease.
   But anti-abortion groups have warned the Bush administration
would find itself in the middle of a firestorm of protest if it did
not continue to the ban.
   ``The evidence is clear that if fetal-tissue transplantation
became successful therapy, it would increase abortions,'' said
James Bopp Jr., general counsel for the National Right to Life
Committee.
   ``I would be inconceivable that a pro-life administration would
have the government sponsor research which would lead to an
increase in abortion,'' he said.
   The New York Times reported Monday the administration would
extend the ban that was imposed in March 1988.
   James Mason, assistant secretary for health in the Department of
Health and Human Services, has recommended the ban be continued,
despite conclusions by two federal panels that such research holds
promise for treating diabetes and Parkinson's disease, the
newspaper said.
   HHS Secretary Louis Sullivan was expected to act within a week,
said the Times, which cited no sources for its information.
   Spokesmen for Sullivan and Mason would say only that the issue
was under review in the department.
   HHS imposed the ban 19 months ago while the department reviewed
the issue. In December, two NIH panels studied the question and
recommended the ban be lifted.
   Robert Windom, assistant secretary for health in the Reagan
administration, told the Times he had been prepared to approve
fetal tissue experiments in January, but was instructed by then-HHS
Secretary Otis Bowen to leave the decision to the Bush
administration.
   Bopp said the NIH advisory panel on fetal tissue research was
``stacked'' with people who favored such research. Bopp was one of
four members of that committee who dissented from the
recommendation that the ban be lifted.
   Wyngaarden, who chaired another NIH advisory committee which
appointed Bopp's panel, said Bopp's claims were untrue. ``It was
not a jury-rigged committee,'' he said, adding that some on the
panel were ``wrenched by the abortion issue.'' Wyngaarden's
committee received the fetal tissue advisory panel's report and
concurred, recommending to Windom the ban be lifted.
</TEXT>
