<FIRST>r w PM-FlagBurning     10-17 0552</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Flag Burning,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Clash Over Flag Amendment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate critics of a constitutional amendment
to ban burning the American flag are urging defeat on grounds it
would stifle freedom of speech, but sponsors call it the only
certain protection for the national symbol.
   ``It is the intention of the drafters of this legislation to go
after speech, certain kinds of speech,'' Sen. Joseph R. Biden Jr.,
D-Del., said Monday as the Senate began to debate the proposed
amendment.
   Biden said it would allow authorities to ignore ``a well kept
businessman in a three-piece, Brooks Brothers suit who burned the
flag'' while jailing ``a college dropout with long hair and torn
jeans who burned the flag.''
   Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., said dissent would not be stifled
by a limit on such protest and called for support ``as we seek to
protect our most cherished symbol of democracy from contemptuous
desecration.''
   The measure would authorize federal and state governments to
outlaw burning and other desecration of the flag.
   The Senate confined itself to debating the measure Tuesday and
aimed for a vote later this week. The House would vote on the
amendment after that.
   Even if approved by Congress, it would have to be passed by the
legislatures of 38 states before becoming part of the Constitution.
   Lawmakers sent to President Bush on Thursday a rival measure
that would ban burning or other desecration by simple statute.
   Sponsors of the amendment, however, say the statutory ban could
be ruled unconstitutional on the same grounds as the Texas law
thrown out by the Supreme Court this summer in overturning the
conviction of flag burner Gregory Lee Johnson.
   ``I remain convinced that the bill that passed the Congress last
week will not survive constitutional scrutiny in light of the
Johnson decision,'' said Thurmond. He said there were many ways to
express dissent other than burning flags and ``those avenues should
and will go unimpeded.''
   The bill already sent to Bush was designed to avoid the
constitutional question by simply barring flag desecration
regardless of whether it involved political protest.
   Thse who are opposing the amendment say it would amount to
tampering with the Constitution for political reasons.
   ``What are we going to remember more, the Constitution or a
momentary political poll?'' Sen. Patrick J. Leahy, D-Vt., asked the
Senate.
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., said lawmakers were being asked
to amend the Bill of Rights ``partly because of concern over the
obnoxious act of a protester who burned the flag but largely
because of an unseemly effort to gain partisan political advantage
from the incident.''
   He said the Texas protester ``committed a despicable act.'' But
he noted President Bush initially seemed to accept the Supreme
Court's decision in the case and only launched a campaign for an
amendment after having lunch with GOP national Chairman Lee Atwater.
   ``The Atwater-Bush amendment will do more violence to the
Constitution than Gregory Lee Johnson could possibly have hoped to
accomplish with his puny act of protest,'' Kennedy said.
   Sen. Alan J. Dixon, D-Ill., said the Supreme Court ruling was
``a wrongheaded decision'' and said the amendment is needed as
``the surest protection against further acts of desecration.''
   ``It's the only effective way to protect our cherished flag,''
Dixon said.
</TEXT>
