<FIRST>r w PM-WanderingPlane     10-17 0546</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wandering Plane,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drama But Little Evidence in Tape of Mystery Flight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tape of radio transmissions involving pilot
Thomas Root's 800-mile autopilot flight and crash into the Atlantic
Ocean provides some drama but little evidence about the mystery
flight.
   Root made only one reference to trouble with the July 13 flight,
moments before he apparently blacked out for unknown reasons,
according to a tape and transcript released Monday by the Federal
Aviation Administration.
   The tape also includes an exchange between an air traffic
controller and a military pilot who said he saw Root move in the
cockpit after passing out but then apparently lapse back into
unconsciousness.
   Root's plane fell into the ocean near the Bahamas when it ran
out of gas after a six-hour journey. Root was flying from
Washington, D.C., to Rocky Mount, N.C., when he radioed the first
and only indication of trouble:
   ``Ah, yes, sir, I'm having a little problem up here, having a
little trouble breathing. How, how far am I to Rocky Mount now?''
Root asked at about 45 minutes into the flight.
   The controller, who was not identifed by the FAA, told the
36-year-old pilot he was about 17 minutes away from his destination.
   Root, his voice faltering, gave one last response: ``Ah, ah,
one, three.''
   The tape did little to clear up mysteries surrounding the July
13 crash of the Cessna aircraft piloted by Root, a Washington
communications attorney.
   About a half-hour after Root's last radio contact, a military
pilot sent up to trail the plane reported he could see the pilot
move.
   Root has said he could not explain photographs that appear to
show him turning his head and changes in the plane's sun visor
while he said he was unconscious.
   ``Sir, we're tracking parallel to `one-three yankee' and, ah,
apparently the individual is unconscious. His head is back, his
mike boom is away from his face,'' the military pilot said.
   A few minutes later, he said, however, ``We just saw the
individual move his head forward.''
   The controller asked whether that might have been caused by the
aircraft bouncing around in turbulence.
   ``No, sir, we were relatively stable and it appeared he had
rocked his head forward and then back,'' the military pilot said.
   The tape, which covered communications from air traffic
controllers and other planes during most of the first two hours of
Root's flight, had no further reference to movements by Root. The
Alexandria, Va. resident, has said the first thing he remembers
after blacking out was finding himself in the water.
   FAA spokesman Fred Farrar said military communications after
Root's plane left FAA-controlled airways were not available.
   Root also was treated for a gunshot wound after he was rescued
from the water. He has said the impact of the plane hitting the
water must have discharged a pistol in the cockpit. The gun's maker
said that couldn't have happened, but authorities have offered no
other explanation for the wound.
   No sound of a gunshot is heard on the tape and there is no
reference to a gunshot in the communications.
   Medical tests found no evidence that Root used drugs, suffered
from carbon monoxide poisoning or had a heart problem during the
flight.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
