<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     10-17 0562</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0597</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A usually sockless state lawmaker donned a
pair of aquamarine argyles to try to rescue a piece of legislation
his colleagues have held hostage.
   Last week, the Michigan House approved 11 out of the 12 bills in
a package sponsored by Rep. David Honigman, but decided to hold off
on the last one until the Republican wears socks to House sessions
for a full week.
   Honigman, a lawyer, says he never wears socks _ except during
athletic activities _ because his feet get too hot.
   But to try to win passage of a bill that would let growing
neighborhoods buy and preserve open spaces, Honigman agreed to give
up his trademark sockless look last week. However, he delayed
keeping his promise until Monday because he had to buy some socks
first.
   ``I bought quite a few pairs of the most unusual variety,'' he
said, showing off his new argyles.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ROGERS, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rogers Corp. stopped paying for the street
lights, so some residents of this northeast Connecticut village
want to stop using the company's name for their community.
   ``Many of the older residents feel betrayed,'' said Roger
Fontaine, an 18-year village resident and spokesman for a group
campaigning to go back to the original name, Williamsville.
   That name was changed to Goodyear in the early 1900s after the
Goodyear Tire &amp; Ruber Co. moved into the area. In 1954, Goodyear
moved out, Rogers Corp., which makes synthetic resins, moved in,
and the company's president, Saul Silverstein, asked residents to
change the village's name to Rogers.
   In exchange, Silverstein said he would pay for the village's 22
street lights.
   But last summer, Rogers Corp. officials decided $2,600 a year
was too much to pay for street lights, and the village went dark.
   ``We don't think it's an appropriate way to spend the
shareholders' money,'' said company spokesman William
Schoppenhorst. ``We give to a lot of chrities.''
   Ronald Robinson, head of corporate facilities for Rogers, admits
he wouldn't mind a name change.
   ``Personally, I like the name Williamsville,'' he said.
``Emotionally and aesthetically, Williamsville is a nice name.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>AGAWAM, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This western Massachusetts suburb of 26,000
has been calling itself a city for several months, but some
residents say they'd feel more at home in a town.
   ``I moved here 45 years ago from a city. Keep it a town,'' said
one respondent to a poll in the Union-News of the city of
Springfield.
   ``Town sounds friendlier and more successful. City means failure
and financial difficulties,'' a second respondent said.
   ``We aren't a city. You don't see people sleeping in the
streets,'' said a third.
   Agawam residents voted last year to dump the town manager form
of government in favor of a mayor and city council. But the
Union-News took an unscientific mail-in poll and reported Monday
that supporters of reverting to a town outnumbered opponents 233-38.
   But city partisans also held strong opinions:
   ``City denotes adults. Town sounds like kids playing in
school,'' one told the newspaper.
   The Rev. Benjamin T. Lockhart, a retired minister and city
councilor, has proposed a non-binding referendum on the matter.
   ``It's not exactly a burning issue,'' Lockhart said. ``But a lot
of the older folks are just uncomfortable with calling it a city.
When they see city, they think of Springfield.''
</TEXT>
