<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru a0799 10-17 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0799,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tokyo Market Regains Most Of Its Monday Losses</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates thruout with closing Nikkei, dollar. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The key index on the Tokyo Stock Exchange bounced
back by more than 500 points Tuesday, regaining most of what it had
lost during the previous day's trading.
   Other Asian stock markets also rebounded Tuesday, encouraged by
news of a partial recovery in New York and the revival in Tokyo.
   On the Tokyo foreign exchange market, the dollar closed at
142.35 yen, up 1.50 yen from Monday's close. It had opened at
141.97 yen.
   Financial centers in the Far East had posted significant
declines Monday, reacting to a plunge on Wall Street Friday that
sent the Dow Jones industrial average down by over 190 points.
   On Tuesday, Tokyo's principal market barometer, the Nikkei Stock
Average, jumped by 527.39 points, or 1.53 percent, to 34,996.08. It
had fallen 647.33 points Monday, at 1.8 percent its largest drop
this year.
   A dealer at Nomura Securities, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said factors affecting the plunge in New York Friday
were totally different from those during the ``Black Monday'' crash
of October 1987, when the Tokyo exchange's main market barometer
fell 15 percent in one day.
   He said there was no reason to fear Friday's plunge would send
stock markets crashing worldwide.
   ``The crash in New York (Friday) was not linked to uneasiness
about funds, as was the crash of Black Monday,'' the dealer said.
   During the crash two years ago, he said, there was a 2 percent
spread between interest on Treasury bills and another key
short-term interest rate which suggested there might be a flight
away from purchasing government bonds.
   But the spread is only 1 percent now, he said.
   The dealer also said good news precipitated Tuesday's stock
market rebound, including the recovery on Wall Street, and
statements by Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan that the Fed
would engage in necessary intervention to prevent the crash from
expanding.
   Japanese Finance Minister Ryutaro repeated remarks he made
Monday that he wasn't seriously concerned about the impact of
Friday's plunge in New York on Japanese markets.
   ``I don't think markets moved that sharply (this time),'' he
said, speaking at a press conference after a regular Cabinet
meeting.
   Hashimoto also praised coordination between financial
authorities of the Group of Seven nations during the stock crisis.
   Sumio Fukushima, a dealer with Sumitomo Bank, said Tokyo's
foreign exchange market was quiet Tuesday morning.
   ``The only news is that the stock market has rebounded. There
has been nothing else this morning,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
