<HEAD>EDS: SUBS lede in 1st item to delete `that'; SUBS lede in 2nd item
delete extraneous graf mark to clarify</HEAD>
<HEAD>State Department To Hire Blind Man as Diplomat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A blind man who has been trying to join the
State Department for more than a decade will be granted his wish
under the reversal of a policy that dates back to the 18th century.
   Avraham Rabby, of New York City, said in a telephone interview
Monday he learned last Friday that the State Department had
notified Congress of its intention to hire qualified blind people
for the career diplomatic service.
   State Department officials said the decision was based primarily
on technological advances, including optical scanners capable of
``speaking'' written words through a conversion process.
   These advances enable the blind to improve efficiency and limit
the need for readers and other types of outside assistance.
   Another factor contributing to the policy reversal was a federal
law that states that the government cannot disqualify prospective
employees persons because of blindness or other handicaps. It must
also provide ``reasonable accommodations'' to help them overcome
their handicaps.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Commission Issues Report on Problems in Mississippi River States</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressional commission says the federal
government must offer aid to end the poverty, unemployment and
infant mortality which add up to misery in the lower Mississippi
River region.
   The Lower Mississippi River Delta Development Commission on
Monday acknowledged the economic ills that burden seven states
bordering the river but said those woes should not prevent the
region from ``participating as a full partner in America's future.''
   ``In short, the region is not only worth saving, but because of
its location, resources and climate, could make a major
contribution to the rest of the nation and the world,'' the
commission said.
   The commission was created by Congress in 1988 to come up with a
10-year plan to aid 214 counties near the Mississippi. It did not
offer specific recommendations Monday; those are due in May.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bennett Criticized for Lack of Aid to City's Prisons</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six months after a well-publicized pledge to
help clean up a burgeoning drug problem in the Disrict of Columbia,
national drug policy director William J. Bennett has failed at his
most important goal, relieving chronic prison overcrowding in the
city, critics say.
   Bennett called the drug problem in the nation's capital ``out of
control,'' in April and pledged an injection of federal aid to
combat the rising tide of drug-related violence.
   But Bennett's efforts have failed to make any discernible dent
in the local drug trade, federal and city officials agree. And
Bennett's campaign has been hampered by bureaucratic roadblocks and
squabbling, leaving his office unable to deliver on crucial
elements of his plan.
   The prisons, which are more crowded than ever, are evidence of
Bennet's biggest failure, critics say.
   ``My problems are worse today than they were six months ago,''
Walter B. Ridley, the District's acting corrections director, told
The Washington Post.
   Ridley's office had been targeted for the most help under
Bennett's plan. ``I can't think of any significant assistance that
we've gotten,'' he said.
   At a news conference scheduled for Thursday, Bennett plans to
release the first of what he promised would be regular progress
reports on the D.C. initiative.
</TEXT>
