<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-89 0328EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Korea-StudentMurder     10-17 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea-Student Murder,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>Student Suspected of Being Police Spy Blugeoned to Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 20-year-old student suspected of
being a police spy was tortured and bludgeoned to death and six
militant students were being held in connection with his murder,
police said today.
   The body of Sol In-jong was found Sunday in the student council
office at Seoul's Yonsei University, laid on a folding bed and
wrapped in a brown blanket, police said.
   They said he had been tied to a chair, tortured and beaten to
death.
   A police spokesman, requesting anonymity in keeping with
official practice, said six students reported the killing and
turned themselves in Sunday after confessing to a Roman Catholic
priest.
   Two of the six students allegedly administered the beatings,
police said.
   Korean newspapers called the killing shocking and senseless and
blamed it on the ideological extremism of radical students.
   ``The murder is a terrible lynching which cannot be forgiven,''
said an editorial in today's Dong-a Ilbo newspaper.
   The six students told police that they discovered Sol carried a
fake university identification card after he gained entrance to
their radical student club _ and they suspected him of being a spy
for the national security police, a police spokesman said.
   The six seized Sol at the university library late Saturday and
took him to a club meeting room for interrogation, police said. The
victim's hands and legs were tied to a chair with nylon cord and he
was beaten repeatedly, police said.
   The radicals claimed Sol confessed he worked for the Agency for
National Security Planning and reported regularly on the activities
of radicals at the university, police said.
   Sol was identified as a second-year student at Tongyang
Engineering College in Seoul.
   There was no explanation as to why he carried Yonsei University
identification or joined the radical's club, but police said a full
investigation was under way and an autopsy would be performed.
   Radical students, a small but vocal minority on campuses, have
staged violent protests to demand the overthrow of the Seoul
government and withdrawal of 43,000 U.S. troops based in South
Korea under a mutual defense pact.
   The extremists have little public support because of their
violent tactics. Police and security agents have used undercover
agents in the past to help keep tabs on the radical students'
activity.
</TEXT>
