<FIRST>r a PM-Abortion-Illinois     10-17 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion-Illinois,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Settlement Talks in Key Abortion Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opponents in a lawsuit that many believe could be
used by the U.S. Supreme Court to restrict abortions agreed to
continue negotiations that could lead to a settlement and keep the
case from the high court.
   The talks were the first meetings between the parties since the
high court decided in July to consider the case, a lawsuit
challenging an Illinois law that regulates abortion clinics. The
plaintiff, who runs an abortion clinic, has prevailed at the trial
and appeals court levels.
   Abortion-rights supporters contend the standards make the
clinics more expensive to operate, thus pushing the price of
abortion out of reach of poor women.
   In Springfield, meanwhile, a state legislative committee was
scheduled to vote today whether a proposal to restrict abortions
could be considered by the full Assembly.
   A recent draft of the bill would require doctors to determine
the viability of a fetus 20 weeks old or older before performing an
abortion, and require that a second physician be present during
abortions of viable fetuses. It also would bar public employees and
public facilities from direct involvement in abortions.
   State Attorney General Neil Hartigan and public health chief Dr.
Bernard Turnock on Monday met with American Civil Liberties Union
attorney Colleen Connell, who represents clinic operator Dr.
Richard Ragsdale.
   None would comment on the substance of the talks, but they said
they agreed to meet again next week.
   It is one of three cases scheduled for a Supreme Court hearing
this term that anti-abortion forces hope might be used to overturn
Roe vs. Wade, the 1973 landmark ruling legalizing abortion.
   Hartigan, who is defending Illinois in the Ragsdale case but who
personally favors abortion rights, said the settlement talks were
intended to keep the case from the Supreme Court, which is
scheduled to hear arguments in December.
   The attorney general, a Democrat who has announced his intention
to run for governor next year, said he opposes ``the idea of
Illinois being used as a football for ... a much broader decision.''
   ``I don't think there's any question ... that in fact this case
... might be used for something else,'' Hartigan told reporters
Monday.
</TEXT>
