<SECOND>PM-BRF--Horse Odor,0184</SECOND>
<HEAD>Smell No Obstacle to Proposed Equestrian Center</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A proposed downtown equestrian center has
passed Mayor Vincent Schoemehl's ``smell test.''
   Schoemehl is backing construction of an equestrian arena
intended to make St. Louis a national center for horse shows. The
10,000-seat, $50 million arena would have stables for 1,500 horses.
   To make sure odor would not be a problem, Schoemehl sent two
emissaries to Oklahoma City during the weekend to check out the
Morgan Horse Association show. J. Christopher Grace, executive
director of development, and Kiel Auditorium director Bruce Sommer
prowled the barns during the 900-horse event and came back with a
thumbs up for the project.
   Sommer's advice to the mayor was simple: ventilation and
constant cleaning.
   Sommer said he and Grace prowled the barns and the trailer area,
``the back of the house, so to speak.''
   ``The odor really didn't appear to be a problem at all,'' Sommer
said Monday. ``We were also looking at the overall requirements to
put on a show like that _ traffic, parking, freight and space.''
