<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     10-17 0530</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0549</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tokyo Market Rebounds In Second-Largest Rise Of The Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GROSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index rebounded
strongly today from the previous day's fall as investors reacted to
news that Wall Street had recovered partially from its own sharper
plunge.
   It was the index's second-largest rise this year.
   The recovery in Tokyo led to rallies on stock markets in other
Asian cities, some of which had plunged on Monday after the Dow
Jones industrial average fell by more than 190 points, or 6.9
percent, on Friday.
   Today, Tokyo's Nikkei Stock Average jumped by 527.39 points, or
1.53 percent, to 34,996.08. It had fallen 647.33 points on Monday.
   Traders said today's volume was a moderate 650 million shares,
up from Monday's thin 520 million.
   Analysts said investors were encouraged by the recovery on Wall
Street and statements by Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan
that the U.S. central bank would intervene to prevent a crash.
   Japanese Finance Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto repeated remarks he
made Monday that he wasn't seriously concerned about the impact of
Friday's plunge in New York on Japanese markets.
   ``I don't think markets moved that sharply (this time),'' he
told a news conference after a regular Cabinet meeting today.
   But Haruhito Ichimura, a trader with Nippon Kangyo Kakumaru
Securities, warned that it was too early to tell whether the New
York market had completely recovered from its fall.
   On the Tokyo foreign exchange market, the dollar closed at
142.25 yen, up 1.50 yen from Monday's close of 140.75 yen. It
opened at 141.97 yen and ranged between 141.80 and 142.35 yen. The
dollar had plunged 3.25 yen on Monday.
   Mitsuhiko Kinugasa, a dealer with Daiwa Bank, said there had
been rumors that Japanese banks again were backing away from a
revised plan for financing a buyout of United Airlines' parent
company. The refusal of banks, mostly Japanese, to commit their
funds to a similar plan last week led to Friday's plunge on Wall
Street.
   But Kinugasa said the rumors did not have a major impact on the
market.
   Elsewhere in Asia today, Hong Kong's Hang Seng Index, the
market's key indicator of blue chips, was by midday up 3.6 percent
from its close Monday, when it plunged 6.5 percent.
   Share prices on the Securities Exchange of Thailand also
rebounded strongly after a record 42-point fall on Monday.
   In Manila, share prices closed 0.87 percent higher in moderate
trading, and prices on the Taiwan stock exchange posted the largest
one-day gain ever on news of the rapid recoveries of the New York
and Tokyo markets.
   The 410.32-point gain in Taiwan _ 4.23 percent _ followed a drop
of 329.48 points on Monday.
   ``The recovery on Wall Street relieves worries over a worldwide
crash and draws bargain-hunters,'' said one Taiwan broker, who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Share prices in Australia and New Zealand rallied as well.
   The All-Ordinaries Index, Australia's main market indicator,
closed 61.6 points, or 3.8 per cent, higher today after a
140.4-point fall on Monday.
   In New Zealand, the Barclays Index gained 117.70 points, or 5.7
per cent, rebounding from an 8.5 percent fall on Monday.
</TEXT>
