<FIRST>r a PM-SipperCraze     10-17 0499</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sipper Craze,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>America Gets a Grip on Cup Gimmick</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA11 of Oct. 16</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LYNN ELBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN BERNARDINO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Slurp on a sipper with a slogan
and you've got your hands and lips firmly around a national fad.
   The sipper, a refillable plastic bottle with a drinking straw
fitted into its cap, originated as a handy, no-spill way for
parched athletes to refresh themselves.
   Now, the bottles are being toted by picnickers, commuters, and
others who are helping sipper manufacturers suck up tall profits.
   The Harmony Container Co. of San Bernardino expects to produce
20 million sippers his year, bearing the names and logos of
convenience stores, fast-food restaurants and businesses.
   The demand for sippers spread from the East Coast to the West,
and now ``they're pretty much in every nook and cranny,'' said Bret
Wilson, Harmony's sales manager. He declined to disclose any
financial details.
   Wilson says the promotional drinkware firm with offices in San
Bernardino and St. Louis noticed about 2{ years ago that a squeeze
bottle for sports looked a bit naked: an empty billboard just
waiting for an ad.
   ``The sports bottle has been around for years for athletic
activities. We took the bottle out of the sports market and started
putting catchy logos on it,'' Wilson said. ``We brought it out of
the hands of the sports market and put it in the hands of the
promotional market.''
   Although sports bottle producers generally have stayed out of
the promotional end of the market, Wilson said competitors have
sprung up in the East.
   ``People are even making them in their garage,'' he said. The
bottles have been especially hot items at convenience stores, which
give them catchy names such as ``Main Squeeze'' and often sell them
as part of a deal. At Arco's AM-PM Mini Markets, for instance, the
bottle is sold for 99 cents, with the 49-cent soft drink. Refills
also go for 49 cents
   Sippers also have proven to be popular items for sale at Knott's
Berry Farm in Buena Park, where they carry the amusement park's
logo and sell for $4 each.
   ``It has been quite the rage,'' said Knott's spokesman Robert
Deuel. ``Our purchasing manager told me that the constantly has to
keep an eye on his stock because they move that many.''
   For companies, it's an inexpensive way to advertise, Wilson
said. And convenience stores and fast-food outlets are always
looking for ways to increase fountain sales.
   Why the popularity among consumers?
   ``I think that a lot of people like the sports appeal of it even
if they're not an athlete,'' he said. The bottle also fits in with
a ``commuter society that's always on the move.''
   Sipper popularity hasn't ebbed at Knott's despite the passing of
summer, Deuel said. But Wilson expects sipper sales to go into
hibernation during the winter and then grow again next spring.
   ``We'll see another big year, but beyond that it's hard to
tell,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891017-0053 </DOCNO>
