<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-Gorbachev     10-17 0643</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Gorbachev,0661</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Blasts Most Daring Practitioners of Glasnost, Journalists
Report</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev has rebuked the editor of
Ogonyok and other outspoken journalists, accusing them of acting
against the Communist Party or of seeking his political downfall,
Soviet reporters said today.
   The journalists said the Soviet president's leader's toughly
worded accusations during a top-level conference had sown great
worry in their ranks that the sort of frank criticism spawned by
the Kremlin's policy of glasnost, or greater openness, might again
be ruled off limits.
   If accounts of the meeting are accurate, it would mark an
about-face for Gorbachev, who has permitted extraordinary criticism
on a wide variety of topics while saying freedom of expression
nonetheless has some, so far ill-defined, limits.
   The incident comes as Soviet lawmakers are drafting a new law
spelling out the rights and responsibilities of the Soviet press.
The bill is scheduled to be submitted to Parliament by the end of
the month.
   On Friday, Gorbachev met at party headquarters in Moscow with
leaders from the country's state-run mass media, creative unions
and agencies charged with formulating ideology to discuss
``consolidation of all forces of society for the successful
realization of the tasks of perestroika,'' Tass said.
   The meeting was attended by voting and non-voting members of the
ruling Politburo and members of the party Secretariat, indicating
the party leadership considered it a major policy session. Tass,
the official news agency, said Gorbachev gave a speech, but
official media have not distributed the text.
   Soviet journalists, however, said they were told by their bosses
who attended that Gorbachev tore into some of the brightest stars
of Soviet journalism and popular thought in the glasnost era,
including Ogonyok weekly editor-in-chief Vitaly Korotich, historian
Yuri Afanasyev and reformist economists Gavriil Popov and Nikolai
Shmelev.
   The Soviet leader accused Afanasyev, Popov and Shmelev of
joining with maverick Communist legislator Boris N. Yeltsin to form
``a fascist clique striving for power,'' said the journalists, who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Gorbachev told the meeting that Afanasyev, the rector of Moscow
Historical Archives Institute and an outspoken member of the Soviet
Congress, should be thrown out of the Communist Party, the
reporters said.
   Korotich was reportedly charged by Gorbachev with violating the
party line by permitting the publication in his trailblazing weekly
of overly radical demands and criticism.
   The reporters said that according to Gorbachev, Korotich had
begged him for mercy and promised to scale back his widely read
weekly. But he only kept that promise for a single issue, Gorbachev
was reported to have told the gathering.
   Gorbachev also reportedly demanded that he been given all
letters critical of him that had been sent to the weekly Arguments
and Facts.
   The tabloid newspaper, using readers' mail, recently calculated
that human rights activist Andrei D. Sakharov was more popular than
Gorbachev or any other member of the Congress of People's Deputies.
   Gorbachev complained that he had always supported the weekly,
which is printed by the ``Znaniye'' national lecture society.
   The editor of Arguments and Facts, V.A. Starkov, was given an
additional dressing-down during a long meeting with chief party
ideologist Vadim A. Medvedev on Monday, the journalists reported.
   Gorbachev also reportedly called the editorial board of the
Moskovsky Komsomolets newspaper ``a nest of informal, anti-party
organizations.''
   The paper is published by the Komsomol Young Communist League in
the Soviet capital.
   It was not immediately possible to obtain comment this morning
from those Gorbachev was said to have rebuked. A colleague at the
historical institute said Afanasyev was on a business trip until
Oct. 27, as were several of the editors involved.
   However, the Communist Party daily Sovietskaya Rossiya asked
today that if Afanasyev believes that the official ideology of
Marxism-Leninism is outmoded, ``then isn't it more honest for him
to leave the party?''
</TEXT>
