<HEAD>Rain Dampens Central U.S.; Snows Falls in Colorado, Wyoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms representing the remnants of Hurricane
Jerry dampened the Midwest early today, and snow fell in Colorado
and Wyoming.
   The remains of the hurricane combined with a cold front crossing
the central United States to bring rain to the lower and middle
Mississippi Valley and the lower Ohio Valley. Light rain fell over
parts of West Virginia, Maryland and south-central Pennsylvania.
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered from the central Gulf
Coast into the middle Mississippi Valley and across southern
sections of the lower Ohio Valley Monday evening.
   Thunderstorms in Mississippi spawned a tornado southwest of
Yazoo City on Monday. More widely scattered showers and
thunderstorms developing along the cold front extended from central
Indiana across the lower Great Lakes region and extreme northern
Maine. Other showers and thunderstorms were widely scattered across
Florida and Georgia.
   Snow fell this morning in the higher elevations of Colorado and
Wyoming.
   Unseasonably warm weather prevailed from the eastern half of
Texas to the southern and middle Atlantic Coast region Monday. More
than a dozen cities reached the record high for the date, including
Atlantic City, N.J., 84, and Baltimore, 84.
   The hot spot in the nation Monday was Beeville, Texas, with a
high of 98 degrees.
   Other reports at 3 a.m. EDT:
