<FIRST>r a PM-People-Newman     10-17 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Newman,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newman Files Antitrust Suit Against HBO</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Paul Newman filed a $5.45 million suit
against Home Box Office Inc., claiming the cable television company
undersold his film, ``Fort Apache, The Bronx'' so it could rent out
other HBO features.
   Ronald Rosen, Newman's attorney, said the actor signed with
HBO's subsidiary, Time-Life Productions, to make the 1980 film
about a veteran policeman in New York City.
   The suit filed Monday in federal court alleges breach of
contract and antitrust violations. It seeks $5 million in punitive
damages and $450,000 in alleged lost fees to the actor. It also
seeks an injunction against further ``block-booking'' of ``Fort
Apache.''
   Newman was to receive 15 percent of domestic gross receipts and
12.5 percent of overseas earnings under the contract, Rosen said.
   In 1985, Time-Life Productions licensed ``Fort Apache'' and 192
other films to Procter &amp; Gamble Co. for $50 million, Rosen said.
   The rental fee charged P&amp;G for ``Fort Apache'' was $1 million,
he said, arguing HBO used the film to coerce P&amp;G into taking the
other films, a violation of antitrust laws. Newman maintained the
film's true value through licensing was $4 million.
   ``HBO compelled P&amp;G to artificially allocate a lower license fee
to the film than was economically justified, and artificially
allocated higher license fees to the other 192 motion pictures in
the group,'' Rosen said.
   A call to HBO's New York offices made after business hours
Monday went unanswered.
</TEXT>
