<FIRST>r i PM-Peru-Strike     10-17 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Peru-Strike,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hundreds of Police On Strike, 300 Detained</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONTE HAYES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of policemen went on a 24-hour strike
for higher pay in this violence-plagued capital, and at least one
man was reported killed in a shootout between strikers and a police
patrol.
   More than 300 policemen were detained by their colleagues on
Monday, according to police sources. They were being held at a
police academy south of Lima, the sources said on condition of
anonymity.
   Strikers clashed with officers leaving the downtown police
headquarters to patrol the city. They exchanged punches, fired
pistols into the air and lobbed tear gas grenades at one another,
according to reporters at the scene.
   In a separate clash, one man was reported killed and several
wounded when strikers and working policemen exchanged gunfire. It
was not immediately clear whether the dead man was policeman or a
bystander.
   Interior Ministry spokesman Fernando Yovera said just 5 percent
of Lima's policemen were on strike, but the sources said as many as
80 percent of lower-level officers were participating.
   The strike, which appeared limited to Lima, came as leftist
rebels stepped up a violent campaign against the government and
private citizens in an attempt to disrupt municipal elections set
for Nov. 12.
   On Monday, three masked men boarded a bus downtown, forced the
driver and passengers off at gunpoint, then burned the bus.
   Yovera said police officers sympathetic to the pro-Cuba Tupac
Amaru Revolutionary Movement were promoting the strike.
   By midday, several hundred on-duty police troopers, wearing ski
masks that covered their faces and armed with automatic rifles,
ringed police headquarters and patrolled the city. The ski masks
were to prevent against reprisals from rebels or striking
colleagues.
   According to some reports, 300 striking policemen occupied the
police compound. But Yovera said on-duty policemen were in control
of the facility.
   In a statement released to reporters, strikers said they were
demanding ``a fair salary'' to compensate for Peru's 3,000 percent
annual inflation and the dangers policemen face in Peru.
   They also want a 48-hour work week, instead of the current 56
hours, and overtime pay. Police earn base pay equivalent to about
$70 a month. The minimum wage in Peru is $40 a month.
   Hundreds of policemen have been killed by guerrillas of the
Mao-inspired Shining Path, a rebel movement that launched an armed
insurgency in 1980.
   The much smaller Tupac Amaru group took up arms in 1984, but in
general has not made policemen a target of attacks.
   In May 1987 policemen went on strike for four days, and the
government led by President Alan Garcia placed Lima under military
control to protect against guerrilla attacks.
</TEXT>
