<FIRST>r a PM-PowertoHeal     10-17 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Power to Heal,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snapshots of Mankind's Search for Health</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH CARTIERE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Photographers will fan out across the globe
next month to chronicle mankind's quest for health, gathering
images of sidewalk snakebite healers in Brazil, laser
acupuncturists in China and some of the oldest people alive.
   The seven-day effort, organized by the creator of the ``A Day in
The Life'' series of coffee-table books, will become ``Power to
Heal: Ancient Arts &amp; Modern Medicine.'' The $45 book is scheduled
for publication next fall by Prentice Hall.
   ``It is certainly going to remind some of us doctors why we got
into this business in the first place,'' Dr. Matthew Naythons, a
physician, photojournalist and co-publisher of the book, said
recently.
   Carrying an average of 160 rolls of film, the photographers _
including six Pulitzer Prize winners _ will shoot more than 400,000
pictures in 30 countries from Nov. 12 through Nov. 19. Only 350 of
the pictures will make it into the book.
   Assignments include a ``safe sex'' instructional tribal dance in
the Ivory Coast, witch doctors in Guatemala, Mother Teresa's
hospitals in Calcutta, acupuncture treatment for crack abusers in
New York, a portable hyperbaric chamber in Colorado, Florida fat
farms and the ``ultimate smoker'' _ who still has to be found.
   The book also will feature pictorial chronicles of 20 physicians
around the world making their rounds; the manufacture of plastic
eyes at the oldest eye factory in the United States; and the daily
activities of Bleachman, who combs the streets of San Francisco in
a superhero's costume to teach drug addicts how to sterilize
needles.
   In accompanying texts, centenarians will offer tips on longevity
and journalists will discuss subjects ranging from childbirth to
the future of medicine.
   ``The concept is that in the course of one week around the world
it seems as if you can almost retrace the footsteps of man's
attempts throughout history to heal this machine we all live in,''
said Rick Smolan of Sausalito, who originated the ``Day in the
Life'' series in 1981.
   ``We're trying to show the human side of healing, not just the
blood and guts stuff,'' said the former Time and National
Geographic photographer.
   Sponsors have paid some of the project's $3.5 million cost or
have provided airfare, accommodations, film and computers.
   Previous books in the series include ``A Day in the Life of the
Soviet Union,'' ``A Day in the Life of America,'' and volumes
focusing on Australia, Japan, Canada, Hawaii, Spain, California,
China and Christmas.
   The 10 books have sold 2 million copies, earning about $100
million, according to Smolan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
