<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-89 0556EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Hospital-Generics     10-17 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hospital-Generics,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hospital, Citing Uncertainties, Stops Use Of Many Generic Drugs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hospital has suspended use of more
than 150 generic drugs because of the quality scandal in the
industry, a move one pharmaceutical group called the first of its
kind in the nation.
   Officials of the Hospital of St. Raphael said Monday they would
replace 60 percent to 80 percent of the generics the hospital uses
with more expensive brand-name drugs as precaution.
   The Food and Drug Administration is reviewing the 30 top-selling
generic drugs because some makers are accused of faking test
results or bribing FDA inspectors to win approval to market
generics.
   ``The allegations were so serious we couldn't in good conscience
wait any longer,'' said Dr. Charles Riordan, St. Raphael's vice
president for medical services.
   The hospital will resume using the generic drugs _ which
generally cost 50 percent to 70 percent less than brand-name
counterparts _ once officials are sure they have been adequately
screened for quality, Riordan said.
   The move was criticized as rash by Jay Molishever, a spokesman
for the New York-based Generic Pharmaceutical Industry Association.
He said the suspension was the first of its kind reported to the
industry group.
   ``This is an astounding action on the part of this hospital,''
said Molishever.
   The hospital will continue using generics produced by the makers
of brand-name drugs, and the products of three generic drug
companies it has dealt with for many years, said James J. Cullen,
chief operating officer of the 491-bed teaching hospital.
   ``We are not making a statement against the use of generic drugs
en toto,'' he said.
   St. Raphael's will absorb the cost of the partial switch to
brand name drugs, estimated at $100,000 a year, Cullen said.
However, hospital officials expect to resume using at least some of
the banned generics within the year, he said.
   The hospital will continue to use generics from three makers _
Elkins-Sinn Inc., LyphoMed Inc., and Roxane Laboratories Inc. _
because there hasn't been any indication of irregularities,
officials said.
   St. Raphael's has stopped using 160 to 200 of the approximately
250 generic drugs it stocks, according to Robert Jacovino, the
hospital's pharmacy director.
</TEXT>
