<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Legislature     10-17 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Legislature,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Panel Rejects Government Proposal as Not Radical Enough</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet legislative panel, flexing its new
muscles in the revamped Supreme Soviet, rejected a government
proposal on decentralizing economic control as not radical enough,
newspapers reported today.
   The committee decided the government plan on taking away some
economic powers from Moscow and parceling them out to the country's
15 constituent republics ``does not reflect the radical changes in
the Soviet federation,'' said the daily Leninskoye Zamya, or
Lenin's Banner.
   ``Can we talk today about the widening of rights for the
republics? What we need is for each republic to be economically
independent,'' the deputy committee chairman, Valerian Advadze, was
quoted as telling the Supreme Soviet on Monday.
   The legislative commission charged with fostering the economic
development of the country's republics and regions gave the Council
of Ministers, the government organ that presented the proposal,
until Nov. 15 to revise it.
   The Supreme Soviet, which gained new powers under President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev's overhaul of the Communist Party-dominated
political system, has demonstrated growing confidence in its new
role.
   It voted down several candidates for ministerial posts proposed
by the government, and refused to follow Gorbachev's lead when he
called for a temporary ban on all strikes.
   Instead, it prohibited strikes in several key sectors.
   Today, the legislature took up a draft law on ownership that was
billed as a measure intended to end the state monopoly on property
in the Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
