<DOCNO> AP891017-0065 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-89 0640EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-China     10-17 0574</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China,0595</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspapers Carry Full Text Of Jiang Speech, Indicating Purge Imminent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A two-month-old speech by Communist Party chief
Jiang Zemin, published in full for the first time today, reveals
serious splits in the party despite its leaders efforts to appear
unified.
   Jiang acknowledged that many party members supported the crushed
pro-democracy movement and that some high officials still don't
back the party's new hard-line stance.
   He called for a purge of these people, whom he called
opportunists, and for an ideological struggle within the party to
``sweep out the dirt.''
   ``Grasp the opportunity to do serious investigation and cleanup
in order to protect party ranks,'' he urged. ``We must not pause,
or there will be trouble later.''
   Jiang delivered the speech in August to a meeting of party
organization officials, but it was not reported in the official
media until Monday, when the Xinhua News Agency carried brief
excerpts.
   The full text appeared today on the front pages of all national
newspapers.
   It is Jiang's toughest statement since party elders selected him
in June to replace ousted reformist Zhao Ziyang as party general
secretary. Zhao was accused of supporting the spring student-led
pro-democracy protests and ``splitting the party.''
   But Jiang's speech revealed that despite repeated party calls
for members to ``unify their thinking'' and unite around the party
core, serious disunity remains.
   ``In this struggle, even now there are some people who are
watching,'' Jiang said. ``Watching what? To see if there wil be
change. We cannot permit high-ranking officials to sit on the
fence. ... This is opportunism.''
   He said that all fence-sitters with top jobs will be required to
immediately make their stands clear and ``become very
revolutionary,'' or expect to be fired.
   Many moderate officials and Zhao allies remain in government and
party jobs, and the belated publication of Jiang's speech may
signal that the hard-liners have finally gathered enough strength
to begin purging them.
   ``So many party members took to the streets and marched, this is
a serious problem,'' Jiang said. ``I read a bulletin that said a
student party member wanted to march, but the school party
organization would not let him go. He said, `I am a student first,
then a party member, I must go.' ... Such a party member is not
qualified.
   ``Some party members left the party at its moment of danger,
imperiling the party. I think we need not urge such members to
stay. It won't hurt us if we lose a group of them.''
   The pro-democracy movement was crushed June 4 when troops broke
up demonstrations in central Beijing, killing hundreds of unarmed
civilians.
   Jiang said the role of the party in workplaces should be
strengthened.
   ``If the party grassroots organizations are dissolved, I think
the party general secretary will become a commander in name only,''
he warned.
   He also said exploiters _ an old word for wealthy private
businessmen _ should be barred from the party.
   He said that one millionaire was allowed to join in recent
years, but, ``Our party is the vanguard of the working class. If we
allow those who don't want to abandon the principle of exploitation
to join, what kind of party will we wind up with?''
   Apparently taking its cue from this speech, the Beijing city
party committee voted over the weekend to bar wealthy businessmen
from its ranks, and to purge all unfit members.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
