<DOCNO> AP891017-0066 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-89 0719EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BigBoy     10-17 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Big Boy,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>Original Bob's Big Boy Closes After 51 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GLENDALE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Connoisseurs of American
meat-and-potatoes cuisine mourned as the original Bob's Big Boy
restaurant closed after 51 years.
   The restaurant, which served up its last Big Boy Combo on
Monday, will be demolished and replaced by a mini-mall.
   ``I've eaten thousands of hamburgers here. I've come here all my
life,'' said Ben Trigg, 57, who remembered being at Bob's when it
opened in 1938. Then, he was a hungry 7-year-old whose mother
rewarded him with a hamburger and chocolate shake after clarinet
lessons.
   ``Hey, I grew up at this place,'' said Rodney Herrick, 41. ``I
used to come here in my battleship-gray Plymouth, order a Coke and
fries and wait for girls. Hard to believe it's closing down. This
place is a landmark.''
   Among the mourners was the restaurant's founder, Robert C. Wian,
75.
   ``I feel perfectly lousy about it,'' he said. ``There is a lot
of sentiment tied up in that place. But it's difficult to stand in
the way of progress.''
   Wian sold his car for $350 to buy the 10-seat diner that became
Bob's Big Boy. A few years later, Wian converted it into a drive-in
restaurant but kept the same meat-and-potatoes menu. A hamburger
and a milk shake ``so thick you can eat it with a spoon'' cost 60
cents.
   The formula was a success. Wian eventually created a national
restaurant chain that inspired numerous imitations.
   On Sunday and Monday, Big Boy customers paid their last respects
by slipping into the brown vinyl upholstered booths and ordering
their last Big Boy Combo _ a double cheeseburger, fries and a small
salad drenched in blue cheese or thousand island dressing.
   Outside stood the chain's mascot, a larger-than-life statue of a
chubby boy wearing suspenders. That character, Wian remembers,
originally was sketched on a napkin by a customer drawing a picture
of a boy Wian had hired to clean counters.
   Wian created the double-decker hamburger as a joke to satisfy a
regular customer's desire for something new, and the idea caught on.
   In 1967, Wian sold the chain to Marriott Corp. Citing lackluster
sales, Marriott decided six months ago to sell the original
restaurant property to a shopping center developer.
   The loss of the original Bob's is only the beginning of the end
of the sit-down burger and home-cooking empire.
   By 1991, all Bob's Big Boys will have been converted into
Allie's, named for Alice Marriott, the mother of Marriott chairman
and president J.W. Marriott Jr.
   Instead of double-deck burgers, fries and brownie hot fudge
sundaes, the menu will feature Mexican dishes, pasta salads and
trendy sourdough.
   As tribute to its past, the Glendale restaurant had a
mini-museum near the front counter with Bob's first spatula and
menu enshrined in a glass case. Wian has asked that the museum
artifacts be shipped to his Newport Beach home.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
