<FIRST>r a PM-Marshall-Afro-American 1stLd-Writethru a0516 10-17 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marshall-Afro-American, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0516,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thurgood Marshall Drops `Black' and `Negro' for `Afro-American'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to CLARIFY that Marshall has used `Negro'
and `black' in his opinions. PICKS UP 8th graf pvs, `Marshall used ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supreme Court Justice Thurgood Marshall has
decided to start using ``Afro-American'' in his written opinions.
   ``I spent most of my life trying to get `Negro' spelled with a
capital `N,''' Marshall told The Sun of Baltimore in a telephone
interview Monday. ``By the time I got that done, everyone was using
`black' with a small `b.'''
   Marshall, 81, the first black on the Supreme Court, said he had
never gotten into the habit of using the word ``black,'' preferring
``Negro'' long after others had abandoned it.
   The New York Times today reported he referred to ``Negroes'' in
speaking from the bench last week while questioning a lawyer in a
case concerning juries' racial composition.
   Marshall conceded that the word ``black'' had ``sometimes
slipped into'' opinions. But ``I don't think `black' connotes
anything,'' he told The Sun.
   ``Who is `black?' I've only seen two black people in my life,
and they were both in Africa.''
   Marshall has now decided to use ``Afro-American,'' which he
calls ``the original phrase.'' Some black activists, including the
Rev. Jesse Jackson, recently have advocated use of the term
``African American.''
   Marshall used ``Afro-American'' for the first time Monday, in a
six-page dissent in a death penalty case.
   Asked by the Times whether he expected the other Supreme Court
justices to follow his lead, Marshall said, ``I didn't ask anyone.
It's everone on his own. It's like what the old lady said when she
kissed the cow _ everyone to his own liking.''
</TEXT>
