<FIRST>r i PM-Refugees     10-17 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Refugees,0352</SECOND>
<HEAD>Refugees To Leave; West Germany Presses For Speedy Solution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first 120 of more than 1,500 East
German refugees here packed their bags today and prepared to fly
West, and West Germany urged Communist authorities to speed up
processing of the others.
   A Polish LOT Airlines charter plane was scheduled to leave
tonight for Duesseldorf, West Germany, a two-hour flight, carrying
the 120 refugees, a West German Foreign Ministry spokesman said on
condition of anonymity.
   The flight was scheduled in the evening to allow time for an
additional group of East Germans to be released from their
citizenship, diplomatic sources in Warsaw said. Forty-six East
Germans were released from citizenship Monday.
   The flood of East Germans to the West German Embassy continued,
with about 200 people joining their countrymen since Monday. That
brought the total at the compound or in nearby shelters to 1,500.
   A dispute was brewing between Bonn and East Berlin over the
issuing of exit permits, which the refugees need to leave Poland.
East Germany has said it will process 40 to 50 people a day.
   Hans Klein, the chief West German spokesman in Bonn, said his
government had asked East Germany to process larger groups of
refugees but there was no immediate response from East Berlin.
   ``It's obvious that the East Germans do not want to have another
spectacular passage'' of hundreds of refugees, Klein said. He
acknowledged that technical problems could limit the number of
requests processed daily.
   In Warsaw, East German ambassador Juergen van Zwoll said, ``We
are interested in speeding up this operation, but this does not
depend solely on us. Verification in the GDR (East Germany) is
necessary. We cannot allow some murderer to leave, for instance.''
   The exodus from Poland is part of a larger flood of more than
52,000 East Germans who have reached West Germany since Sept. 10,
when Hungary opened its border to Austria. Many also fled in large
groups through West German embassies in Warsaw and Prague,
Czechoslovakia.
</TEXT>
