<FIRST>r i PM-FootloosePope     10-17 0444</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Footloose Pope,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pontiff Marks 11th Anniversary Of Election Aboard Jetliner</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmits a0414 to CORRECT overline to 11th anniversary, sted
10th.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II marked the 11th anniversary of his
election as pontiff in fitting fashion _ winging home aboard a
jetliner over the Indian Ocean and with Lebanon and other
destinations on his mind.
   The most-traveled pontiff returned Monday from Mauritius, the
last leg of an Asian pilgrimage that was his 44th foreign tour
since his election to the papacy Oct. 16, 1978.
   Over 10 days, the pope visited South Korea, Indonesia and
Mauritius, spending 58 hours in the air alone.
   John Paul turns 70 in May and showed signs of tiring on the
Asian tour, especially under the wilting tropical sun. His
shoulders slumped at times as he clearly battled fatigue and jet
lag.
   But he was fresh and in good spirits when he briefly addressed
reporters aboard the Air Mauritius Boeing 767 taking him home and
explained why he is a such a frequent flier, having already covered
some 424,000 miles.
   The pope recalled being asked by a seminarian in Indonesia last
week why he travels so extensively.
   Responding, John Paul quoted Christ telling his apostles, ``Go,
teach all nations.''
   The pope said he was also carrying out the Second Vatican
Council's opening to the world, part of the great reform of the
Roman Catholic Church in the 1960s launched by Pope John XXIII.
   John Paul certainly doesn't go as a tourist, having passed up a
look at famed Budhist and Hindu temples in Java on his Indonesian
swing and of the Taj Mahal when he visited India in 1985.
   Foremost in John Paul's travel plans is Lebanon, although no
date has been fixed.
   ``He keeps thinking of a trip, if that could help,'' said
Vatican spokesman Joaquin Navarro. ``The consideration should be
that it will bring results.''
   John Paul has made a series of appeals to the Moslem and
Christian communities for a lasting peace in the country torn by 14
years of civil war.
   Polish-born John Paul began his globetrotting after just three
months in the papacy, flying to Mexico to address the bishops of
Latin America.
   In the works for 1990 are two trips to Africa, where the
Catholic Church is experiencing its fastest growth, and another
visit to Mexico.
   John Paul began his latest tour with a flight for the first time
over the Soviet Union, which he hopes was a prelude to an actual
visit.
   This could be determined by his talks with Soviet leader Mikhail
S. Gorbachev at the Vatican later this year.
</TEXT>
