<FIRST>r a PM-Judge-Homosexuals     10-17 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Judge-Homosexuals,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge's Anti-Gay Comments Defended as Off The Record</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note language in 9th graf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHIP BROWN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge who told a reporter he gave a lighter
sentence to a killer because the victims were homosexuals ``asking
for trouble'' thought the remarks were off the record, his lawyers
argued at a disciplinary hearing.
   State District Judge Jack Hampton confirmed, however, that after
making the remarks in his chambers he told the newspaper reporter,
``Just spell my name right because no one will remember what I've
said in 1990.''
   The confirmation was in a deposition presented at the hearing
Monday by Bill Hornung, an attorney for the State Commission on
Judicial Conduct.
   The commission has accused Hampton of damaging public confidence
in the integrity and impartiality of the judiciary. The panel could
dismiss the allegations, censure Hampton or urge his removal by a
seven-judge tribunal.
   ``The place the judge expresses his opinion should be from the
bench, not in an impromptu conversation with the press,'' Hornung
said.
   Cliff Hutchinson, an attorney for Hampton, said Dallas Times
Herald courthouse reporter Lori Montgomery had been in Hampton's
chambers more than 100 times and did not make clear she would write
a story about his Dec. 16 comments about the sentencing of murderer
Richard Bednarski, 18.
   ``Ms. Montgomery took advantage of the friendship she cultivated
with Judge Hampton to write a slanted article about the judge,''
Hutchinson said.
   ``I am not on trial here. My work is not on trial. What the
judge said is the issue,'' Ms. Montgomery said after the hearing.
``The judge knew I was conducting an interview on the record.''
   Ms. Montgomery quoted Hampton as saying he gave a 30-year-prison
term to Bednarski, and not a longer sentence, in part because his
two victims were ``queers.'' The judge said they were ``asking for
trouble,'' based on testimony from Bednarski that they were
soliciting sex.
   On the same day Hampton's comments were published in the Times
Herald, he told The Associated Press, ``The victims were
homosexuals. They were out in the homosexual area picking up
teen-age boys. Had they not been out there trying to spread AIDS
around, they'd still be alive today.''
   Hampton, a Republican, later apologized for a ``poor choice of
words'' but has claimed the criticism is politically motivated. He
was out of town Monday on a judicial retreat.
   About 35 gay-rights protesters stood outside the Criminal Courts
Building chanting slogans against Hampton during Monday's hearing.
   Retired Judge Robert R. Murray, who presided over the hearing,
will submit a statement of facts within two weeks to the 11-member
commission.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
