<FIRST>u w PM-TreasuryBills     10-17 0167</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Treasury Bills,160</SECOND>
<HEAD>Interest Rates Down for T-Bills</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on short-term Treasury
securities fell in Monday's auction.
   The Treasury Department sold $7.6 billion in three-month bills
at an average discount rate of 7.37 percent, down from 7.63 percent
last week. Another $7.6 billion was sold in six-month bills at an
average discount rate of 7.42 percent, down from 7.60 percent last
week.
   The rates were the lowest since three-month bills sold for 7.36
percent on Oct. 17, 1988, and six-month bills averaged 7.35 percent
on last July 31.
   The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors
_ 7.61 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling
for $9,813.70 and 7.82 percent for a six-month bill selling for
$9,624.90.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said Monday that the
average yield for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index
for making changes in adjustable rate mortgages, fell to 8.00
percent last week from 8.35 percent the previous week.
