<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-89 1056EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Elephants 1stLd-Writethru a0464 10-17 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Elephants, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0464,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conference Confirms Ban Despite Objections</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads thruout to UPDATE with delegates confirming ban, today's
developments. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MORT ROSENBLUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAUSANNE, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The world body controlling wildlife
trade formally banned ivory sales today despite bitter objections
from southern African countries, which insist their elephant herds
are not endangered.
   A 91-nation plenary session of the Convention on Trade in
Endangered Species, or CITES, approved without vote a compromise
proposal that places elephants on the endangered list but also
creates a panel of experts to consider exemptions.
   Objecting nations have three months to file reservations. That
means they would be allowed to sell ivory to other CITES countries
who file reservations or to more than 60 non-CITES members.
   Zimbabwe took the hardest stand against the ban, and said it
might withdraw completely from the convention.
   ``(Withdrawing) would hurt us a lot,'' said Rowan Martin,
director of research in Zimbabwe's Park and Wildlife Department.
``But it shows how much this means to us.''
   South African delegate Johannes Neethling said the vote punished
those countries that successfully managed their wildlife and
maintained stable elephant herds. He said he expected his
government to file a reservation.
   Earlier, Botswana, Malawi, and Mozambique said they also would
file reservations. They claim they need the proceeds from ivory
sales to maintain successful conservation.
   They were joined by Burundi, which has no elephants left but has
a stockpile of 86 tons of suspect ivory.
   Ivory from elephant tusks is highly valued for its use in the
signature stamps popular in many Asian nations and for jewelry,
piano keys and carvings.
   The plenary session followed a committee vote where the
compromise formula, proposed by Somalia, received the required
two-thirds majority.
   Under the new measure, countries may be granted exemptions from
the ban if they can prove to a special panel of experts that they
maintain stable elephant populations.
   Countries granted exemptions would be allowed to resume limited
ivory trade. But no exemptions are likely to be considered before
the next conference of CITES in 1991.
   The meeting, which ends Friday, also is considering about 300
other emdangered animals and plants. But the focus was on the
African elephant after a continent-wide census suggested the
elephant population had declined from 1.3 million to less than
650,000 in the past decade.
</TEXT>
