<HEAD>LaserPhoto TLV3</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Israeli military investigation urged that a
colonel in charge of air defenses be reprimanded over his failure
to detect a fighter jet that a defector flew over the border from
Syria last week.
   The Israeli army said Monday that investigators had concluded a
``faulty report and mistaken decision-making process'' in the air
force led to the failure to intercept the Soviet-made MiG-23
fighter jet.
   The Oct. 11 flight into northern Israel caused an uproar here
over possible flaws in the air defense system along the border with
Syria.
   The military team recommended that the colonel who directed air
defenses at the time of the defection be reprimanded. The officer
was not identified.
   Military officials said the air force also was expected to
update its standing orders and procedures related to air
infiltrations.
   One question not answered by the army probe was why the pilot,
Maj. Mohammed Bassam Adel, spent 20 minutes on the ground with no
security officials around after landing at Megiddo, a few minutes'
flight from Haifa, a port city of 250,000.
   Adel, 34, was on a training flight over southern Syria when he
flew into Israel and landed at an airstrip used by crop-dusting
planes. He said he defected in search of freedom and democracy.
   Also Monday, a Beirut newspaper reported that Israel's secret
service used a Druse woman to lure the Syrian air force pilot who
flew the jet.
   Ad-Diyar, a conservative daily based in Christian east Beirut,
said in an unsourced front-page report that a Druse woman, whom it
did not identify, confessed following her arrest that she had been
recruited by Israeli intelligence.
   Ad-Diyar said Israel had been interested in gaining direct
information from a Syrian pilot flying a MiG-23. Syria and Israel
have been in a state of war since Israel's creation in 1948.
