<FIRST>r a PM-MooseDead     10-17 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Moose Dead,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hunter Charged For Shooting Wandering Moose</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNDERWOOD, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A deer hunter pleading self defense was
cited today for killing a moose that had wandered hundreds of miles
from its natural range and startled farmers by ambling through
Iowa's cornfields.
   Michael Scott Wiggins was charged with shooting an animal out of
season _ Iowa has no moose season _ and having a center-fire rifle
in his possession while deer hunting during a muzzle-loading season.
   Each charge carries up to a $100 fine or 30 days in jail, said
Assistant County Attorney Tim Markel. The state also will seek
$1,000 in damages, he said.
   The bull moose was first seen Sept. 22 near Sheldon, in the
state's northwestern corner. It wandered into downtown Cherokee and
many cornfields, startling farmers and attracting spectators. Some
people even took to airplanes to get a better look.
   Wiggins, who turned himself in Sunday, said he encountered the
moose in a soybean field earlier in the day near Underwood, about
10 miles from Council Bluffs, while hunting coyotes, said
Conservation Officer Doug Clayton.
   Wiggins said he shot the animal when it threatened to charge
him, Clayton said.
   The nearest natural habitat of moose is about 400 miles north of
Iowa, in the woods and lakes of northern Minnesota. Only three
others, all bulls, have been reported in Iowa in the last dozen
years.
</TEXT>
