<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-89 1202EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-FuelTesting     10-17 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fuel Testing,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil, Auto Companies to Test Gasoline Against Methanol</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The oil and auto industries, seeking to
influence the outcome of Congress' debate over alternative motor
fuels, today announced a joint program to test the
pollution-cutting benefits of gasoline against methanol.
   Keith McHenry, senior vice president of technology at Amoco
Corp., said the $11 million testing program would provide an
``objective assessment'' of the relative air quality benefits to be
derived from methanol and new formulations of gasoline.
   The joint program, involving the Big Three auto companies and
the 14 largest oil companies, is to begin immediately. A report on
findings is due by next July or August.
   McHenry said too little was known at present about the
emission-reduction potential of methanol and reformulated gasoline
for Congress and the states to make good decisions on policies
aimed at curbing smog caused largely by burning fossil fuels.
   The American Petroleum Institute, the trade organization of the
major oil companies, has vigorously lobbied against methanol and
touted the advantages of gasoline.
   McHenry asserted, however, that the joint study would have ``no
bias.''
   ``We have made no preconceived notions about how our data will
turn out,'' he told a news conference.
   The oil companies have sought to defeat a provision in President
Bush's proposed amendments to the Clean Air Act that would require
the auto companies to make vehicles that run on fuels other than
gasoline, and for the alternative fuels to be available for use by
motorists in the most polluted urban areas by 1995.
   The alternative fuel favored by the administration is methanol,
which currently is not in commercial production. The oil industry,
which sells about 100 billion gallons of gasoline yearly, has
raised safety, economic and environmental questions about methanol,
a form of alcohol.
   McHenry said senior executives of Amoco and General Motors Corp.
met with White House chief of staff John Sununu to inform him of
the joint study, but he said there was no discussion of the
political aspects of alternative fuels.
   ``He said, `Sounds like a good program, go ahead and do it,
we've very interested in the results,''' McHenry quoted Sununu as
saying.
   McHenry said the oil companies and automakers hoped their test
results would be available before Congress passes clean-air
legislation.
   The testing procedures and results are to be reviewed by an
independent advisory committee composed of academic specialists and
federal and state agencies, McHenry said, adding that this would
ensure the outcome was not biased.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
