<FIRST>u i PM-Colombia 4thLd-Writethru a0561 10-17 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colombia, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0561,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Murdered In Medellin</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 11 grafs to UPDATE with judges considering strike,
details. Pick up 9th pvs, `Meanwhile, the...' ADDS byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge was gunned down today as
he waited on a Medellin street corner for a ride to work, and an
anonymous caller said drug traffickers killed him in retaliation
for extraditions to the United States.
   Courts reportedly were paralyzed in Medellin after the slaying.
Shocked judges conferred with each other and a union encompassing
all Colombia's judges and court employees considered a strike for
better security.
   Police said Judge Hector Jimenez Rodriguez was shot six times by
a passenger on a motorcycle.
   The gunman got off the motorcycle, walked up to Jimenez and shot
him, the Colombian radio chain Caracol quoted witnesses as saying
in Medellin, the base of the country's most notorious cocaine
cartel.
   An anonymous caller to Caracol said the judge was slain by ``The
Extraditables,'' a group of suspected drug traffickers being hunted
for extradition to the United States.
   The government of President Virgilio Barco has extradited four
Colombians to the United States, including three last Saturday,
since a crackdown on drug trafficking began Aug. 19.
   ``The Extraditables'' said in a communique soon after the
crackdown began that they would kill 10 judges for every Colombian
extradited. Jimenez was the first judge killed since the drug sweep
started. It was not immediately known if Jimenez had been involved
in any recent extradition cases.
   There are varying figures on the number of judges that have been
killed in Colombia, but the Justice Ministry says that about 50
judges and 170 judicial employees have been killed since 1982.
   The Association of Judicial Employees says 1,600 of Colombia's
5,000 judges have been threatened with death in the last 12 months.
   The court workers' union held an emergency meeting in Bogota to
decide whether to ask members to strike for better security, an
executive with the union told The Associated Press.
   Court activity in Medellin came to a standstill as judges met
behind closed doors to decide what to do, the union executive said.
He asked to remain anonymous so he would not become a target of
drug traffickers.
   Meanwhile, the newspaper Vanguardia Liberal of Bucaramanga,
heavily damaged by a bomb on Monday, hit the streets with a 16-page
edition today. The newspaper had joined in a condemnation of
cocaine barons.
   There had been doubts that Vanguardia Liberal would be able to
publish today. The paper usually publishes 24 pages each day. Four
employees of the newspaper were killed when a car bomb wrecked its
building in northeastern Colombia.
   The newspaper's publisher blamed drug traffickers for the
bombing in Bucaramanga, a city of 400,000 people 175 miles north of
Bogota.
   Four journalists were assassinated by unidentified gunmen last
week in the cities of Medellin and Monterria.
</TEXT>
