<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-89 1227EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-ChildCare     10-17 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Child Care,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study: Child Care Jeopardized by Low Wages</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAMARA HENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Children in child care centers are in jeopardy
because poverty-level wages have fueled ``an alarming rate of
turnover'' of trained teachers, according to a study released today.
   The National Child Care Staffing Study found that teachers are
earning an average hourly wage of $5.35, which provides an annual
income of $9,363 for full-time employment. The 1988 poverty
threshold for a family of three _ the average family size in the
sample _ was $9,431 a year.
   The study said almost three-quarters of the child care teachers
in the study had some college background but earned less than half
as much as comparably educated women and less than one-third as
much as comparably educated men in the work force.
   ``These low wages are fueling an alarming rate of turnover,''
said Marcy Whitebook, head of the Child Care Employee Project and
principal investigator of the study. She said staff turnover jumped
from 15 percent in 1977 to 41 percent last year, nearly tripled in
the last decade.
   ``Instead of centers that promote healthy child development, we
are confronted by programs where children don't know who will be
caring for them from day to day, where they are isolated from
peers, where they lack language competence and miss critical social
development,'' said Rep. George Miller, chairman of the House
Select Committee on Children, Youth and Families.
   The House early this month approved a $22.7 billion child care
package that Miller said addresses the problems of salary and
training. Now lawmakers are working out differences between the
House version and one passed by the Senate earlier this year.
   Deborah Phillips, assistant psychology professor at the
University of Virginia and a project investigator, said 227 child
care centers in Atlanta, Boston, Detroit, Phoenix and Seattle were
examined between February and August 1988. The centers served a
total of more than 16,000 families _ including 53 infants, 97
toddlers and 110 preschoolers _ and employed more than 3,000 staff.
   ``Our study raises serious concerns about the quality of care in
America,'' she said. ``The typical classroom in centers had barely
adequate quality ratings. Better quality centers had higher wages
for teaching staff, lower teaching staff turnover, better educated
and trained staff and more teachers caring for fewer children.''
   Other observations, said Ms. Phillips, were that better quality
centers were more likely to be non-profit and that low- and
high-income children were more likely than middle-income children
to attend centers providing higher quality care.
   Ms. Phillips explained that day care for low-income families
oftentimes is subsidized by the federal government, while
middle-income families must personally pay for the entire expense.
   Carollee Howes, professor at the University of California at Los
Angeles, said the study recommended that child care teacher
salaries be increased to recruit and retain qualified workers, and
that formal education and training be promoted. She said staff
training should be adopted at both the federal and state levels.
   The study, funded with $500,000 by a consortium of foundations
including the Ford Foundation and the Foundation for Child
Development, was endorsed by a number of organizations.
   ``We have known for far too long that the staffing crisis is
strangling the supply and quality of early childhood programs,''
said Barbara Willer of the National Association for the Education
of Young Children. ``The staffing study dramatically supports the
adage, `You get what you pay for'. ''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
