<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Crickets     10-17 0153</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Crickets,0157</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cricket Catchers Damage Shanghai Fields</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The cricket wars are laying waste to Shanghai
fields, an official newspaper said Tuesday.
   Nearly 1,700 acres of fields have been damaged and 1 million
square feet of city shrubbery trampled by people hunting at night
for bugs to do battle in cricket fighting contests, the China Daily
said, quoting a Shanghai newspaper.
   It said 1,000 people in the city of 12 million make their living
by dealing in crickets, and that at one market, 10,000 crickets are
sold daily for an estimated $54,000 to $81,000.
   A cricket club has been set up and at a recent national cricket
fighting contest, the winner took home the equivalent of $810,
double what a factory worker earns in a year.
   City agriculture and urban management departments have called
for cricket fighting, a popular activity for gambling in many parts
of China, to be banned.
</TEXT>
