<FIRST>r i AM-Korea-US     10-17 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea-US,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students Stage Anti-U.S. Protests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of radical students on
Tuesday hurled firebombs at riot police and chanted ``Yankee go
home!'' as they denounced President Bush's meeting in Washington
with President Roh Tae-woo.
   Police fired volleys of tear gas at the 500 students at Seoul's
Kunkook University, where demonstrators burned an effigy of U.S.
Ambassador Donald Gregg and demanded his recall.
   Similar anti-U.S. protests occurred at Wonkwang University in
the southern city of Chonju after police blocked about 200 students
from marching into the streets.
   The students demanded an end to close ties between the United
States and South Korea and to efforts by the United States to open
South Korean markets wider.
   Police reported no arrests or injuries.
   The protests came as police questioned six radical students for
the torture death of a student suspected of being a police spy. The
students surrendered Sunday after confessing to a priest, police
said.
   Police have been on heightened alert since Roh left Sunday for
Washington, with security bolstered at U.S. facilities after an
attack on Gregg's residence on Friday.
   Dissidents and radical students have demanded Gregg's recall,
contending he supported South Korea's military rule when he was CIA
station chief in Seoul in the 1970s.
   Six radical students armed with firebombs and iron bars broke
into the ambassador's residence on Friday and hurled homemade bombs
at guards and smashed artwork and windows before being overpowered
by police.
   Gregg and his wife escaped unhurt and left for Washington to
take part in the Roh-Bush talks Tuesday.
   A U.S. Embassy spokesman said U.S. officials were conferring
with Korean police to determine how security around U.S. facilities
could be improved to prevent future attacks.
</TEXT>
