<FIRST>u p PM-MississippiElection 1stLd-Writethru a0523 10-17 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mississippi Election, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0523,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Key GOP Seat Up For Grabs in Mississippi</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to CORRECT congressman's name to Smith. PICKS
UP 4th graf pvs, `The district ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT NAYLOR JR.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters picking a successor to the late
U.S. Rep. Larkin Smith decided today whether to keep the seat in
GOP hands or give the Democrats Mississippi's entire House
delegation for the first time in 17 years.
   Republican Tom Anderson, 43, long-time chief of staff to U.S.
Sen. Trent Lott, faced Democrat Gene Taylor, a 36-year-old state
senator, in a high-stakes campaign to fill the seat left vacant by
Smith death in a plane crash Aug. 13.
   Lott had held the seat for the Republicans for 16 years before
he went on to the Senate. Smith defeated Taylor for the post last
year.
   The district in the southeastern corner of the state includes
the Gulf Coast and the cities of Biloxi, Gulfport and Hattiesburg.
   The GOP has shown the importance they place on the seat in the
amount of money Anderson has spent, a campaign appearance by
President Bush and Lott's visibility. Anderson spent about $500,000
_ roughly five times what Taylor has spent.
   ``That district is important to us not because it has been in
Republican hands for so long,'' said state Democratic Chairman Ed
Cole. ``That's one of the reasons.
   ``But that district represents the best of what Mississippi has
to offer in that it has the strongest economy, the highest per
capita income, the highest technology base and the greatest
population growth in the last 10 years.''
   A Taylor victory would give Democrats all five of Mississippi's
congressional seats for the first time since 1972. Republicans hold
both Senate seats.
   In the primary Oct. 3, Taylor got 42 percent of the vote and
Anderson 37 percent to advance to today's runoff. Attorney General
Mike Moore, a Democrat, got 21 percent of the vote and was
eliminated.
   Taylor's campaign predicted a victory. Anderson described
himself in recent days as the underdog and took the offensive
recently, criticizing Taylor's legislative record and accusing him
of accepting money from big labor groups.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
