<FIRST>u i PM-India-Elections 1stLd-Writethru a0515 10-17 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India-Elections, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0515,0525</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Calls For November Balloting</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with official confirmation, comment
from opposition leader, date of elections; Picks up 8th graf, `Gandhi said
...'; ADDS byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi today called
for new parliamentary elections next month in which he will face
voters amid charges of inept leadership and government corruption.
   Voting in the world's largest democracy will start Nov. 22 and
continue Nov. 24, chief election commissioner R.V.S. Perisastri
told a news conference. He said subsequent dates would be announced
if two days appear insufficient.
   Gandhi's decision came on the heels of fresh charges of
high-level corruption and his failure to push two constitutional
amendments through Parliament last week. Gandhi took office five
years ago.
   ``By deciding to face the people, the government has been forced
to take the only option available to it,'' said Gandhi's chief
political rival, Vishwanath Pratap Singh.
   Singh is the leader of the Janata Dal, one of five groups
comprising the opposition National Front.
   United News of India and Press Trust of India said Gandhi's
Cabinet decided to set November elections rather than wait for the
constitutional deadline of late December or early January.
   Gandhi and his Congress Party want to turn the election into a
referendum on the constitutional amendments defeated Friday in
Parliament's upper house, the Press Trust said.
   Gandhi said the amendments were designed to give village and
municipal governments more autonomy.
   They fell three votes short of the necessary two-thirds
majority. Opposition parties charged the bills were intended to
consolidate the federal government's power.
   Some analysts said that by pushing power-to-the-people measures,
Gandhi hoped to divert attention from charges that he is presiding
over a corrupt government.
   The 45-year-old prime minister has been dogged for the past two
years by charges that people close to him or his party received
kickbacks paid by the Swedish arms company, AB Bofors.
   Indian newspapers have alleged that Bofors paid as much as $50
million in commissions or kickbacks to secure its 1986 contract to
sell $1.4 billion worth of artillery to India.
   Gandhi has repeatedly denied he profited from the deal, and has
said no Indians received commissions. The Indian press has charged
the money went to companies whose ownerships are largely a mystery.
   At stake are 542 seats in the Lok Sabha, or house of the people,
Parliament's policy-making lower house.
   Gandhi's Congress Party won 415 seats in the last vote, held in
December 1984 two months after his mother, Prime Minister Indira
Gandhi, was assassinated by two of her Sikh bodyguards.
   The wave of sympathy that propelled Gandhi to an unprecedented
landslide subsequently eroded with allegations of corruption.
   An August poll published by the respected news magazine India
Today projected Gandhi's party would win only 314 seats this time.
   An opposition victory would mean an end to the Nehru-Gandhi
dynasty that has governed the world's largest democracy for all but
about three years since independence from Britain in 1947.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
