<FIRST>r w PM-O'Neill-Abortion 1stLd-Writethru a0548 10-17 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-O'Neill-Abortion, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0548,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pro-Choice Group Removes Conn. Governor From Target List</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts new 5th graf, In Hartford, with O'Neill reaction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A national abortion rights group today removed
Connecticut Gov. William O'Neill from a list of top political
targets for defeat today, reversing a stand the group took just
three days earlier.
   The reversal by the National Abortion Rights Action League took
O'Neill off a list that included Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C.; Florida
Gov. Bob Martinez and six other elected officials as ripe political
targets because of their anti-abortion views.
   ``I have spoken with Gov. O'Neill's office and I have received
assurances that the governor is not planning any anti-choice
initiatives,'' NARAL leader Kate Michelman said in a statement
today.
   ``The governor has stated that regardless of his own personal
views he believes individuals have a right to make their own
decisions. As a result, NARAL is removing him from its list of
elected officials targeted for defeat in 1990.''
   In Hartford, Conn., O'Neill said today he didn't have the
slightest idea how he got on the list in the first place, ``but how
I got off there became self-evident because the local people in the
state of Connecticut knew I shouldn't have been on there to begin
with.''
   Michelman added that her group will be watching all the
candidates in the 1990 race for Connecticut governor and may
``consider involvement'' as the campaign develops. O'Neill, a
Democrat, has said he plans to seek re-election.
   O'Neill's selection to the group's ``NARAL Nine'' drew protests
from NARAL's Connecticut chapter and from the governor's office,
which said that O'Neill, while personally opposed to abortion,
supports abortion rights.
   After discussions Monday between Michelman and O'Neill's chief
of staff, David J. McQuade, the group agreed to issue a press
release removing O'Neill's name from the list.
   ``Short-lived infamy,'' McQuade said after Michelman agreed in a
telephone conversation to remove O'Neill's name from the list and
to announce the move in a press release today.
   Lynn Blackwell, president of the board of the Connecticut NARAL
group, said NARAL's national office never consulted with the board
members of the local chapter about O'Neill's abotion stand. And
despite a NARAL claim that the organization wrote to O'Neill about
his abortion stand, the governor's office had no record of such a
letter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
