<FIRST>r i AM-Pacific-US     10-17 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pacific-US,0444</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Envoys Take Posts in Australia, New Zealand</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD BILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two new U.S. ambassadors arrived at
their posts in Australia and New Zealand this week amid debate over
their appointments and the future of U.S. relations with the South
Pacific nations.
   Multimillionaire Florida developer Melvin Sembler arrived
Tuesday in Canberra to take over from Bill Lane, a California
publisher appointed by former President Ronald Reagan.
   On Monday, Della Newman, a Seattle real estate agent who ran
President Bush's election campaign in Washington state, arrived in
New Zealand to take up her post. She replaces Paul Cleveland, who
left in May.
   Mrs. Newman's arrival in Wellington ``comes amid conflicting
signals over the future of American-New Zealand relations,'' said
the Evening Post, the New Zealand capital's only afternoon
newspaper, in an editorial Tuesday.
   ``Mrs. Newman is entitled to a courteous reception but until the
U.S. sees that New Zealand is still a staunch friend, and adjusts
its attitude accordingly, the New Zealand government's welcome
should be measured,'' said the paper, which has a daily circulation
of 90,000 in a city of 200,000 people.
   Sembler has been the subject of lengthy debate in Washington _
which received widespread coverage in Australia _ about political
appointees over career diplomats. Sembler is known to Australians
as a Florida shopping center developer who raised $130,000 for the
Bush campaign.
   He follows a long line of U.S. ambassadors to Australia who
previously worked in non-related jobs such as car salesmen,
publishing and real estate.
   The South Pacific, long perceived as a backwater, has had its
share of world headlines in recent years with general turmoil among
island states and two coups in Fiji, to the bombing of the
Greenpeace ship Rainbow Warrior by French secret agents in
Auckland, and New Zealand's anti-nuclear policy that led to the
collapse of the ANZUS military alliance and the virtual severing of
its relations with the United States.
   Mrs. Newman, 57, on her arrival pledged to strenghten ties
between the two countries while recognizing major policy
differences.
   ``We cannot ignore the serious differences that have developed
between our governments in recent years regarding ANZUS and nuclear
policy, but we must not allow that to blind us to our many
interests,'' she said.
   Sembler, 58, drew headlines in Australia as ``Bush's $100,000
Man To Get Posting In Australia,'' while Mrs. Newman was reported
as a woman ``experienced in holding parties and functions.''
   An Australian government official said of the appointments that
at least the two countries will ``have the ear of the president.''
</TEXT>
