<FIRST>r a AM-DepressionArt     10-17 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Depression Art,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Artist Gets Second Chance to Complete Library Mural</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MUSKEGON, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An artist whose library mural was
forestalled by a canceled federal grant during the Depression says
he's getting ready to complete his painting on the theme, ``Reading
good books is time well spent.''
   The Works Progress Administration, which hired unemployed
artists during the Depression, paid artist Wilfrid Berg $100 to
paint a mural featuring people of the world in native dress, he
recalls. The mural is on a wall in the children's reading room at
Hackley Public Library, but the opposite wall is blank because the
WPA withdrew promised funding in 1934 for a second mural, Berg said.
   Berg, now 81, said he expects to complete the second mural in
time for the library's centennial next year thanks to a private
donation.
   ``Painting has been my life, but I never had the studio or the
space to do the big things I really like to do. That's why I
couldn't resist when I got a chance to do this,'' he said Monday.
   The design for the second mural features characters from classic
children's literature, including Huck Finn, Peter Rabbit,
Cinderella, Rip Van Winkle and Pinocchio.
   The benefactors, Daniel and Shirley Rapoport of Muskegon, would
not disclose the amount of their donation, but Mrs. Rapoport said
it is ``considerably more than what the WPA paid him.''
</TEXT>
