<HEAD>Nicaraguan Cleared of Biting Border Agent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOBILE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal jury acquitted a man of biting a
Border Patrol agent on the Fourth of July, and on hearing the news
the defendant bent down an kissed the courtroom floor.
   Rolando Dominquez, 40, a native of Nicaragua, was in this
country illegally, according to testimony. He was detained for
questioning in Mobile on July 4.
   Border Patrol agent Thomas Kilgoar said Dominquez bit him on the
arm and sent him to the hospital. But Dominquez testified that
Kilgoar slapped him in the face and he was acting in self-defense.
   Kilgoar denied he slapped and shoved the man.
   Dominquez testified that he walked out of Nicaragua in 1987 to
Honduras and lived in forests and begged for money to reach this
country.
   When he was stopped at a Mobile bus station, he said he was on
his way to New York.
   Although acquitted Monday of the biting charge, Dominquez
remains in custody and could be deported. His attorney, Domingo
Soto, told U.S. District Judge Charles Butler that his client will
seek political asylum in this country.
