<FIRST>u a PM-Abortion-Illinois     10-17 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion-Illinois,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>House Panel Blocks Action on Abortion Measure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DOWLING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Illinois House committee today voted
to block further action on abortion restrictions designed to mirror
the Missouri law upheld in July by the U.S. Supreme Court.
   The measure fell one vote short of the 10 needed to clear the
House Rules Committee and move to the full House. Nine lawmakers
voted in favor of the measure, eight against.
   Anti-abortion lawmakers have said they might try to bypass the
committee and bring the issue to the House, but some parliamentary
experts have questioned whether that's possible.
   In a brief debate before the vote, anti-abortion lawmakers said
the measure adheres to the guidelines set down by the Supreme
Court, and that it was an emergency.
   ``I ask you, please, to vote `aye' for life,'' said Rep. Penny
Pullen, the bill's sponsor.
   Pro-choice lawmakers argued that the measure was being rushed to
final passage and amounts to ``harassment'' of physicians and women
needing late-term abortions.
   ``Yes, the Supreme Court did say on July 3 that a bill like this
is constitutional,'' said Rep. Barbara Flynn Currie. ``What it
didn't and couldn't say is that a bill like this is sensible.''
   The bill would have required doctors to determine the viability
of a fetus believed to be 20 weeks old or older before performing
an abortion, and mandate the presence of a second physician at
abortions of viable fetuses. It also would bar public employees and
public facilities from direct involvement in abortions.
   Anti-abortion lobbyists voiced hope Monday for a victory, though
they acknowledged that pro-choice movement has gained momentum from
the recent vote by Congress to expand Medicaid funding of abortion
and the defeat of proposed abortion restrictions in Florida.
   Nicholas Stojakovich, lobbyist for the Illinois Pro-Life
Coalition, had said Monday that if the measure failed in committee,
anti-abortion lawmakers might seek another vote later in the week
or try to bypass the committee and bring the issue to the House.
But he called such alternatives ``a long shot at best.''
   ``If it comes to a vote on Tuesday and it's voted down, that
could be the end of it,'' he said.
   The measure before the Rules Committee was introduced last
spring as a legislative vehicle for any new abortion restrictions
permitted by the U.S. Supreme Court.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
