<SECOND>PM-Quayle Visit, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0611,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vice President Met With Protest Against Military Aid</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 2nd graf to update with protester saying none of injuries
serious.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY CARPENTER HALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opponents of U.S. military aid to Central
America demonstrated outside a hotel where Vice President Dan
Quayle was speaking, and 21 people were arrested.
   Several of those arrested were later injured in a traffic
accident as they were being taken to jail. Protester Robin Terry
said the worst injury was a broken leg and that all of the
protesters had been released from a hospital by today.
   ``There were about 200 protesters out there. I would say out of
respect for the office of vice president there should have been
500,'' Quayle quipped during his appearance at a Republican
fund-raiser at a downtown hotel.
   Quayle's press secretary, David Beckwith, said it was the
largest demonstration against Quayle since he's been vice president
and the only demonstration that disrupted his schedule. Quayle left
the hotel a half hour late.
   The protest began as a ``die-in,'' with 11 demonstrators wearing
red-stained clothes lying on the sidewalk in front of the hotel.
   When police asked them to move, the protesters tried to push
their way through the doors, chanting: ``Bush, Quayle, we know you;
Hitler was elected, too.''
   Police used nightsticks to quell the demonstration. ``It was
hats and bats and shoving and pushing,'' said a police officer who
didn't give his name.
   Earlier, Quayle dropped in at an FBI news conference to praise
investigators' efforts in breaking up a drug ring.
   ``What you've been able to accomplish is part of the strategy of
President Bush in his war against drugs,'' he told law enforcement
officers from several agencies. ``We're not going to give up until
that war is won.''
   The news conference was called to announce the seizure of $150
million worth of tar heroin and cocaine on the West Coast.
</TEXT>
