<FIRST>r a AM-NAACP-OleMiss     10-17 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NAACP-Ole Miss,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>NAACP Officials Ask University of Mississippi to Integrate Fraternities</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OXFORD, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state NAACP demanded full racial
integration of University of Mississippi fraternities and
sororities in a meeting Tuesday with school officials.
   The meeting was in response to an incident last month in which
two white fraternity pledges were left naked, with racial slurs
scrawled on them, at a black college near the university.
   NAACP officials also recommended stiffer penalties for racial
incidents on campus; additional black staff members at the
university so students of all backgrounds would have more black
role models; and establishment of an academic course that would
give students a knowledge of black history and cultural differences.
   Such a course is scheduled to start next fall.
   ``The meeting was a sharing of ideas by officials representing
the NAACP and Ole Miss officials,'' said Ed Meek, director of
public relations at the university. ``It was a calm, deliberate
kind of discussion.''
   ``The black community is outraged and disturbed at what took
place and the ongoing racial incidents stemming from the
fraternities and students who are enrolled there,'' Morris Kinsey,
education chairman for the state chapter of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People, said prior to
the meeting.
   Kinsey was joined by state NAACP President Aaron Henry and other
NAACP officials in the meeting with a university delegation headed
by Chancellor Gerald Turner, Meek said.
   He said Turner told the NAACP officials that ``many of the
recommendations were already under study and said their concerns
certainly would be taken under advisement.''
   The Beta Theta Pi fraternity was expelled from campus for three
years because of the recent racial incident. The chancellor also
handed out punishments ranging from expulsion to probation to 14
students who took part in the prank.
   Last week, Turner set up a 23-member minority affairs council to
build programs and policies to increase minority participation in
campus life.
</TEXT>
