<FIRST>r w AM-Hastings     10-17 0589</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hastings,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Forecasts Victory in Senate Impeachment Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Judge Alcee L. Hastings said Tuesday he
believes he will win his fight to remain on the federal bench, but
hinted he might attempt an unusual appeal to the Supreme Court if
the Senate votes to remove him.
   ``I'm not going to be convicted,'' the Miami jurist told a news
conference the day before the Senate was to hear final arguments in
his impeachment case.
   A special committee of 12 senators heard evidence in the
impeachment trial in July and August and the Senate is now nearing
the final chapter in the case.
   The Senate is to hear final arguments Wednesday, followed by a
closed-door debate Thursday with the vote to come at an unspecified
time afterward.
   A Senate vote to convict Hastings on any of the charges against
him would immediately remove him as a federal judge and halt
payment of his $89,500 judicial salary.
   Hastings is accused in the articles of impeachment, approved by
the House in August 1988, of plotting to accept a $150,000 payoff
and lying about it to a U.S. District Court jury in 1983.
   The jury acquitted Hastings, the first black federal judge in
Florida history.
   The articles of impeachment also accuse Hastings of improper
disclosure of information obtained as a result of a federal wiretap
that he had authorized. The allegation arose after the 1983 trial,
and thus was not an issue in it.
   Senate action in an impeachment case is considered final.
   Hastings said, however, that so many unusual issues have arisen
that an attempt might be made to appeal an unfavorable verdict to
the Supreme Court.
   ``There is that possibility,'' Hastings told the news
conference, which was called by congressional Delegate Walter
Fauntroy, D-D.C., as a way to register his support for the
embattled judge.
   As an example of one unusual circumstance in the case, he noted
that he was acquitted by the 1983 jury but being placed on trial
anyway. He said that represented a violation of his right against
double jeopardy.
   The Senate has determined that the impeachment trial does not
represent double jeopardy, calling it a fundamentally different
type of proceeding from a criminal trial. If convicted, Hastings
would merely be removed as a judge. He would not face any sentence,
fine or the like.
   Hastings reiterated that he believes the major reason for the
allegations against him is that he was used as a ``guinea pig'' to
test judicial ethics rules. But he also expressed the belief that
race played a role in the case.
   ``I am not guilty of having committed any crime at all
whatsoever,'' Hastings said. ``But even so, with innocence as my
defense and the facts as my defense, if I were a white person this
would not be happening.''
   Despite Hastings' claim, black leaders have with some exceptions
kept their distance from the case. Among the House prosecutors,
Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich., a veteran campaigner for civil rights,
said at the time Hastings was impeached that the judge had brought
his problems on himself.
   Fauntroy, however, told the news conference that ``basic
constitutional principles of justice and fairness are being
violated in the impeachment proceedings against Judge Alcee
Hastings.''
   ``I find it difficult to believe that, after nearly a decade
when records have been lost and witnesses have passed, any serious
student or advocate of the United States Constitution would
consider the upcoming proceedings of the Senate just or fair,''
Fauntroy said.
</TEXT>
