<HEAD>Administration Urges Palestinians To Talk To Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration made a fresh appeal
Tuesday to Palestinian Arabs to neg
   The House early this month approved a $22.7 billion child care
package that Miller said addresses the problems of salary and
training. Now lawmakers are working out differences between the
House version and one passed by the Senate earlier this year.
   The study _ funded with $500,000 by a consortium of foundations
including the Ford Foundation and the Foundation for Child
Development _ examined 227 child care centers in Atlanta, Boston,
Detroit, Phoenix and Seattle between February 1988 and August 1988.
   The centers served more than 16,000 families and employed more
than 3,000 staffers.
   ``The staffing study dramatically supports the adage, `You get
what you pay for,''' said Barbara Willer of the National
Association for the Education of Young Children.
   The study was endorsed by both the Service Employees
International Union and the American Federation of State, County
and Municipal Employees, which have been working to organize child
care workers.
   SEIU President John Sweeney noted that only 4 percent of child
care teachers ``are protected by a union contract,'' and called for
``adoption of minimum federal standards for adult-child ratios,
staff training, education, and compensation.''
   Investigator Deborah Phillips of the University of Virginia said
the study found ``better quality centers had higher wages for
teaching staff, lower teaching staff turnover, better educated and
trained staff and more teachers caring for fewer children.'' Better
centers also were more likely to be non-profit, she said.
   The study also found that low- and high-income children were
more likely than middle-income children to attend centers providing
higher quality care. She said the main reason is that day care for
low-income families oftentimes is subsidized by the federal
government, while middle-income families must personally pay for
the entire expense.
