<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan-Press 1stLd-Writethru a0647 10-17 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan-Press, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0647,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spanish Journalist Gets 5-Year Sentence For Illegally Entering Country</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 1st graf to CORRECT dateline.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EZUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Spanish free-lance journalist has
been sentenced to five years in prison for illegally entering
Afghanistan, a government spokesman said Tuesday.
   Jorge Juan Garcia, 35, arrested near the Pakistani border in
August, was tried and sentenced Sunday. The government spokesman
said Garcia was convicted of entering the country illegally and
collecting ``anti-government'' material.
   Garcia entered Afghanistan with U.S.-backed guerrillas known as
the mujahedeen, or Islamic holy warriors, who have been fighting
for 11 years. Since the Soviets withdrew their troops in February,
the guerrillas have continued to battle the Soviet-backed
government in Kabul.
   In a news conference in September, Garcia said he was had not
collaborated with the guerrillas and that he was ``just making
notes for my book.''
   A government spokesman said Garcia's five-year sentence was not
excessive and that it matched the conviction. He said the
government would consider relasing Garcia if Spain made a formal
request.
   The Afghan government apparently seeks to use such incidents for
diplomatic purposes. A senior French official went to Kabul last
month to secure the release of Henri-Xavier Lemire, a French aid
worker also arrested for illegally entering Afghanistan.
   In July, the Afghan government released a jailed American
photographer Tony O'Brien after Washington complied with a demand
to make a formal request for his freedom from the regime it does
not recognize. O'Brien was captured at a guerrilla hideout but was
never charged.
   A French photographer and an Italian photographer captured by
government forces were freed last year, but only after their
governments formally requested their release and dispatched senior
officials to Kabul.
</TEXT>
