<FIRST>r a AM-CarWash     10-17 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Car Wash,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>Motorists Wax Nostalgic Over Closure of 1950s-Style Car Wash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Motorists waxed nostalgic during a tearful
farewell to the Studio City car wash they battled to spare from a
wrecker's ball.
   ``I'll miss this place,'' said Pat Galati, his reddened eyes
gazing over the empty car wash waiting room.
   Galati, who operated the car wash and gasoline station, watched
the last car roll through the scrub brushes on Saturday. ``It's
really hard to say goodbye to people you've known for 35 years,''
he said.
   Residents, fans and motorists battled all summer to keep
property owner Ira Smedra from going ahead with demolition and
construction of a shopping center on the site.
   The car wash had a brief brush with immortality when the
Cultural Heritage Commission considered landmark status for the
odd-looking structure, which features a 55-foot tower in the shape
of three giant boomerangs.
   But the commission turned down the request in July.
   ``I'll miss this place. I've taken my car here every Saturday
for five years,'' said Ed Peck, watching workers towel off his
green 1965 Mustang.
   Smedra is angry, meanwhile, that the city has required an
environmental study that could cost $1 million and stall
construction of his $15 million shopping center.
</TEXT>
