<SECOND>AM-BRF--Soviet-Asylum,0128</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Dancer Asks For Political Asylum</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet dancer who went into hiding while
at a hotel has asked for political asylum, a spokesman for the
Interior Ministry said Tuesday.
   Vladimir Karimov, 39, a member of the Soviet Union Red Army
Choir and Dance troupe, disappeared from the Convencion Hotel early
Friday.
   Karimov had asked for political asylum Monday night at a police
station, according to the spokesman, who was not identified in
keeping with custom.
   The Soviet troupe searched for Karimov in the hotel for several
hours before reporting him missing to police. The troupe then left
for Portugal.
   The spokesman said authorities had given Karimov a provisional
three-month residence permit while studying his asylum request.
