<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-89 1453EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-HungerStrike     10-17 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hunger Strike,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prisoners Stay Away From Dining Hall for Second Day</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKDALE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly all the 1,160 inmates at the Federal
Detention Center boycotted the dining hall for a second day
Tuesday, but officials said they couldn't find out why.
   ``We've had staff circulating through the population since
yesterday lunchtime, and we just haven't been able to pick up much
of anything,'' M.L. Jeziorski, executive assistant to the warden,
said.
   Only about 100 inmates ate at the dining hall Monday or Tuesday,
he said.
   ``In an ordinary hunger strike, the inmates would present a list
of grievances to the administration in hopes of getting changes,''
said Jeziorski. ``But we've gotten no list of complaints, no one
stood forth as spokesman for inmates.''
   At lunch Monday, inmates refused a meal of pork chops, potatoes,
cabbage and salad, Jeziorski said. They also refused to eat the
dinner of meatballs and noodles.
   Jeziorski said the prison closed the commissary after lunch
Monday, so striking inmates could eat only what little they might
have in their cells.
   In 1987, Cuban detainees took hostages, rioted and set fire to
the Federal Detention Center during an eight-day siege. The rebuilt
center does not house Cuban detainees, Jeziorski said.
   He said inmates at the center continued the normal routine of
work, school and recreation.
   ``There's not even a hint of violence or anything of that
nature,'' he said.
   Jeziorski said the prison continued to prepare meals. It was
salvaging what food it could, but had to throw away a lot, he said.
   The food couldn't be given to soup kitchens or other charities,
he said.
   ``It's something we couldn't even consider. We couldn't
guarantee the quality after it left here _ some could be sabotaged
or whatever,'' he said.
</TEXT>
