<FIRST>r a PM-Shuttle-Unthinkable 1stLd-Writethru a0479 10-17 0423</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Shuttle-Unthinkable, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0479,0426</SECOND>
<HEAD>What If? ...</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with launch scrubbed; PICKS UP
4th graf pvs, `In a ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Space Shuttle, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F.ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA has given elaborate assurances
that the nuclear power plant carried by space shuttle Atlantis is
safe, but dozens of experts were on hand _ just in case _ before
today's launch was scrubbed.
   They were ready ``if the unthinkable happens,'' said Chris West,
a spokesman for the Department of Energy.
   About 50 people carrying dosimeters and other devices were to be
scattered around the Kennedy Space Center to sample the air in case
of an accident as the shuttle lifted off. The launch was scheduled
for 12:57 p.m. but was canceled because of rain, and NASA
considered making another attempt on Wednesday. The Department of
Energy had planned to have an airplane aloft and 150 people
standing by.
   In a Washington courtroom last week, attorneys for the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration convinced a judge that the
launch was safe and that the two nuclear power packs on the Galileo
space probe would not leak even after a Challenger-like explosion.
   West said the Department of Energy was asked by the state of
Florida and Brevard County, where the Kennedy Space Center is
located, to monitor the launch. A twin turboprop airplane,
outfitted with sophisticated detection equipment, was to circle the
area at lift-off time.
   ``If the unthinkable happens, as soon as the big pieces stop
falling, the plane will do a criss-cross pattern around the
vicinity of the problem and map from the air what the radiation
levels are and where it's going,'' he said.
   Ten teams of two people each will be at posts outside the launch
center with equipment designed to detect plutonium-238, the fuel
used to provide electricity for the Galileo space probe on its
eight-year mission to Jupiter.
   The two nuclear generators on Galileo, carrying 24.7 pounds of
plutonium each, are not reactors and would not produce fission
products in an explosion, NASA said. If the containers broke open,
the plutonium inside would emit mostly heat and alpha radiation _ a
low-level radiation that is stopped by even a piece of paper.
   In case of an accident, said West, state and local authorities
would go on radio and television and advise people to stay indoor
or in their cars and turn on the air conditioning until the
pollution had blown out of the area.
</TEXT>
