<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-89 1457EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-Namibia     10-17 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Namibia,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department: U.N. Officials Are Impartial Toward Namibia Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.N. officials have impartially supervised
preparations for upcoming elections in Namibia, despite initial
fears they might favor leftist guerrillas, a top State Department
official said Tuesday.
   John R. Bolton, the assistant secretary of State for
international organizations, told a group of conservatives that the
U.N. Transition Assistance Group in Namibia has done a good job of
preparing the country for its first elections Nov. 7.
   Voters in the country, a South Africa-governed territory
formerly known as South-West Africa, will go to the polls to elect
delegates for a constituent assembly. That body will draft a
constitution for when Namibia gains full independence next year.
   Bolton said officials in Washington were worried that UNTAG
officials might show favoritism to rebels from the South-West
Africa Peoples Organization, or SWAPO, the group that waged
guerrilla warfare against South Africa for 23 years.
   SWAPO, which operated from bases in Angola and other countries,
has a strong Marxist element. Several years ago, the U.N. General
Assembly accorded SWAPO observer status at the United Nations. It
also created the Council for Namibia, a group that was to
administer the country.
   ``As a result, we and others had significant worries that the
United Nations could not be impartial in supervising an election in
Namibia,'' Bolton said in prepared remarks at a conference on the
future of the territory.
   To date, however, UNTAG ``has not shown any favoritism towards
SWAPO, as was feared, although there have been reports that
individual personnel in UNTAG have done so.''
   The U.N. special representative has told his subordinates that
the ``need to be and be perceived as impartial'' is a key
requirement.
   As an example of even-handedness, Bolton said the U.N. officials
authorized the use of South African and Namibian forces to
counter-attack when SWAPO tried to infiltrate armed guerrillas into
northern Namibia in April, he said.
   In the election, SWAPO representatives will run against those
from right-leaning Democratic Turnhalle Alliance and the Federal
Convention of Namibia.
   So far, nearly 700,000 Namibians have registered to vote and
41,000 Namibians refugees have been repatriated.
   ``If all goes well, conservatives should cautiously welcome the
U.N. role in Namibia,'' Bolton said. ``The emergence of a new state
according to democratic principles is a rare event in the history
of decolonization.''
</TEXT>
