<FIRST>u w PM-US-Nicaragua 2ndLd-Writethru a0579 10-17 0597</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Nicaragua, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0579,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Votes to Limit Debate on Nicaraguan Package</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 8 grafs new, Senate votes to invoke cloture and begin debate.
Picks up 6th graf pvs, White House spokesman.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate moved ahead today on a $9 million
aid package President Bush is seeking to give the political
opposition a boost in Nicaraguan elections scheduled for next year.
   The Senate voted 74-25 to limit debate on the issue, assuring
that the matter would come up for a final vote later in the day.
Sixty votes were required to invoke cloture, heading off filibuster
threats from opponents of the package.
   Earlier, at the White House, Bush had mapped strategy with
Republican senators in a bid to win support for the aid package, of
which up to $2 million could go to an electoral council controlled
by the leftist Sandinista government.
   The money would flow through the National Endowment for
Democracy, a quasi-governmental body established by Congress to
encourage democratic processes around the world.
   Some of it would be used to boost the long-shot election chances
of opposition newspaper publisher Violeta Chamorro, the
presidential candidate of the opposition coalition UNO. She is
opposing incumbent President Daniel Ortega, who is seeking
re-election.
   Under Nicaraguan law, half of any contribution to Mrs. Chamarro
must go to the Sandinista-controlled Supreme Electoral Council,
which is supposed to use the money for expenses of running the
election. But U.S. officials fear the it could be spent to aid the
Sandinista side.
   The cloture vote came because of fears that opponents would
filibuster the bill.
   The administration was concerned about an amendment planned by
Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, that officials said could torpedo the
entire aid package.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Bush told the
senators that no one likes the prospect of giving $2 million to the
Sandinistas, ``but we have no choice.''
   Sen. Malcolm Wallop, R-Wyo., charged after the meeting with Bush
that the real intent of the Harkin amendment is ``to assist the
Sandinistas.''
   Harkin, a liberal, was forging an alliance with conservative
senators in an effort to prohibit any U.S. aid from going to the
Sandinistas. The administration said that would in effect kill the
whole aid package and wind up hurting Mrs. Chamarro's chances.
   Harkin was not immediately available for comment, but his
legislative assistant, Ed Long, said, ``The senator wants to have
positive, constructive support for free elections, not support that
would be perceived as having bought off the election. That can be
done with a smaller package.''
   Long said the United States has already provided $3.5 million
through the National Endowment for Democracy for the Nicaraguan
elections.
   The Sandinistas, in control of Nicaragua since 1979, have agreed
to elections Feb. 25. Mrs. Chamarro is facing an uphill struggle
against Sandinista President Daniel Ortega.
   Fitzwater quoted Bush as saying, ``many senators don't want to
give aid to the Sandinistas, and neither do we, but we have no
choice. It's the only way to help Mrs. Chamarro and the opposition
to assure a reasonable shot at free and fair elections.''
   Congress and the administration have stopped military aid to the
anti-Sandinista Contra rebels.
   Fitzwater said Bush ``feels this election is the last crucial
shot at getting representative democracy in Nicaragua. Under
current circumstances, with the Sandinista government controlling
the media, the assets, the money, the funding, and Mrs. Chamarro
and the opposition being so underfunded there is no way to suggest
that this is a fair election without some (U.S.) support for her
campaign.''
</TEXT>
