<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     10-17 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Windfall or short change? Taxes aren't as
certain as they used to be.
   A $20 million bank error threw off state estimates of how much
sales tax revenue was due earlier this month to New York counties,
cities and towns.
   Quarterly checks to many downstate governments, such as Putnam
County, came up short, while Plattsburgh and others upstate got
more than they deserved.
   But Benjamin Franklin's famous axiom _ the one about death and
taxes being the world's only certainties _ may not be off on the
tax part for long.
   ``We will be informing them very shortly of the adjustments we
have to make upward or downward,'' said Paul Rickard, a state Tax
Department spokesman. ``They shouldn't look at what happened this
month as any significant trend.''
   About $20 million in tax revenue was not counted at a bank,
skewing the complex formula the state uses to distribute the money.
   Plattsburgh, for example, wrongly received a check for $822,000
_ a 17 percent increase over $697,000 last year. Putnam County
received less tax revenue than last year _ $3.9 million, compared
with just more than $4 million.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GREENWICH, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mason Hommel likes his world a little
topsy-turvy.
   The 75-year-old motorist has no plans to exchange license plates
that were printed with the state name, slogan and Connecticut map
upside down.
   Hommel called the Connecticut Department of Motor Vehicles about
the odd plates he bought recently. The man he talked to told him to
go ahead and use them.
   ``Undoubtedly, he thought I was drunk or something,'' Hommel
said.
   The words ``Connecticut'' and ``Constitution State'' appear
upside down.
   ``I'd love to be stopped by a state cop and see what his
reaction is,'' Hommel said.
   Paul Oates, a state motor vehicles spokesman, said the plates
were made at the Cheshire Correctional Community and are
``basically legal.''
   ``They're an oddity, no doubt about it,'' he said.
</TEXT>
