<HEAD>Prisoners Pitch In to Put Out Jail Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SABA, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   County jail prisoners were freed by a
dispatcher when fire broke out and stayed around to help fight the
blaze.
   There was no fear the five prisoners would escape.
   ``We're just a small country town,'' said San Saba County
sheriff's dispatcher Nan Barker. ``If you're calling from Dallas,
then you really wouldn't understand.''
   The men were transferred to the Mills County Jail, about 20
miles away.
   San Saba County commissioners will have to decide whether their
jail, which was built in 1884, can be repaired.
   The jail was heavily damaged and a computer and radio equipment
lost. No damage estimate was available.
   Investigators had not determined what caused the fire, which
started in an area where recovered property is stored.
   San Saba is a town of about 3,000 located about 80 miles
northwest of Austin.
