<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-89 1537EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ToyTrains     10-17 0624</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Toy Trains,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Railroad Heaven Found in Downtown Washington</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Every child's fantasy has come to downtown
Washington, where the National Geographic Society has gathered toy
trains of every size and era into a model railroad heaven.
   Collected from basements and museums, garages and model clubs
across the land, the trains will be on display until Jan. 7 at
Explorer's Hall, on the ground floor of the Society's headquarters.
   Intricate wood and ivory trains carved by Ernest Warther are
displayed across from giant one-eighth size metal model
locomotives; elegant place settings from railroad dining cars are
around the corner from a computerized control system that can run
80 electric model trains at once.
   A class of Maryland third-graders scampered busily around the
displays on opening day, boys and girls equally interested and
amazed.
   But the joy was far from limited to the children, with National
Geographic President Gilbert Grosvenor overheard volunteering to
remain at the exhibit and help out following the grand opening.
   ``The Disappearing Railroad Blues'' was playing over the sound
system as the exhibit opened, but looking around a visitor would
never know that trains are no longer the nation's most important
transportation system.
   Railroad calendars from past years cover one wall, a large
display case traces the comparative sizes of the different popular
model train gauges, a video plays in an enclosed area and visitors
can listen to recordings of train sounds and railroad history.
   ``People of all ages share a nostalgia about railroading,''
observed Susan Coughlin, deputy director of the Federal Railroad
Administration.
   These models, she commented, trace the growth of the United
States from coast to coast,
   Lionel Trains Inc., lent many current and historical items for
the display. Presenting Lionel President Arthur Peisner with a
souvenir boxcar model, Grosvenor paused for a moment and quipped:
``This is a little like someone giving me a map.''
   The railroad display is a map of exacting work and nostalgia.
   ``Any model is never really finished,'' said Robert Love of
Bethlehem, Pa., who lent a section of his model of Leaville, a
project he and his son Dennis have been working on for decades.
   Leaville is a model of a fictional California mining town in the
1930s.
   Only nine feet of the 20-foot Leaville model has come to
Washington, enclosed in a large covered display to simulate night.
All buildings are lighted from inside to show the detail. Street
lights glow and even automobiles have lighted headlights.
   Less technology but the same dedication to detail is shown in
the display of David Warther, who lent several models carved by his
late father, Ernest.
   The elder Warther carved various woods, ivory and mother of
pearl by hand into exacting model trains.
   ``My father felt that every soul on Earth had a God-given
talent, if they could just find it. He found his at age 5,'' said
Warther.
   One model is dismantled to show the exactness. Warther points
out that a single drive wheel is composed of 54 pieces, including
hubs made of a wood containing natural oils so they would never
have to be oiled, since that could stain other parts.
   His father, a steel worker, spent a lifetime carving the model
trains, creating a detailed history of the steam engine that the
family now displays at a museum in Dover, Ohio.
   Playing in their father's workshop was perhaps the ultimate
childhood for train lovers like Warther and his sister. And he
remembers fondly that if, as sometimes happened, there was an
accident and something got broken, dad wasn't cross.
   His father believed that it took more energy to get mad than to
simply repair whatever damage had been done, said David Warther.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
