<FIRST>r p AM-VaGovernor     10-17 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Va Governor,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>NOW Tour Aimed at Coleman's Anti-Abortion Views</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Organization for Women
launched a tour this week to encourage women to vote for Democrat
L. Douglas Wilder for governor because of the anti-abortion views
of his Republican opponent.
   The involvement by NOW in the campaign between Wilder,
Virginia's lieutenant governor, and former Attorney General J.
Marshall Coleman reflects a turn in the contest during the past
couple of weeks to a focus on abortion.
   ``If we get illegal abortions in this country, women will die,''
said NOW President Molly Yard. ``We will never go back to the day
when abortions were illegal in this country.''
   NOW's ``Freedom Caravan for Women's Lives'' stopped Monday in
Newport News, in Frederickburg on Tuesday, Richmond on Wednesday
and Roanoke on Thursday.
   The NOW caravan comes on the heels of a newspaper and television
advertising campaign by the National Abortion Rights Action League,
which has targeted Coleman for defeat Nov. 7.
   Anti-abortion activists have been less visible in the campaign,
focusing instead on informing supporters about the candidates'
views and conducting occasional protests at abortion clinics.
However, some advertising has been used.
   ``We intend to be involved for Mr. Coleman,'' said David N.
O'Steen of the National Right to Life Committee. ``We just don't
discuss our strategy. ... We want to stay as flexible as possible.''
   Polls show that most Virginians have pro-choice views on
abortion.
   Wilder has endorsed parental consent when a minor seeks an
abortion but otherwise supports leaving unchanged Virginia's law,
which allows virtually unrestricted abortions in the first
trimester.
   Coleman opposes abortion except when the pregnant woman's life
is threatened but has said he would not ask the General Assembly to
adopt abortion restrictions.
   The abortion debate has all but overshadowed other issues in the
campaign, Wilder's bid to become the first elected black governor
of a U.S. state and Coleman's comeback effort from a 1981 defeat in
the race for governor against Democrat Charles S. Robb.
</TEXT>
