<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--Supercomputer-Cuts     10-17 0197</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Supercomputer-Cuts,0202</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foundation Says It Will Cut Funding for Princeton Supercomputer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRINCETON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Science Foundation said
Tuesday it is cutting off funding for Princeton University's
supercomputer center.
   The John von Neumann National Supercomputer Center, home of some
of the most technologically advanced computing devices in the
world, had expected to receive about $69 million over the next five
years.
   Cheryl Dybas, a spokeswoman for the foundation, said support is
being cut off because of the demise of ETA Systems Inc., the
Minnesota computer company that made a machine that is the heart of
the Princeton center.
   Doyle Knight, president of the Consortium for Scientific
Computing, which manages the center, told the The Star-Ledger of
Newark he received a telephone call Monday from the foundation,
informing him that federal funding for the center would be
terminated as of Sept. 30, 1990.
   Center officials have developed a new five-year plan using
equipment from another computer maker, and five members of a
seven-member foundation panel voted to recommend continued funding
after reviewing that plan, he said.
   The center has received about $44 million from the federal
science agency since it was founded five years ago.
</TEXT>
