<FIRST>r a AM-BeverlyHillsStrike     10-17 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Beverly Hills Strike,0260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teachers Strike for More Pay in Wealthy Beverly Hills</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Substitute teachers were hired to
keep classes open during the first teachers strike in this wealthy
city of movie stars, but some classrooms are in chaos.
   One class ordered pizzas Monday, the first day of the strike,
while other students sneaked off to go shopping. Some students in a
second-story classroom at Beverly ills High School hurled books,
papers and even a chair out a window.
   ``It's crazy, it's chaos, it's havoc,'' said junior Chris
Wegener, who left class to join his teachers _ and his mother, a
school counselor _ on the picket line.
   ``I have a feeling the substitute teacher is not going to make
it through the day,'' he said, describing how students were playing
football in his history classroom.
   All but 15 of the city's 300 teachers joined the strike,
affecting 4,700 students in one high school and four elementary
schools.
   Starting Beverly Hills teachers earn $21,604. Starting pay in
Los Angeles, where teachers won a 24 percent raise over three years
after a strike in May, is $27,346. Top scale for a Beverly Hills
teacher is $46,270.
   The district offered an 11 percent increase over two years. The
union wants an 18 percent over two years or 10.5 percent for 1989.
   The yearly after-tax household income in the city of about
33,000 people averages $122,003, according to Quinn-Brein
Communications, hired by the city to promote its diamond jubilee
earlier this year.
</TEXT>
