<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-89 1557EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-UNESCO     10-17 0530</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UNESCO,0548</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Agency Postpones PLO Request For Membership</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY DUNPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   UNESCO's General Conference on Tuesday postponed
the PLO's request for membership for two years, a move aimed in
part at persuading the United States to rejoin the U.N. agency.
   In return for agreeing to the postponement, the Palestine
Liberation Organization obtained assurances that UNESCO would
involve Palestinians in the Israeli-occupied territories more
closely in its activities.
   The decision by the United Nations Educational, Scientific and
Cultural Organization's highest decision-making body was taken by
consensus. The executive board called Oct. 11 for the postponement.
   Yacov Aviad, the Israeli representative to UNESCO, protested the
PLO membership request ``in the most vigorous terms'' and said it
would divert the organization from more pressing business.
   The head of the PLO observer mission, Omar Massalha, said his
group accepted the postponement ``in order to avoid a confrontation
or disruption that is not in UNESCO's interests.''
   The United States, which left UNESCO in 1985, had said admitting
Palestine as a member state would eliminate any chance of a U.S.
return.
   Massalha said if the PLO had lobbied to have the membership
application approved, it would have succeeded. Most UNESCO members
recognize the Palestinian state proclaimed by the PLO in November
1988.
   UNESCO has promised the Palestinians greater participation in
its educational and cultural programs in the West Bank and Gaza.
   At his opening speech to the month-long conference, Director
General Federico Mayor said he would never allow the organization
to be used for political purposes and vowed to work for ``freedom
of expression that does not have any limits.''
   The Spanish biochemist who took over the troubled agency two
years ago also said he wanted to see disparities between
industrialized and developing nations that threaten cultural
diversity ``grow smaller and eventually disappear.''
   In other business, the conference elected Malaysian Education
Minister Anwar Ibrahim as its chairman for the next two years and
admitted the Cook Islands and Kirbati in the Pacific as the 160th
and 161st members.
   The conference, which meets every two years, will adopt a plan
of activities for the first half of the 1990s and a program and
budget for the next two years.
   The United States and Britain left UNESCO in the mid-1980s
because they said the organization had become too politicized,
spent too much money and was poorly managed under Mayor's
predecessor, Amadou Mahtar M'Bow of Senegal.
   Singapore also withdrew, saying it could spend its dues better
elsewhere.
   Mayor hopes to end the decade-long controversy over the New
World Information and Communication Order, which communications
specialists say has been made obsolete by technological advances.
   Western governments and media organizations believe the new
order could lead to press censorship and licensing of journalists.
Developing countries said it was needed because Western media
reported about them unfairly and dominated information flows.
   In his speech, Mayor also appealed for the release of all
hostages, ``journalists or not, who have become pawns in an
intolerable bargaining.''
   This seemed a reference to American and British hostages held in
Lebanon, including Terry Anderson, the chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press, and British TV journalist
John McCarthy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891017-0142 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-89 1600EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Ivory     10-17 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ivory,0620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ivory Ban Approved After Bitter Fight</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Vanishing Ivory, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MORT ROSENBLUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAUSANNE, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An international group approved a
formal ban on ivory trade Tuesday after a long, bitter fight over
how best to save the last elephant herds still roaming wild in
Africa.
   The Convention on Trade in Endangered Species overrode
objections from southern African governments, which threatened to
find alternative channels for selling ivory tusks.
   ``This will be a great help,'' said Ian Douglas-Hamilton, a
Nairobi-based expert whose count of 609,000 is the widely accepted
estimate for African elephants, less than half the 1979 total.
   ``The African elephant is enormously better off today than it
was a year ago because of international action,'' he said.
``Unilateral import moratoriums in the United States and Europe are
already showing results.''
   But Wlliam Nduku, head of Zimbabwe's Parks and Wildlife
Department, called the vote a slap at the few countries which
successfully protect their elephants and count on revenue from
legal ivory sales.
   He said Zimbabwe might withdraw altogether from the convention,
known as CITES. Delegates from South Africa, Botswana, Burundi,
Mozambique and Malawi said their governments might file
reservations to the ban, allowing them to find buyers outside of
the convention.
   The compromise won preliminary approval Monday on a 76-11 vote
with four abstentions. The measure sets up a panel of experts to
consider whether countries with well-managed herds might continue
to trade legally in ivory.
   The measure places elephants on the convention's ``Appendix I,''
banning trade in elephant products. Members have 90 days to file
reservations, which means they consider their elephants to be
listed in ``Appendix II,'' which allows trade.
   Some objecting countries said they would organize a ``Southern
African Center for Ivory Marketing'' in Botswana to sell ivory
taken from culled elephants.
   South Africa also might market its ivory through the center,
overcoming political differences with its frontline neighbors.
   ``For us, Appendix I is a dead end. Once our elephants are
listed on it we will never get them off,'' said Pieter Mulder,
chief of the South African delegation. He said South Africa will
accept a two-year moratorium on ivory sales until the next meeting
of the convention but objected to a ban.
   Countries insisting on a ban, including Kenya, Tanzania and the
United States, argue that any legal trade would open loopholes and
encourage poaching in critical areas.
   Japan, which has consumed 40 percent of world ivory exports,
made no immediate comment. Although Japan temporarily banned
imports last month, it could file a reservation and buy southern
African ivory.
   ``This vote was a crushing blow to the ivory market which is the
critical factor in the fate of the elephants,'' said Craig van Note
of the Washington-based Monitor Consortium, a network of
environmentalist groups. ``Now all nations and citizens must reject
any product made from ivory.''
   The long dispute left Africans split and in some cases bitter.
   ``Imagine a situation where Trinidad and Tobago are deciding the
fate of African elephants,'' said Rowan Martin, director of
research in Zimbabwe's wildlife department.
   In South Africa, John Ledger of the private Endangered Wildlife
Trust urged South Africa to renounce all ivory sales.
   ``The ivory trade is rotten to the core,'' he said a statement
from Johannesburg.
   ``By continuing to trade in ivory, South Africa finds itself in
the company of ruthless poachers, smugglers and criminals who will
kill the last elephant in Africa to satisfy their greed.''
   Ivory is highly valued for its use in the signature stamps
popular in many Asian nations and for jewelry, piano keys and
carvings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
