<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon-Palestinians     10-17 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Palestinians,0483</SECOND>
<HEAD>Third PLO Guerrilla Killed in 8 Days</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SIDON, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A PLO guerrilla was shot and killed in a
southern Palestinian refugee camp before dawn Tuesday, the third
such killing in eight days, prompting residents to go on strike.
   Armed guerrillas loyal to PLO chairman Yasser Arafat swooped
through the narrow alleys of Ein el-Hilweh after the shooting by
unidentified assailants.
   Munir Saadi, a corporal with the PLO's military police in the
densely populated shantytown, was shot in the head shortly before
sunrise, said a police spokesman who cannot be identified in line
with regulations.
   Witnesses said pro-Arafat guerrillas fired their automatic
rifles in the air in a traditional expression of anger and they
shouted slogans blaming the killing on ``agents of Israel.''
   Brig. Wajih Abu Ali, commander of the Palestine Liberation
Organization's military police in the camp on the eastern edge of
Sidon, a southern port city, blamed the killing on ``a terrorist
and criminal faction'' which he did not identify.
   Saadi's assassination came one week after unidentified
assailants gunned down Palestinian physician Ali Hashem in Ein
El-Hilweh.
   Hashem, a member of Arafat's Fatah guerrilla group, was very
popular among the camp's 50,000 refugees. He was killed one day
after gunmen shot and killed a follower of Palestinian terrorist
mastermind Abu Nidal in the camp.
   Abu Nidal's Fatah-Revolutionary Council group identified its
dead official only by his code name Sadeq and said in a statement
he was also killed by ``agents of Israel.''
   Abu Nidal, whose real name is Sabri al-Banna, broke away from
Arafat's Fatah in 1973 and founded his own faction, basing it in
the Syrian capital of Damascus. His group, bankrolled by Libya, has
been blamed for a series of terrorist activities, including the
December 1985 attacks on Vienna and Rome airports.
   PLO spokesmen and Lebanese police have also blamed Abu Nidal's
group for the abduction in Sidon Oct. 6 of Emmanuel Christen and
Elio Erriquez, two Swiss citizens working for the Swiss-based
International Committee of the Red Cross.
   The Red Cross representative in Sidon, Roland Sidler, discussed
the abduction with pro-Iranian clergyman Sheik Maher Hammoud in
Sidon.
   ``We denounce the abduction which targeted two people working
for a humanitarian organization that helps the Lebanese people,''
Hammoud said after the meeting.
   Hammoud is one of a few Sunni Moslem clergymen cooperating with
the Shiite Moslem, Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, which
is believed to be the umbrella for the underground pro-Iranian
factions holding 18 Westerners hostage.
   Sidler's organization said its orthopedic center in the southern
provincial capital has failed to provide 81 amputees with
artificial limbs because of the abduction of Christen and Erriquez.
The Red Cross suspended work at the orthopedic center after the two
were abducted.
   There has been no authenticated claim of responsibility for
their kidnapping.
</TEXT>
