<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Rabies     10-17 0135</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Rabies,0137</SECOND>
<UNK>Bat-borne Rabies Kills 23 in Peruvian Jungle</UNK>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An outbreak of rabies spread by bats has
killed 23 people in the southeastern jungle, and health officials
are worried more will die if they don't receive an anti-rabies
vaccine.
   Regional Health director Nazario Flores was quoted in the Lima
newspaper Expreso as saying he has asked the government to send 300
doses of vaccine to treat people who have been bitten by bats near
the jungle city of Puerto Maldonado, 690 miles southeast of Lima.
   He said most of the 23 who died are from the mining camp of
Choque, 100 miles east of Puerto Maldonado, and many people have
fled the camp out of fear.
   Flores said at least 100 people are being treated for bat bites
in Choque.
