<FIRST>r a AM-Nielsens     10-17 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nielsens,0587</SECOND>
<HEAD>ABC's World Series Coverage Ends NBC's Winning Streak</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ABC put an end to NBC's long domination of
the ratings with its broadcasts of the first two games of the San
Francisco Bay-area World Series.
   NBC fell behind ABC in the Nielsen ratings for the week ended
Oct. 15 after an unprecedented winning streak of 68 weeks. In all,
NBC has been the No. 1 network for four years.
   Neither Saturday's game nor Sunday's game between the San
Francisco Giants and the Oakland Athletics was in the Top 10. In
fact, neither won its time period. But they had enough viewers to
to put ABC into first place.
   ABC won the A.C. Nielsen Co. survey with an average of 14.8. NBC
was second with 13.9 and CBS third with 12.5, according to CBS.
ABC's interpretation of the ratings gave NBC 13.8 and NBC gave
itself 14.0. A ratings point represents the percentage of the 92.1
million television homes. A share is the percentage of the sets in
use.
   The raw data is provided by Nielsen and then interpreted by the
networks. The networks generally agree on their interpretations,
but figures can vary when programs such as ball games run live in
prime time in one part of the country and in fringe time in another
part of the country.
   ``I'm sorry it's come to an end,'' Brandon Tartikoff, president
if NBC Entertainment, said in an earlier interview, ``but I hope we
start a new streak soon.''
   ABC's ``Roseanne'' was the top-rated show of the week and the
network had three other series in the Top 10. NBC had five shows at
the top and CBS had one.
   Saturday's opening game of the World Series was tied for 18th
place with ABC's ``Doogie Howser, M.D.'' The Sunday game was 16th.
   It appeared likely that ABC also would win the current week with
additional Series games.
   Here are the Top 10: ABC's ``Roseanne;'' NBC's ``The Cosby
Show;'' NBC's ``Cheers;'' NBC's ``A Different World;'' ABC's ``The
Wonder Years;'' ABC's ``Who's the Boss?;'' NBC's ``The Golden
Girls;'' CBS' ``Murder, She Wrote;'' ABC's ``Chicken Soup,'' and
NBC's ``Dear John.''
   ``Chicken Soup'' is the highest-rated new show, and ABC's
``Doogie Howser, M.D.,'' tied at 18th place with Saturday's World
Series game, was second. ``Doogie Howser'' is the first series from
producer-creator Steven Bochco's multi-series deal with ABC.
   NBC's ``Mancuso, FBI,'' the last new series to premiere, was in
56th place.
   Here's how other new shows are doing: CBS' ``Major Dad,'' 32nd;
ABC's ``Family Matters,'' 36th; CBS' ``Rescue: 911,'' 45th; CBS'
``Island Son,'' 47th; CBS' ``People Next Door,'' 52nd; ABC's
``Young Riders,'' 55th; NBC's ``Nutt House,'' 58th; ABC's ``Life
Goes On,'' 59th; NBC's ``Hardball,'' 60th; NBC's ``Baywatch,''
NBC's ``Sister Kate,'' and CBS' ``Wolf'' in a tie with NBC's
``Quantum Leap'' for 61st; CBS' ``Top of the Hill,'' 65th; ABC's
``PrimeTime Live,'' 66th; CBS' ``Peaceable Kingdom,'' 72nd; and
CBS' ``Snoops,'' 73rd.
   Fox Broadcasting Co.'s ``Married ... With Children'' remained
its highest-rated show, in 51st place.
   ABC had the highest-rated evening news show. The ratings: ABC
9.9, CBS 9.3, NBC 9.0.
   CBS' ``Saturday Night with Connie Chung'' was the lowest-rated
show among the three networks.
   Here are the bottom five programs among the three networks:
NBC's ``Magical World of Disney,'' CBS' ``Peaceable Kingdom,'' CBS'
``Snoops,'' ``CBS' ``Tour of Duty'' and CBS' ``Saturday Night with
Connie Chung.''
</TEXT>
