<FIRST>r a AM-CorvetteContest     10-17 0209</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Corvette Contest,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>New York Carpenter Wins 36 Corvettes</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA11 of Oct. 16</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CULVER CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Millions of drivers, young and old,
have dreamed of owning a Corvette in the years since the car was
introduced in 1953.
   That dream came true for Dennis Amodeo _ 36 times over.
   The 33-year-old carpenter from Huntington Station, N.Y., learned
Saturday that he won VH-1's grand prize: one Corvette for each year
the car has been manufactured.
   ``I've always told myself: `Before I die, I'll have one,'''
Amodeo said Monday night at a reception at the Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer
offices in Culver City.
   Amodeo plans to hold on to the Corvette collection, worth an
estimated $1 million, although insurance costs could exceed the
cars' value.
   ``I'd like to try to keep them,'' he said. ``For now, I'll try
to find a way to get them back'' to his home.
   About 2.2 million people entered the contest sponsored by VH-1,
the soft-rock music video cable channel operated by MTV Networks,
said Jim Cahill, a VH-1 executive.
   The success of the contest was due to the enduring popularity of
the Corvette, Cahill said. ``I can't think of another product which
has inspired as many people in the postwar era than the Corvette.''
</TEXT>
