<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-89 1612EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Baysball Bjt   10-17 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baysball, Bjt,0555</SECOND>
<HEAD>No Dancing In The Streets _ Yet _ For Baysball Fans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANTHONY MARQUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Everyone is supposed to love a parade. But
baseball fans in Oakland and San Francisco have to ponder whether
they can love a victory parade on the other side of the eight-mile
Bay Bridge.
   Fans of the Oakland Athletics weren't dancing in the streets
Tuesday just because their American League champion team was ahead
2-0 in the World Series going into the night game here. Not after
last year, when the A's post-season swagger was humbled by the Los
Angeles Dodgers.
   ``We expected to win last year, and so there is a little more
cautious approach this year,'' said Sonny M. Ismail, who works for
the Port of Oakland. ``Just from observation, everything's very
quiet on the streets.''
   A taste of defeat also hampered the enthusiasm of San Francisco
fans, who had been ecstatic over the Giants' first appearance in a
World Series since 1962.
   ``My heart is with the Giants,'' said Robin O'Donnell, who works
in San Francisco's financial district and acknowledged Tuesday that
the odds didn't look good for a comeback.
   ``I don't like it, but I'm not a worrier,'' said O'Donnell, who
plans to attend all the series games at Candlestick Park this week.
``We've come back from worse situations than this.''
   Both cities have made their parade plans. But until the victory
fireworks, the most colorful signs of team pride are the green A's
flags that adorn streetlights and insignias of the team that can be
seen in the windows of most restaurants in Oakland.
   ``Oakland's been real reserved this year,'' said Tim Gallen, of
Celebrate Oakland, a group leading a promote-Oakland campaign.
``Basically, what's happening is everyone's just waiting to erupt.''
   Some fans have divided loyalties, so a hot souvenir item has
been a baseball cap that has the Giants logo on one side and the
A's insignia on the other.
   CalTrans, the state transportation agency, tried a similar
approach on a grander scale. It put up small Giants banners along
the Bay Bridge route into San Francisco and A's flags along the
bridge heading eastbound, into Oakland.
   Civic boosters say the game they are calling Baysball is a
no-lose situation for the area.
   ``I think they're representing the whole Bay area,'' said Lyle
Gordan, a worker at Cost Plus Nursery in Oakland, where he said
nearly all his customers are talking about the two ballclubs.
   Of course, there are always people who don't care about
baseball, even amid a World Series.
   While diehard fans were attending Game 2, or watching on the
252-square-foot television screen at Jack London Square in Oakland,
Marjorie Fishkin was huddled in a wool coat and scarf in a line to
see the new Woody Allen movie, ``Crimes and Misdemeanors.''
   ``Woody Allen is a genius, and I'm not interested in baseball,''
she said.
   Darryl Lindsey of Oakland acknowledged he's not much of a
baseball fan either, and being originally from Los Angeles, he
hasn't followed the A's much.
   But if they do win the World Series, Lindsey said he intends to
be at the victory parade, ``just to be able to say I was there.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
