<FIRST>u i AM-Sudan-Families 1stLd-Writethru a0629 10-17 0549</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan-Families, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0629,0561</SECOND>
<HEAD>Relatives of Terrorist Victims to Decide on Death Penalty</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf `Rocker said ...' with one graf to CORRECT second
reference to Rockett. Picks up graf 8 pvs, `The Palestinians ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMED OSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Sudanese court is asking the families
of seven victims of a terrorist gang's bomb to decide whether the
five Palestinians convicted in the attack should live or die.
   Among the victims were a British couple and their two children,
whose relatives are Quakers opposed to the death penalty.
   But contrary to a statement last month by an appeals court, they
and the parents of a fifth British victim, a teacher for a relief
agency, say they have not agreed to pardon the bombers.
   The five Britons and two Sudanese died in May 1988 when a bomb
blew the roof off a Khartoum hotel dining room where the British
victims and one of the Sudanese were having dinner. The other
Sudanese victim was a waiter.
   Dinah Rolfe, whose son, daughter-in-law and two grandchildren
died in the blast, said in Britain that she and her husband,
Edward, do not want the killers executed. But she added: ``We don't
think it's sensible to let them go free so that they can kill
again.''
   Ken Rockett, a retired music teacher whose daughter was killed,
said killing the terrorists would make them ``martyrs in their own
country.''
   Rockett said he had ``no desire to see them killed'' but added:
``It is a terrible crime and should be punished.''
   The Palestinians were caught after the bombing and a
simultaneous machine gun attack on a nearby private club restricted
to citizens of Commonwealth nations.
   They told investigators they were avenging the April 1988
assassination by Israeli commandos of Khalil Wazir, also known as
Abu Jihad, who was military commander of the Palestine Liberation
Organization.
   A year ago, the Palestinians were convicted of bombing and
illegal possession of arms, and were sentenced to hang.
   The official Sudan News Agency this week quoted a judiciary
source as saying the Court of Appeal has asked the government to
notify families of the victims to appear Jan. 3 and say whether
they want the sentence carried out.
   At issue is a stipulation of Sudan's Islamic law, or Sharia,
that came into effect with a recent appeals court order changing
the assassination conviction to premeditated murder.
   As Islamic law, based on the Moslems' holy book the Koran and
pronouncements of the Prophet Mohammed, does not deal with the
political crime of assassination.
   But the Sharia decrees that the family of a murder victim can
decide whether the convicted person should be executed, made to pay
restitution and be pardoned or be pardoned outright.
   Sudan News Agency said it was told that the court will order the
five Palestinians executed if the families do not appear at its
January hearing. The agency's source did not say what would happen
if families disagree on the fate of the defendants.
   When the Court of Appeal amended the charge, it said relatives
of Christopher Rolfe, who was killed, had pardoned the
perpetrators. In addition to Rolfe, the British victims were his
wife, Clare; their children, Thomas, 3, and Louise, 1; and Sally
Rockett, a teacher.
</TEXT>
