<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-89 1919EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p AM-NJGovernor-Trooper     10-17 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NJ Governor-Trooper,0537</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parents Outraged Over Courter Ads About Their Son's Slaying</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JO ASTRID GLADING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROSELLE PARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The parents of a slain state trooper
say the Republican candidate for governor's campaign ignored their
wishes by invoking their son's name and using film of his funeral
in a commercial.
   ``They won't even let him rest in peace. That's all we want _
for him to rest in peace,'' Grace Lamonaco said in an interview
Monday. ``What kind of person could exploit a picture of a
funeral?''
   The 30-second television commercial for Republican James Courter
features a photograph of Philip Lamonaco, footage from his 1981
Christmas Eve funeral, and a brief interview with his widow, Donna.
   The widow urges viewers to support Courter on grounds that he
will pursue a stronger death penalty. She criticizes Democrat James
Florio for being satisfied with the existing death penalty law.
   The Lamonacos said the ad has reopened the wound of their son's
slaying. They said the Courter campaign knew they objected and say
their wishes should have been respected regardless of the
willingness of their daughter-in-law to appear in the ad.
   ``If it wasn't for the commercial, we wouldn't be going through
all this again,'' said Joseph Lamonaco, breaking into tears during
the interview at the couple's home. ``How can they bring something
like this up in a political campaign?''
   Ken Connolly, Courter's campaign manager, said Courter was not
told of the parents' objections.
   They parents also said the commercial is misleading because it
implies that their son's killers were spared the death penalty
because of a flaw in the law. The capital punishment law was not
enacted until 1982 _ a year after his slaying.
   Donna Lamonaco wrote a letter on pink stationery on behalf of
Courter during last spring's primary election. His campaign sent
the letter to thousands of Republican voters in a mailing that
included a snapshot of the dead trooper.
   When Lamonaco's parents heard of the letter, they called Courter
and told Connolly they did not want their son's name exploited for
political purposes.
   ``I thought he was going to be enough of a gentleman to stop
with the pictures. Then to jump on pictures of the funeral for
God's sake. How cold-hearted can you be?'' said Grace Lamonaco.
   Connolly said deciding whether to tape the commercial against
the parents' wishes was difficult. He said the failure of the
campaign to call the parents and warn them of the commercial was
``an oversight on my part.''
   Donna Lamonaco did not return a message left with the Courter
campaign. She has an unlisted telephone number. The campaign and
her family refused to give it out.
   Lamonaco was shot on Interstate 80. After a three-year manhunt,
police captured self-avowed revolutionaries Thomas Manning and
Richard Williams and charged them with the slaying. Manning was
convicted, but the jury was unable to reach a verdict on Williams
and he is to be retried.
   Courter is running an uphill battle against Florio in the race
to succeed Republican Gov. Thomas Kean. Recent polls show Florio
ahead by 14 to 23 percentage points.
</TEXT>
