<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-89 1931EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-MooseDead     10-17 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Moose Dead,0556</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hunter Charged For Shooting Moose _ In Iowa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNDERWOOD, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A moose that caught the fancy of Iowans
as it wandered southward for weeks, hundreds of miles south of its
normal range, has been killed by a hunter who claimed self defense.
   ``Everyone is appalled that the moose was shot because everyone
has been watching him from day one,'' Doug Clayton, a conservation
officer for the state Department of Natural Resources, said Tuesday.
   The moose had been wandering southward through Iowa since first
being seen Sept. 22 near Sheldon. The moose's wanderings had taken
him to downtown Cherokee and into many Iowa corn fields.
   Michael Scott Wiggins, 27, of Underwood, was cited Tuesday in
Pottawattamie County District Court for shooting an animal out of
season _ there are normally no moose in Iowa and therefore no
hunting season _ and having a center-fire rifle in his possession
during a deer hunting season restricted to muzzle-loading guns.
   Both citations are simple misdemeanors with a maximum penalty of
$100 fine or 30 days in jail, said Assistant County Attorney Tim
Markel. The state will also seek $1,000 in damages, he said.
Arraignment was set for Oct. 20.
   Wiggins, who notified Iowa Department of Natural Resources
officials about the shooting Sunday, said he encountered the bull
moose in a soybean field east of Underwood, about 10 miles northest
of Council Bluffs in southwestern Iowa, Clayton said.
   Clayton investigated the shooting and said he is skeptical about
Wiggins' claim that he shot the moose after it charged him.
   ``He said the moose was charging north to south, but we found
moose tracks going east to west,'' Clayton said. He also said the
animal had not been killed with ``head-on shots.''
   Clayton said Wiggins told him he had been hunting for a coyote
with his .270-caliber Magnum rifle in his father's soybean field
when he looked up and saw the moose charging him.
   Richard McGeough, chief of the department's enforcement bureau,
said he also found it hard to accept Wiggins' explanation.
   ``These animals routinely travel through the state, and people
line up on the highways and gawk and take pictures,'' he said.
``And of all these reports, the people who shoot the moose are the
only ones who say the moose charged them.''
   Only three other moose, all bulls, have been reported in the
state in the last dozen years. Their natural habitat is about 400
miles north of Iowa, in the lakes and forests of northern
Minnesota. Underwood is about 150 south of the Minnesota state line.
   Wiggins could not be reached for comment; there was no answer at
his father's house.
   Officials said the moose would be stuffed and used in an
educational display at the Springbrook State Park north of Guthrie
Center.
   State wildlife specialist Lee Gladfelder said the best theory is
that the wandering bulls lost a contest for mating rights and were
rejected by the rest of the herd.
   But why some of the beasts travel south is a mystery, he said.
Of the other three moose in Iowa, one was shot by a farmer who was
fined for killing a protected animal, one died of natural causes
and one wandered on to Missouri and disappeared.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
