<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-89 1933EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Cavazos-Choice     10-17 0630</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cavazos-Choice,0644</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cavazos' Choice Pitch Gets Tangled in East Harlem School Funding
Woes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE MITGANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's education secretary said Tuesday
that letting parents pick their child's school is the ``cornerstone
of education reform.'' But East Harlem parents and a state educator
told him ``choice is not enough.''
   Education Secretary Lauro F. Cavazos was in the city's East
Harlem neighborhood to lavish praise on its impoverished school
district which has gained fame for transforming crowded schools
into 52 smaller magnet schools aimed at providing educational
options.
   But the choice-in-education message Cavazos hoped to convey in
the first stop of a five-city road show became mired in politics as
parents demanded an explanation for the loss of $1.4 million in
federal magnet funds for their district _ the very funds designed
to encourage the choice programs Cavazos was praising.
   At a 2{-hour meeting Monday night at Intermediate School 117,
parents told Cavazos and city and state education officials that
choice without adequate funding holds only hollow promise for
improving schools.
   ``The irony is that we're celebrating choice at a time when
we're in a crisis in this district. Instead of increased support,
we're getting less support,'' said Ray Rivera, who has two children
in the district's schools.
   At Tuesday's concluding session, some speakers stressed that
expanding parental choice alone would not cure school ills.
   ``At the risk of being branded an infidel, choice is not
enough,'' said New York State Education Commissioner Thomas Sobol.
``Adequate resources need to be provided. When the average
elementary class size in New York City is 28, and outside the city
it is 22, the quality of choice outside the city is likely to be
greater. And that has to end.''
   New Jersey Gov. Thomas Kean, who delivered one of the final
speeches of the conference, said: ``Choice isn't the be all and end
all. But there are too many schools that just don't work. Choice is
the passageway to get from the schools of today to the schools of
tomorrow.''
   Cavazos himself said choice was just ``one of the strategies''
needed. But he later told reporters: ``Choice by itself is a
stimulus. It creates competitive interaction.''
   President Bush has called choice ``the single most promising
idea'' in education today. He and others argue that if parents are
given the chance to choose schools, the resulting competition will
improve education everywhere.
   At Tuesday's session, an East Harlem group called ``Parents For
Choice'' distributed leaflets saying they had been told by
Education Department officials that the district's magnet fund
grant proposal ``was weak and inadequate and therefore funds were
not provided this year.''
   The district had received federal magnet grants the last two
years. Without those funds, district officials have said 30
teaching and other staff jobs are in jeopardy.
   Education Undersecretary Ted Sanders told reporters that the
quality of magnet fund applications has improved making competition
stiffer and that Congress wants preference given to new applicants.
   Lon Anderson, a spokesman for the department, said Cavazos had
nothing to do with awarding grants and the rejection of East
Harlem's bid ``was absolutely no reflection on the quality of
education programs in the district.''
   Cavazos's visit was the first of five regional meetings on
parental choice planned by the Bush administration. The other
scheduled stops are in Minneapolis-St. Paul, Oct. 23-24; Charlotte,
N.C., Nov. 13-14; Denver, Nov. 16-17; and Richmond, Calif., Nov.
28-29.
   In 1972, East Harlem's Community School District 4 ranked last
among the city's 32 local school districts in standardized test
scores, and only 15 percent were reading at grade level. Today,
with parents able to choose among 52 magnet schools, 66 percent are
reading at grade level and the district's citywide rank has
improved to 16th.
</TEXT>
