<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-89 1648EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-Korea     10-17 0659</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Korea,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush, South Korean Leader Discuss U.S. Troops, Trade</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush promised anew Tuesday to help
defend South Korea against its communist neighbor. He also nudged
President Roh Tae Woo to open South Korea's markets wider to
American competition.
   The two leaders concluded 2{-hours of meetings and a luncheon at
the White House with pledges to keep U.S. troops there to help
maintain peace on the Korean peninsula.
   Bush pledged, ``our forces will remain as long as there is a
threat from the North.'' He also applauded Roh's ``creative
diplomacy'' in proposing to create a commonwealth between North and
South Korea ``as a step toward reunification.''
   On trade, the thorniest issue between the two allies, Bush said,
``South Korea is now the world's 10th largest trading nation and
America's seventh largest trading partner.
   ``Korean workers and companies have benefited from U.S. open
markets, but American workers and companies deserve equal access to
Korean markets,'' Bush said at the ceremony in the East Room, with
their wives and top Cabinet members standing nearby.
   Roh, speaking through an interpreter, said: ``I emphasized to
President Bush that in spite of many domestic difficulties, the
Korean government, with strong faith in free and fair trade, has
been moving toward economic liberalization and market opening.''
   What had been scheduled as a 10-minute private meeting between
the two leaders lasted 40 minutes, and they spent another 30
minutes with Cabinet officials and top aides before a working
luncheon.
   Richard Solomon, an assistant secretary of state who briefed
reporters afterwards, said that at one point, Roh used the
``analogy that if an apple is picked before it is ripe, it can be a
bit tough and sour. When it's ripe, however, it's nice and sweet.''
   But Bush rejoined, ``We don't want the ripening to take so long
that we're too old to enjoy the food.''
   Solomon said Roh ``indicated that he will continue to
liberalize,'' with a goal of making South Korea's market as open by
the mid-1990s as markets are now in the major Western industrial
nations.
   Roh also noted that the U.S. trade deficit with South Korea was
down in August by a third from last year's level.
   Bush ``indicated his hopes for rapid progress in the areas of
telecommunications and implementation of intellectual property
rights,'' Solomon said.
   Asked about the prospects for getting more U.S. agricultural
goods into South Korea, Solomon said, ``That's an area where it may
take _ from the Korean perspective _ a little longer for the apple
to ripen.''
   Bush said ``the division of Korea is merely a part of a great
divide between all the nations of the world.''
   Roh said both he and Bush ``shared the view that a new breeze of
reform and openness currently blowing ... (is) spreading freedom in
the socialist world.''
   ``We noted the stark reality, however, that despite this
encouraging trend of change, confrontation and tension have not
abated on the Korean Peninsula,'' said Roh.
   Talk of a reduced U.S. military deployment has become more
commonplace as South Korea becomes more prosperous and the Soviet
Union appears less menacing than before. Moscow has close links to
Seoul's arch-rival, North Korea.
   South Korea has made strides toward democracy in the past two
years, but human rights groups claim there has been an increase in
repression lately. Roh has defended the arrest of several hundred
dissidents in recent months, saying they had violated the law.
   Six anti-American radicals staged a bold attack on the U.S.
ambassador's residence in Seoul last week.
   The White House was ringed with police as several dozen young
Koreans demonstrated in nearby Lafayette Park in protest of the Roh
visit.
   Bush met with Roh in Seoul last February, a month after Bush's
inauguration. Roh will have breakfast with Vice President Dan
Quayle before addressing a joint session of Congress Wednesday. His
five-day visit to the United States ends Thursday.
</TEXT>
