<FIRST>r w AM-ImmigrantNurses     10-17 0145</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Immigrant Nurses,130</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bill Would Give Foreign Nurses Resident Status</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House on Tuesday approved a bill that
would give permanent resident status to registered nurses who would
otherwise be forced to return to their native countries, including
thousands to the Philippines.
   The bill, approved by voice vote and sent to the Senate, would
exempt the nurses from the ceilings on visa allotments because of
the current shortage of nurses in this country.
   To be covered by the bill, a person would have to prove he or
she was employed as a nurse for at least three years in the United
States, entered the country before Sept. 1, and was employed as a
nurse on the date of the bill's enactment.
   The bill also includes a pilot program for admission of
additional foreign nurses needed for hospitals and other health
facilities.
</TEXT>
