<HEAD>Dow Falls Again, Stocks Retreat After Two Wild Sessions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs to UPDATE with closing Dow average, delete
trade figures as cause because of conflicting theories. Picks up 3rd graf,
`The closely...'. SUBS 11th graf, `In the...', with two grafs to UPDATE
with market detail. Picks up 12th graf pvs, `Monday's rally....'. A version
moved on financial wires. ^LaserPhoto NY5; LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks prices retreated today following two of
the wildest sessions on Wall Street since the October 1987 market
crash.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks fell 18.65 points
to 2,638.73 after being down as much as 63 points around 11:30 a.m.
Broader market indicators also fell.
   The closely watched Dow had ended a volatile day of trading
Monday with a gain of 88.12 points, or 3.4 percent, at 2,657.38 _
the fourth-biggest point rise on record. Volume was the
fourth-largest in history, with 416.29 million shares changing hand.
   The Monday rally erased about half of Friday's 190.58-point
plunge, the worst decline since the Black Monday crash of Oct. 19,
1987.
   The Commerce Department reported today that the nation's trade
shortfall increased to $10.77 billion in August, up 30.77 percent
from a revised July deficit of $8.24 billion. Many economists had
expected the deficit to be about $9 billion.
   Larry Wachtel, a vice president at Prudential-Bache Securities
Inc., attributed today's retreat largely to concerns that the U.S.
trade deficit was worsening and could lead to higher interest rates.
   But not all analysts agreed that the trade deficit was a major
factor in today's decline. Some noted that bonds and the dollar _
which are most sensitive to bad trade figures _ held up relatively
well.
   The dollar recovered after a sharp drop that followed the trade
report, while bonds were mixed _ an indication that investors were
not seriously worried about worsening inflation and higher interest
rates.
   The Federal Reserve injected $1.5 billion into the banking
system today after adding $2 billion in reserves on Monday.
   Banks will be able to use the new reserves to come to the
assistance of brokerage firms caught in a cash squeeze because of
the drop in stock prices.
   Traders were worried about the outlook for the
employee-management buyout proposal for the parent of United
Airlines. The stock fell another $25.67{ a share to $197.25 after
tumbling about $57 a share Monday, and that contributed to the
overall market weakness.
   In the overall New York Stock Exchange today, declining issues
outpaced advances by almost 3 to 2. Volume totaled a
heavier-than-usual 224.07 million shares, with the heaviest action
in the early going.
   Monday's rally was concentrated in blue-chip stocks, which
benefited from a ``flight to quality'' among nervous investors
while many smaller issues continued to lose ground.
   Declining issues outnumbered advancing ones by a 5-to-4 margin
on the New York Stock Exchange. Indexes of the American Stock
Exchange and over-the-counter stocks fell.
   Friday's plunge had raised fears of a repeat of Oct. 19, 1987,
when a Friday decline turned into a Monday rout that knocked a
record 508 points off the Dow average. That did not turn out to be
the case.
   Stocks rallied today in Tokyo in response to Wall Street's
strength of Monday, but London's market lost ground in sympathy
with today's weakness on the New York Stock Exchange.
   In Tokyo, where Tuesday trading ended before New York opened for
business, the Nikkei average jumped 527.39 points, or 1.5 percent,
to 34,996.08. It was the second-biggest gain this year and erased
most of Monday's 647.33-point decline.
   In London, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index
fell 27.9 points, or more than 1 percent, to close at 2,135.5.
   Traders said the stock market benefited from the experience
gained in the 1987 crash. The New York Stock Exchange managed to
handle the heavy volume because of a big investment in technology
made after Black Monday 1987.
   In addition, traders were soothed by a promise during the
weekend by the Federal Reserve to supply fresh money to the
financial system if necessary to make sure banks kept loans flowing
to traders who lost money.
   It turned out that little Fed action was necessary.
   Turmoil continued in the airline sector. Donald Trump announced
he was withdrawing his $7 billion bid for AMR Corp., parent of
American Airlines, after the company's stock fall. He said he would
consider making a lower offer.
   It was a failure to obtain financing for an employee-management
buyout of United Airlines parent UAL Corp. that sparked Friday's
plunge. A spokesman for British Airways, which is backing the
buyout group, said the group planned to pursue a takeover, although
the terms of the deal were under review.
</TEXT>
