<FIRST>u w AM-US-Turkey     10-17 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Turkey,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Committee Commemorates Armenian Massacre</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Judiciary Committee voted Tuesday
to commemorate the massacre of more than a million Armenians 75
years ago, approving a resolution sure to anger Turkey and the Bush
administration.
   Before passing the measure on an 8-6 vote, the panel rejected an
effort by Sen. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, to soften its language by
eliminating the word ``genocide.''
   Metzenbaum said he offered his substitute at the suggestion of
Brent Scowcroft, the president's national security adviser.
Scowcroft met Monday with Sen. Bob Dole, R-Kan., the resolution's
sponsor, to discuss the issue.
   The Dole measure would set April 24, 1990, to memorialize the
1.5 million Armenians who were killed between 1915 and 1923 during
the Ottoman Empire.
   The Bush administration, concerned that the resolution could
damage relations between the United States and Turkey, lobbied
behind the scenes to defeat the measure, even bringing back the
U.S. ambassador to work against it.
   Publicly, however, the State Department took no position on the
resolution.
   President Bush found himself in a jam over the resolution
because he had voiced support for language marking the ``Armenian
genocide'' during the 1988 campaign.
   The measure, which now goes to the Senate floor, aroused strong
feelings among Americans of Turkish and Armenian ancestry.
   ``I became the focal point for the greatest lobbying campaign
I've experienced in a long while,'' said Sen. Alan Simpson, R-Wyo.
   Metzenbaum suggested replacing the word genocide with a
``national day of remembrance'' for Armenians.
   Genocide means a ``deliberate and systematic'' elimination of a
racial group, he said. ``I don't think that's really what occurred
here.'' Some historians have rejected the idea of a genocide.
   But Sen. Joe Biden, D-Del., chairman of the Judiciary Committee,
said, ``The only debate is whether it was attempted genocide or
genocide.''
   And Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill., said ``people were massacred
because of their ancestry,'' in the Ottoman Empire.
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, failed in his attempt to transfer the
resolution to the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, saying the
Judiciary Committee did not have the expertise to understand the
foreign policy ramifications of the measure.
   The Turkish government had strongly opposed the resolution,
believing it was tantamount to comparing that nation's history to
Nazi Germany.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
