<FIRST>u i AM-UN-Soviet-Israel     10-17 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Soviet-Israel,0461</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Abstain on Seating Israel, Still Oppose Its Mideast Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The Soviet Union abstained Tuesday on the
annual vote to seat Israel, instead of opposing it as usual, but
tempered the sign of better relations by repeating its disapproval
of Israeli policy in the Middle East.
   It was the first time since 1982 the Soviets did not join Arab
nations in voting to reject Israel's credentials for the 159-member
General Assembly. Israel has been U.N. member since the Jewish
state was founded in 1948.
   The vote in the assembly was 95-37 to seat Israel, with 15
abstentions and 12 nations not voting. Last year's vote was 95-41,
with seven abstentions and 16 absent.
   Credentials of all nations must be approved each year and the
annual challenge to Israel has become a ritual.
   Although the Kremlin did not support Israel, the changed vote
was considered a victory for the Israelis and a setback for the
Arabs.
   Soviet Ambassador Alexander M. Belonogov said later his
government had given ``a signal to the government of Israel that it
is high time to listen to the world community'' and heed U.N.
resolutions on the Middle East.
   ``The ball is in Israel's court and it is up to them to make
their assessement and take certain concrete decisions,'' he said.
   Belonogov said dropping opposition to Israel's credentials did
not mean a change in Soviet views on Israel's Middle East policy or
presage resumption of the diplomatic relations severed in the 1967
Middle East war.
   Israeli ``intransigence'' in Middle East peace efforts and its
refusal to talk to the Palestine Liberation Organization make
resumption of formal ties impossible despite warmer unofficial
relations, he said.
   Israeli diplomats had said the Soviet vote would be a test of
its intention to improve relations and play a constructive role in
the Middle East peace process.
   Byelorussia and the Ukraine, the Soviet Union's other two votes
in the General Assembly, joined the switch. Turkey, which abstained
last year, supported Israel in Tuesday's vote.
   Ambassador Johanan Bein of Israel called the Soviet change of
heart ``a move in the right direction; yes, definitely positive.''
   In Jerusalem, Foreign Minister Moshe Arens issued a statement
praising ``the positive attitude of the Soviet Union that found
expression'' in the vote.
   Clovis Maksoud, representative of the Arab League, described the
new Soviet position on the challenge to Israel as ``regrettable,'
but called it a ``tactical change'' that did not alter Moscow's
support for the Arab position.
   U.S. Ambassador Thomas R. Pickering, a former ambassador to
Israel, said: ``The Soviet abstention is a good sign. A `yes' vote
would have been better.''
</TEXT>
