<FIRST>r w AM-HighwaySafety 1stLd-Writethru a0680 10-17 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Highway Safety, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0680,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cyclists, Officials Oppose Bill Tying Road Aid to Helmet, Belt Laws</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 2nd graf to CORRECT name of committee.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Motorcyclists and state officials joined
Tuesday in opposing legislation to withhold some federal highway
aid from states without mandatory automobile seat-belt and
motorcycle helmet laws.
   The cyclists told a hearing of a Senate Environment and Public
Works subcommittee that most states either have helmet laws or are
on their way to doing so. The cyclists also argued that riders'
edcuation programs have helped reduce fatalities over the last
eight years by 35 percent.
   ``Issues of highway safety and personal freedom have
traditionally and rightfully been resolved by state governments,
and the imposition (of the proposed law) is a violation of state's
rights,'' said Robert Rasor, vice president for governmental
relations of the American Motorcyclist Association of Westerville,
Ohio.
   At issue is legislation sponsored by Sen. John R. Chafee,
R-R.I., to empower the Transportation Department to withhold up to
10 percent of a state's federal highway aid unless it required
motorcylists to wear helmets and all front-seat automobile
passengers to wear safety belts.
   Chafee said that nearly 50,000 people are killed on the highways
each year. The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration
estimates that 20,000 lives have been saved over the last five
years through the wearing of motorcycle helmets and automobile
safety belts.
   Public health groups, physicians and the insurance industry
support Chafee's proposal.
   ``Our taxes pay more than $9 billion each toward the care of
injured motor vehicle occupants and motorcyclists,'' Susan P. Baker
of the Johns Hopkins Injury Prevention Center in Baltimore told the
subcommittee on water resources, transportation and infrastructure.
   But represenatives of state government and other opponents of
sanctions contained in the proposed ``National Highway Fatality and
Injury Reduction Act of 1989'' argued that the sanctions would be
counterproductive.
   ``Adding to the list of ways in which a state can jeopardize
funding for transportation, including safety, only limits the
state's ability to find the most effective combination of laws,
regulations and educational efforts to encourage driver and
passenger safety,'' said Virginia state Sen. Charles Wadell,
representing the National Conference of State Legislators.
   Robert Ford of the Massachusetts-based ``Freedom First'' group,
which fought successfully for repeal of that state's seat-belt law,
argued that reducing highway aid would make roads more hazardous.
   The insurance industry's Insurance Institute for Highway Safety
says that only 16 states don't now have mandatory seat-belt laws.
   Twenty-two states and the District of Columbia have helmet laws
applying to all riders. Three states _ Colorado, Illinois and Iowa
_ don't have helmet laws. The rest have laws covering riders under
a certain age, which varies from state to state.
</TEXT>
