<FIRST>u i AM-Commonwealth 1stLd-Writethru a0699 10-17 0419</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commonwealth, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0699,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thatcher Opposes Deadline on South Africa</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES and edits throughout to include ANC statements. No pickup</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-South Africa</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER O'LOUGHLIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 49-nation Commonwealth of
Britain and its former colonies opens its biennial summit
Wednesday, divided over whether to toughen sanctions on South
Africa or give it six months to make racial reforms.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher of Britain will make the
opening speech and argue against stronger sanctions or a deadline
for reform in South Africa, which quit the Commonwealth in 1961.
   The African National Congress, the main group fighting white
domination in South Afrida, urged the Commonwealth to impose more
sanctions and indicated its hit-and-run guerrilla attacks may
change.
   ``It is very important ... to pay attention to the question of
building up the military capacity to conduct a sustained armed
struggle, not merely to carry out an operation once in a while,
however spectacular,'' said Thabo Mbeki, the organization's
spokesman on foreign affairs.
   Mrs. Thatcher is likely to dominate the 40th anniversary summit
as she has in the past.
   Many delegates said they were prepared to give South Africa's
new president, F.W. de Klerk, six months to deliver on promises of
radical reforms following Sunday's release of several leading black
nationalists.
   British officials said Mrs. Thatcher felt a deadline would be
``wholly artificial.''
   ``You're not going to solve the South African question in six
months. It's going to take some time,'' one said.
   Commonwealth countries have led the push for international
action against apartheid, South Africa's official policy of racial
segregation.
   Britain says recent progress toward political settlements in
Namibia, Angola and Mozambique should not be jeopardized by forcing
South Africa into a corner.
   ``The way forward is not to set it back and not to put artifical
deadlines upon people,'' the official said. ``You must allow the
reform process to go forward to prove its worth.''
   Sir Shridath Ramphal, Commonwealth secretary-general, indicated
in a briefing before Mrs. Thatcher's arrival that environmental
issues might eclipse the South Africa question. He said
environmental problems were of such wide concern, ``it could be in
some respects a crisis agenda.''
   After her arrival and meetings of British officials with other
delegations, however, it became clear Mrs. Thatcher wanted South
Africa at the top of the list for the conference in the Putra World
Trade Center on the Klang River.
   The summit, which does not take formal votes on issues, runs
until Oct. 24.
</TEXT>
