<FIRST>r w AM-Congress-Drugs     10-17 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-Drugs,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressmen, Administration Argue Over Drug Effort</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers and Bush administration officials
clashed Tuesday over President Bush's war on illegal drugs, with
some congressmen complaining about unrealistic goals and confusion
over the duties of government agencies.
   Representatives of the Defense Department, Customs Service and
Coast Guard told two House Government Operations subcommittees that
the administration has made progress in stemming the flow of drugs
into the United States.
   ``I have spent 60 percent of my time on the drug war this
year,'' said Gen. Thomas Kelly, director of operations for the
Joint Chiefs of Staff. ``I assure you our attention has been
gotten.''
   The general said the commanders in chief of the Unified and
Specified Commands have completed their proposals for the drug war.
Last month, Defense Secretary Dick Cheney asked military leaders to
draw up plans by Oct. 15 for using ships, planes, radar and troops
in the fight against illicit drugs.
   Kelly said Cheney and the Joint Chiefs of Staff will be briefed
on the proposals later this week with a final plan expected
sometime later. No date was given.
   Kelly said he was not at liberty to discuss the proposals but
did confirm earlier reports that the United States will use its
ships in the drug war.
   ``We will have battle groups in the future in the Caribbean,''
said Kelly, who spoke of achieving the goals set by the president.
   But members of the subcommittee on legislation and national
security and the panel on government information, justice and
agriculture expressed reservations about the administration's
policy.
   Rep. John Conyers Jr., D-Mich., chairman of the full committee,
questioned Bush's recent stated goal to reduce drug imports by 10
percent in two years and 50 percent over 10 years.
   ``Ten percent of what?'' Conyers asked.
   Michael Lane, acting commissioner of the Customs Service, said
the agency has asked William Bennett, head of the Office of
National Drug Control Policy, for clarification on what the base
will be for judging reductions.
   Shortly after Conyers' comment, Rep. Glenn English, D-Okla., and
Stephen Duncan, the Defense Department's coordinator for drug
enforcement policy and support, got into a heated exchange over
whether the Pentagon is usurping the Customs Service as the top
agency in the drug war.
   ``Has this administration changed the directive of the previous
administration? ... In May 1987, Customs was the lead agency for
interdiction,'' English said.
   Duncan said the Bush administration has not changed the
directive. He also emphasized that the various agencies ``don't get
into whose under and whose over in day-to-day operations.''
   Englsh persisted, asking ``Who determines where we're putting
our resources?''
   Duncan stressed that the Defense Department is the lead agency
for detection and monitoring but Customs remains the chief
department for interdiction.
</TEXT>
