<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-89 2040EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-IncompetentDoctors     10-17 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Incompetent Doctors,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government To Open Data Bank Of Incompetent Doctors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A data bank to help hospitals and other
health-care providers keep track of incompetent physicians,
dentists and other practitioners is due to go on line early next
year, the Department of Health and Human Services announced Tuesday.
   The National Practitioner Data Bank ``will reduce the ability of
incompetent medical practitioners to avoid scrutiny by moving to
another jurisdiction,'' but will protect confidentiality, HHS
Secretary Louis Sullivan said.
   The Public Citizen Health Research Group said the data bank was
``a good thing,'' but complained that the information in it would
not be available to most of the public.
   Lynn Soffer, a research associate with the health group, said
access to the information would be limited to hospitals, licensing
boards and other health-care entities and to individuals who are
subjects of reports.
   ``I think some basic information should be available to the
public from the bank,'' Soffer said. ``If a patient knows their
doctor was kicked off the staff, they deserve to have some basic
information on this.''
   The data bank will contain information concerning malpractice
payments made on behalf of physicians, dentists and other
health-care practitioners, as well as information on actions taken
by state boards against the licenses of physicians and dentists.
   Hospitals and other health-care facilities and professional
societies will be required to report their review actions
concerning professional competence or conduct that affect the
clinical privileges or membership of physicians or other
health-care practitioners. Reports must be made within 30 days from
the date of the payment or action.
   Also, hospitals must consult the data bank each time a
physician, dentist or other health-care practitioner applies for a
medical staff position or clinical privileges. Hospitals also must
request information every two years on the practitioners on its
medical staff and those who have clinical privileges.
   The data bank will be operated by UNISYS Corp. under a
five-year, $15.9 million contract.
</TEXT>
