<FIRST>r w AM-CleanAir     10-17 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Clean Air,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>EPA Affirms Support For Mandatory Construction Of Fuel-Efficient
Cars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN FLESHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration wants to require
automobile companies to manufacture, but not necessarily sell, cars
that burn cleaner fuels than gasoline, an Environmental Protection
Agency official said Tuesday.
   Seeking to clarify the administration's position on a key
element of the president's clean air bill, William G. Rosenberg,
assistant EPA administrator for air and radiation, told a Senate
committee Bush opposes an amendment endorsed by a House
subcommittee last week.
   The amendment would eliminate Bush's requirement that automakers
build and sell a million cars a year to run on alternative fuels
such as methanol and compressed natural gas. The cars would be sold
in the nation's smoggiest cities.
   Lawmakers friendly to the auto and oil industries pushed the
amendment, which environmentalists said would weaken the bill.
   Confusion arose during last week's meeting of the House Energy
and Commerce environment subcommittee, which approved the amendment
12-10, when the administration appeared to send conflicting signals
on its position.
   Rep. Norman Lent, R-N.Y., said White House Chief of Staff John
Sununu had told him the administration was neutral on the
amendment. But Rep. Henry Waxman, D-Calif., said EPA Administrator
William Reilly had voiced opposition.
   During Tuesday's hearing of the Senate Committee On Energy and
Natural Resources, Rosenberg said the administration would support
the House amendment only with major changes.
   Under the House amendment, sponsored by Reps. Ralph Hall,
D-Texas, and Jack Fields, R-Texas, automakers would have to certify
they could build the clean-fuel cars but would not have to make
them. Rosenberg said the administration wants the cars actually
built but would agree to drop the requirement that the autos be
sold.
   Automakers have fought the sales requirements, saying there is
no guarantee the public would buy the cars.
   The administration also wants the bill to establish a two-part
system for phasing in use of clean-fuel cars, Rosenberg said. For
the immediate future, cars burning a combination of gasoline and
clean fuels such as methanol would be acceptable. Over the long
term, EPA would establish auto emission standards based entirely on
clean fuel use.
   ``We are confident that with these changes, the Fields-Hall
amendment will achieve environmental benefits comparable to the
administration's proposal,'' Rosenberg said. ``Until these
adjustments are made part of the Fields-Hall amendment, the
administration continues to support the president's original
propsal in both the Senate and the House.''
</TEXT>
