<FIRST>r i AM-Egypt-Libya     10-17 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Egypt-Libya,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mubarak Visits Libya in Fence-mending Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Hosni Mubarak on Tuesday shuttled
to Libya for a second day of mending fences with Moammar Gadhafi in
the neighboring land that no Egyptian leader had visited for 18
years.
   His trip came a day after the U.S. State Department appeared to
frown on his dialogue with Gadhafi, whom it accuses of backing
international terrorism.
   On Monday, the two leaders met at Egypt's Mediterranean resort
of Mersa Matruh. Gadhafi, who broke relations with Eygpt over its
peace initiatives with Israel, had not visited Egypt for 16 years.
The two countries fought a brief border war in 1977.
   The state-run Middle East New Agency reported that Mubarak flew
from Mersa Matruh to the eastern Libyan town of Tobruk on Tuesday.
   It said Gadhafi greeted Mubarak at Tobruk's Gamal Abdel Nasser
Air Base, named for Egypt's first president. The two leaders then
met privately at a local hotel, the report said.
   However, their were no details on their meeting. The agency said
Mubarak did not talk to reporters when he returned late Tuesday to
Cairo airport.
   The two leaders began their reconciliation in May, when they met
privately at an Arab summit in Morocco. The last time an Egyptian
leader went to Libya was when Anwar Sadat made the trip in 1971.
   Despite the latest talks, diplomatic relations remain severed.
Mubarak told reporters Monday night he had not raised the issue
with Gadhafi.
   After their meeting Monday, the two leaders announced only that
they were easing formalities for travel between their two countries.
   In her comments in Washington on Monday, U.S. State Department
spokeswoman Margaret D. Tutwiler said, ``Our position on Libya, its
support for terrorism and other regional activities involving
destabilization, is well known.'' She added, ``We have made known
to Egypt our views and concerns.''
   In other remarks Tuesday in Libya, Mubarak criticized Syria for
allowing a radical Palestinian group to ``insult'' Egypt from its
soil, the Middle East News Agency said.
   Asked if relations with Syria could improve as they did with
Libya, Mubarak said, ``I know President Hafez Assad (of Syria)
well, and I know others there well, and there is no problem with
them except that I blame them for letting George Habash insult
Egypt from Damascus.''
   Mubarak was referring to a warning made in the Syrian capital on
Oct. 9 by Habash, chief of the Marxist-oriented Popular Front for
the Liberation of Palestine.
   In his comments, Habash rejected a plan put forward by Mubarak
for Middle East peace.
   He also said the Egyptian president could suffer the same fate
as his predecessor, Anwar Sadat, who was assassinated by Moslem
extremists in 1981 after the 1979 peace treaty with Israel.
   Syria and Libya are the only two of 17 Arab countries that have
failed to restore ties with Egypt after breaking them over the
treaty.
</TEXT>
