<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Ownership     10-17 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Ownership,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Legislators Permit Ownership of Equipment, Inheritance of Leased
Land</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislators gave overwhelming preliminary approval
Tuesday to a bill that would scrap decades of Communist orthodoxy
by allowing people to own factories and farmers to pass leased land
on to their children.
   The landmark legislation stopped short of permitting widespread
private property, which some members advocated, and said all land
still would belong to the state.
   By a vote of 309-29, with 34 abstentions, the Supreme Soviet
approved the bill and sent it to a commission headed by President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev, which will edit the legislation and publish
it for nationwide discussion before final action.
   Strict ideologists say Marxist principle stipulates that all
means of production belong to society as a whole, and that private
ownership leads to exploitation.
   Under the legislation approved Tuesday, citizens may own their
``means of production'' and ``pursue individual and other kinds of
economic activity,'' the official news agency Tass reported.
   It did not define means of production, but the term generally
means equipment and factories.
   Farm families would have the right to pass land leased from the
state to future generations, and the legislation would permit
joint-stock and other forms of private ownership, Tass reorted.
   Allowing farmers to pass leased land along was suggested by the
Communist Party Central Committee.
   Some deputies pressed for complete legalization of private
property as a means of providing incentives for employees to work
harder.
   The bill says land and natural resources will be joint property
of the nation as a whole and the individual republics involved.
   Deputies from the independence-minded Baltic republics of
Latvia, Lithuania and Estonia want exclusive ownership. They say
Moscow has abused land and resources in the past and the republics
should receive the profits from their own territory.
   The Baltics have won central government approval for control
over their own economies, beginning next year.
   Some private enterprise, in the form of cooperatives, already is
allowed and the Supreme Soviet passed legislation Tuesday governing
those businesses.
   One law bars cooperatives from buying manufactured goods and
food from the state and reselling it for profit. Another imposed
price controls on cooperatives to prevent gouging.
</TEXT>
