<FIRST>r a AM-BatteredWoman     10-17 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Battered Woman,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>Battered Woman Freed After Pleading Pleaded Guilty in Boyfriend's
Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DOVER, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who was sentenced to 25 years in
prison after pleading guilty to killing her live-in boyfriend, who
she said beat her, has pleaded guilty a second time and been
allowed to go free.
   Susan J. Scott, 36, was a free woman Monday for the first time
since the slaying of Frederick E. Bickling, 43, in September 1986.
   Scott has always maintained that she was a battered woman and
feared Bickling would kill her.
   Kent County Superior Court Judge John E. Babiarz Jr., who
sentenced her after her first guilty plea in May 1988, this week
accepted a prosecution recommendation to resentence her to time
already served _ three years and 26 days _ and seven years
probation.
   ``I know now ... that you were abused by him to a certain
extent,'' Babiarz told Scott. ``I am not about to characterize how
much or how little. But I am satisfied you are less culpable than I
thought you were last year.''
   Scott first pleaded guilty to manslaughter a week before she was
to be tried on a charge of first-degree murder.
   Scott's family later fired her lawyer and retained Richard L.
Ducote, a New Orleans attorney who specializes in abuse cases.
   Earlier this year, Ducote asked Babiarz to allow Scott to
withdraw her guilty plea, alleging the first attorney did not give
her adequate representation and should have argued that Scott
suffered from ``battered woman syndrome'' and shot Bickling in
self-defense.
   Scott was allowed to withdraw her original plea and jury
selection was scheduled to begin Monday for a new first-degree
murder trial. At the last minute, Deputy Attorney General James
Rambo again offered a plea bargain, and Scott agreed to plead
guilty to manslaughter a second time. She also waived her $56,000
share of Bickling's life insurance policy.
   Scott issued a statement saying she should have fled the
relationship with Bickling.
   ``I admit that my recklessnness led to the death of Fred
Bickling,'' she said. ``When he began abusing me, I was reckless in
remaining in the relationship. When the pattern of abuse got worse,
I was reckless in not leaving him and seeking help for battered
women.''
</TEXT>
