<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-GOPGovernors     10-17 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-GOP Governors,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>For Release At 8:35 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Says GOP Needs to Win More Governorships</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, in a rallying cry to GOP
governors, said Tuesday night that the key to wresting control of
Congress from the Democrats in the 1990s is to elect more
Republican governors next year.
   Bush, in remarks prepared for delivery at a Republican Governors
Association dinner, said that if the party is to escape its
minority status, ``we must rededicate ourselves to the nuts and
bolts of politics, the grassroots, as our opponents, do.''
   He bemoaned the fact that 34 years have passed since the
Republicans last controlled the House of Representatives, and said
the Democrats perpetuate their hold through gerrymandering schemes
approved by state legislatures they also control.
   ``We have proven, time and again, that our party can keep the
White House,'' said Bush. ``But to win a majority of governorships,
state offices and seats in Congress, we must roll up our sleeves
and get down to the basics of winning elections.''
   Bush outlined what he called ``three obtainable goals'' for the
1990 elections.
   The first is ``to move toward our rightful place as the majority
party of governors,'' said Bush. The Democrats now hold 28
governorships to the Republicans' 22.
   ``Our second goal is to recapture the U.S. Senate,'' he said.
The Republicans held the Senate from 1981 to 1987, but Democrats
now have the edge, 55-45.
   ``And third, we must open the House of Representatives to
two-party competition,'' the president said. ``But the key to all
three goals is the first: to elect more Republican governors.''
   He called gerrymandering _ drawing congressional district lines
in ways to boost the chances of a particular party _ ``a terrible
injustice.''
   ``As Republican leaders, you can veto these gerrymander schemes
and take our message to voters of your states by declaring that
this form of voter discrimination must end,'' said Bush, the first
president in the last four to reach the White House without first
serving as a governor.
   Virginia and New Jersey choose new governors next month.
Thirty-six governorships are at stake in 1990, including 20 now
held by Democrats. Virginia now has a Democratic governor, New
Jersey a Republican.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
