<FIRST>r i BC-Britain-Chess     10-17 0173</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Chess,0179</SECOND>
<HEAD>Karpov, Timman Win in Semifinals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOODMAN</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anatoly Karpov of the Soviet Union and Jan Timman
of the Netherlands on Tuesday scored last-round semifinal victories
in the World Chess Championship Candidates.
   The winner of the Candidates' final, scheduled for March in
London, will challenge world champion Garri Kasparov for his title
in a 24-game match starting October 1990.
   Karpov, 38, who held the world title for 10 years before losing
to Kasparov in 1985, returned to form and scored a crushing 53-move
victory over fellow Soviet Artur Yusupov in the eighth and final
game.
   Timman, 37, defeated Jon Speelman of England in 54 moves after a
zigzag battle.
   Both Karpov and Timman won by 4.5 points to 3.5. A win scores
one point and a draw one half-point.
   Karpov, playing white, built up a devastating kingside attack
and then exchanged down to reach an endgame with two extra pawns.
   Karpov and Timman each get $77,000 for winning their semifinals,
while Yusupov and Speelman each won $46,000.
</TEXT>
