<FIRST>u i AM-SwissKidnap     10-17 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Swiss Kidnap,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>Red Cross Asks Release Of Two of Its Workers in Lebanon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The International Committee of the Red
Cross on Tuesday demanded release of two Swiss medical workers held
hostage in Lebanon.
   ``The ICRC calls for the immediate and unconditional release of
its delegates,'' it said in a French-language statement released in
Beirut.
   It called the Oct. 6 abduction of Red Cross orthopedic
technicians Emmanuel Christen, 32, and Elio Erriquez, 23, an
``unacceptable and unjustifiable attempt against the 15 years of
humanitarian work of the ICRC in Lebanon.''
   Masked gunmen kidnapped the pair, bundled them into the trunk of
a car and sped off toward Ein el-Hilweh Palestinian refugee camp on
the outskirts of Sidon.
   Tuesday's statement said a Western news agency in Ankara,
Turkey, received a telephone call from a man purporting to speak
for the Lebanese Islamic Jihad, or holy war, and claiming
responsibility. He said the lives of the two would be in danger if
air pirate Mohammed Hussein Hariri was not released in three days.
   Islamic Jihad usually communicates through written statements,
accompanied by a photograph of a hostage to demonstrate
authenticity. Such was not the case with the Ankara call.
   Hariri, 22, a Lebanese Shiite Moslem, is serving a life sentence
in Switzerland for hijacking an Air Afrique jetliner to Geneva in
1987 and killing a French passenger on board.
   The Red Cross closed its orthopedic center in Sidon, which
provides artificial limbs to civil war victims, after the
abductions.
</TEXT>
