<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru a0661 10-17 0670</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0661,0685</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shamir Says Israel Willing to Risk Antagonizing Washington</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout, UPDATING with Shamir saying Israel ready to
tilt with United States, later casualty count. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said Tuesday that
Israel stood ready to confront the United States rather than trade
occupied land for peace.
   ``We are not interested in conflicts,'' Shamir said, in some of
his harshest words for the Bush administration. ``But the United
States should know that there are things Israel will stand on to
the end.''
   Shamir told supporters of his right-wing Likud bloc at a rally
in Ramle: ``In everything related to the Land of Israel, we shall
stand as one man, and we will not give in, even if we would have to
face a conflict. I hope we would not have to. It is not justified
from the American point of view, but totally justified from the
Jewish and the Israeli points of view.''
   Shamir rejected American efforts to arrange negotiations between
Israeli and Palestinian delegations in Cairo. President Hosni
Mubarak of Egypt has offered to play host to such talks.
   ``The stone-throwers, the firebombers have not succeeded in
driving us into the arms of the PLO. It is not possible that when
they fail to do this, others by diplomatic means and exercises
would try to bring us to meetings with the PLO,'' Shamir said.
   He said the proposed meeting would be a ``trap'' in which other
parties would try to make Israel ``slide into recognition of a
Palestinian state.''
   Israel has balked at the proposed meeting with Palestinian
representatives because it fears the Palestinians would be members
of the Palestine Liberation Organization. Israel considers the PLO
a terrorist group and refuses to negotiate with it.
   Shamir told a closed-door meeting of Likud legislators earlier
Tuesday that Israel might be ``entering a period of tension with
the United States,'' Israel radio reported.
   On Tuesday, a human rights group reported that Israeli soldiers
killed 20 Palestinians in the first two weeks of October, one of
the bloodiest periods of the 22-month-old uprising against Israeli
rule in the occupied lands.
   The increase in deaths followed a change in army orders last
month that allows soldiers to fire live ammunition at masked
Palestinians who ignore orders to halt, even if they are not armed.
   Army reports said at least eight Palestinians killed in the
first 15 days of October wore masks.
   According to the Israeli Information Center for Human Rights,
the early October death toll was second only to the same period in
April 1988, when 23 Palestinians were killed.
   Soldiers or Israeli civilians have killed 596 Palestinians since
the uprising began Dec. 8, 1987, in the occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip, and 40 Israelis have died. At least 130 Palestinians have
been killed by fellow Arabs, most on suspicion of collaborating
with Israel.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin toured three West Bank towns
Tuesday, including Beit Sahour, where soldiers and tax agents have
carried out tax raids for three weeks.
   Reporters and photographers were not allowed to accompany Rabin
into the Christian town, which the army has declared a ``closed
military zone.''
   Telephone lines also have been cut to Beit Sahour, a town of
about 10,000 known for widespread compliance with a tax boycott
called by the uprising leadership.
   Israeli officials said up to $1 million worth of furniture,
machinery and other goods had been confiscated in Beit Sahour and
would be sold to recover unpaid taxes. The town is prosperous
because scores of small, family-owned factories operate there.
   ``Everyone, everywhere, pays taxes,'' Rabin said after touring
Beit Sahour.
   In nearby Bethlehem, a soldier pursuing Palestinian
stone-throwers was slightly injured by a rock and troopers opened
fire, wounding one Palestinian, the army said. A second man was
reported arrested.
   Elsewhere, seven other Palestinians were shot and wounded in
clashes with Israeli troops, Arab hospital officials reported. The
army said it was checking the reports.
</TEXT>
