<FIRST>u a AM-PreschoolMolest     10-17 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Preschool Molest,0477</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Lawyer: Molestation Investigators Fanned Rumors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators inadvertently touched rumors at
the outset of the McMartin preschool molestation case, creating
community hysteria that tainted the probe, a defense attorney said
Tuesday in the 2{-year-long trial.
   Attorney Dean Gits outlined a range of doubts about police
competence and witnesses' credibility, appealing to a jury during
his closing statement to depend on common sense and the legal
standard of reasonable doubt.
   ``I want you to take them and put them in your pocket and carry
them with you,'' Gits said.
   Raymond Buckey, 31, and his mother, Peggy McMartin Buckey, 62,
are charged with 64 counts of molestation and a joint count of
conspiracy. They are accused of molesting 11 children at the
family-owned McMartin Pre-School in suburban Manhattan Beach.
   The alleged crimes date back a decade and the trial _ at 2{
years _ is the longest criminal proceeding in the nation. Judge
William Pounders has said jury deliberations in Superior Court
could be very lengthy.
   Gits argued that police incompetence at the start of an
investigation of a parent's complaint touched off rumors in
Manhattan Beach.
   He cited a Sept. 8, 1983, form letter that investigators sent to
hundreds of parents whose children had attended the preschool.
   The letter asked parents to keep the investigation confidential
because of ``the highly emotional effect it could have on our
community.''
   ``Law enforcement completely lost control of the interview
process. It was the start of rumors that governed this case,'' Gits
said.
   He said medical procedures used to determine whether children
were molested were unscientific, and that too many people testified
they never saw sexual abuse for the allegations to make sense.
   Gits focused on conflicting information in the testimony of one
alleged victim, a boy who said games like ``naked movie star,''
``tickle'' and ``cowboys and Indians'' took place in a secret room.
   The boy attended the school from fall 1978 to June 1979.
   He testified at a preliminary hearing that teacher Babette
Spitler was in a room at the time of a ``naked movie star'' game
and molested him, Gits said. He said the boy didn't claim that
during the trial and that Ms. Spitler didn't work at the school
when he was there.
   Ms. Spitler was among seven McMartin teachers originally
arrested in 1983. Charges against her and four others were dropped
for lack of evidence, and the case was scaled down from hundreds of
counts involving 41 children.
   The judge has limited each side to 6{ days for closing
arguments, fearing a mistrial if the case drags on.
   Deputy District Attorney Roger Gunson concluded his summation on
Monday after three days, reserving 3{ days for rebuttal of defense
arguments.
</TEXT>
