<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     10-17 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0346</SECOND>
<HEAD>Afghanistan Sends Convoy to Relieve Besieged Troops</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Reporter</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Afghan convoy is en route to the
eastern border town of Khost, where planes have been parachuting
supplies to communist troops besieged by U.S.-backed rebels,
Western diplomats said Tuesday.
   They said that elsewhere, rebels have blockaded the 75-mile
highway linking Kabul, the capital, to the eastern city of
Jalalabad and that the government has launched heavy air attacks
and armored assaults trying to open the road.
   The sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said guerrilla
forces have moved within three miles of Khost airport. The town
lies about 10 miles from the border with Pakistan. Guerrilla groups
long have used Pakistan as a base.
   The rebels have been trying for weeks to take the heavily
fortified town. The capture of Khost would allow them to open
direct supply lines to bases in central and northern Afghanistan.
   Diplomatic sources, presumably with access to satellite
pictures, said photographs show parachutes inside the Khost
perimeter. ``There is clear visible evidence of air drops'' by
government forces, one diplomat said.
   Rebel sources said planes parachuted 44 barrels of fuel about
two weeks ago, but eight reached the target and the rest landed in
guerrilla-controlled areas.
   The last attempt to resupply Khost by land was in December 1987,
when 20,000 Soviet soldiers reportedly helped out. The attempt
succeeded after six weeks.
   Diplomats said a 200-vehicle convoy left Kabul late last week
and was moving slowly toward Gardez, about 45 miles northwest of
Khost.
   Moscow sent more than 103,000 soldiers into Afghanistan in 1979
to back up the Marxist government. But the last Soviet soldiers
left last Feb. 15 in keeping with a U.N.-brokered accord.
   However, the Soviet Union has airlifted millions of dollars in
military aid to the government in Kabul since then, diplomatic
sources say.
   Washington is a major backer of the Afghan rebels, who have been
fighting for more than a decade to oust successive communist
governments.
</TEXT>
