<FIRST>u i AM-Britain-Bombs 2ndLd-Writethru a0765 10-17 0747</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Bombs, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0765,0767</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Government Won't Fight Appeals of Convicted Bombers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with newspaper report police will
be prosecuted. Picks up 5th graf, `British Broadcasting .. .'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain paved the way Tuesday for the probable
release of at least three people imprisoned 14 years ago for IRA
bombings aimed at British soldiers. The Irish government and civil
libertarians cheered the move.
   The government said it will not oppose the appeal by the
so-called ``Guildford Four'' _ three men and a woman who insisted
throughout that they were innocent and who became the focus of a
lengthy campaign for their release.
   The Times of London newspaper said policemen involved in the
original investigation that led to the convictions and life terms
will be prosecuted.
   In its Wednesday issue, copies of which were available Tuesday
night, the paper reported: ``A handful of officers, who were then
of relatively junior rank, will face charges after an investigation
by ... police into a number of aspects of the original inquiry.''
   A spokesman at the Home Office, the government department
responsible for police, refused to comment.
   The bombings led to murder convictions for the Guildford Four
during a wave of terrorism by the Irish Republican Army.
   The Dublin government, leaders of the Roman Catholic and
Anglican churches, and prominent British government figures
protested the innocence of the four.
   British Broadcasting Corp. Television, the domestic news agency
Press Association and other news reports said at least three of the
prisoners probably would be released soon after a Court of Appeal
hearing Thursday.
   ``Circumstances have recently come to the notice of the Director
of Public Prosecutions which have caused him to conclude that it
would be wrong for the Crown to seek to sustain the convictions,''
the prosecutor's office said.
   It said its decision will be explained at the Thursday hearing.
   The murder convictions of Paul Hill, Gerard Conlon and Patrick
Armstrong, all of Belfast, Northern Ireland, and of Armstrong's
English girlfriend, Carole Richardson, were referred to the Court
of Appeal by Home Secretary Douglas Hurd in January.
   The four were convicted of murder in the bombing of two pubs
frequented by British soldiers in Guildford, southwest of London,
on Oct. 5, 1974. Five people were killed, including two soldiers,
and 65 injured.
   Armstrong and Hill also were convicted of a Nov. 6, 1974, pub
bombing in Woolwich, a London suburb, in which two people died and
26 people were injured. Hill is serving a concurrent sentence for
the murder of a former British soldier in Belfast in 1975, and so
may not be released with the others, news reports said. That
conviction was based on statements obtained by Belfast police while
he was in prison in Guildford.
   IRA guerrillas are fighting to drive the British from Northern
Ireland and unite the British province with the Republic of Ireland.
   In ordering the case reviewed, Hurd cited possible alibi
witnesses for two of the convicts, and evidence that Ms. Richardson
had been injected with drugs during interrogation because she was
suffering from withdrawal from barbiturates.
   All four were convicted on the basis of incriminating statements
which they repudiated when they came to trial. The prosecution did
not offer any forensic evidence or identifications by witnesses to
the bombings.
   Four members of an IRA unit _ the ``Balcombe Street Four'' _
admitted the two Guildford pub bombings after their arrest in
December 1975, but they were never charged in the case.
   The IRA men's statements about the bombing were presented to the
Court of Appeal in 1977, but the government attorney argued those
statements did not necessarily preclude the participation of the
four convicted earlier.
   In Dublin, the Irish government welcomed the decision ``in the
most positive terms.''
   ``The government shares what it knows will be a general feeling
today of great relief and satisfaction at this outcome,'' the Irish
statement said.
   Cardinal Basil Hume, head of the Roman Catholic Church in
Britain, told BBC-TV he was ``immensely grateful'' for the decision.
   ``I absolutely can't believe it,'' Hill's mother, Lilly Hill,
told BBC radio from Belfast. ``Good God, I just can't believe that
this has happened.''
   Lord Scarman, who was active in the campaign, said the decision
represented ``more than a pardon. These people will now be
innocent.''
   ``I think the British legal system will benefit in reputation,''
sid Scarman, 78, who as a law lord formerly was part of Britain's
highest appeals court.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
