<HEAD>Killing in Salvador May Affect Peace Talks, Government Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with rebels denying responsibility
for attack, background. Picks up graf 8 pvs, `There has ...' Edits thereafter
to trim</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SAL2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The killing of an army colonel's
daughter could jeopardize talks between Salvadoran guerrillas and
the government over ways to end their country's 10-year-old civil
war, a government spokesman said Tuesday.
   ``It is a disastrous terrorist plan to assassinate public
officials and their families,'' said Mauricio Sandoval, a spokesman
for the government delegation, following the shooting in San
Salvador on Tuesday.
   Men firing automatic weapons killed Ana Isabel Casanova, a
student who was celebrating her 23rd birthday, in her car a block
from her home.
   In San Salvador, the government blamed insurgents for the
attack, but the language in the claim of responsibility was unlike
that used by the rebels in the past.
   A man purporting to speak for the ``joint command'' of urban
guerrillas of the Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front called
at least one radio station in El Salvador to claim responsibility
for the attack.
   The caller said the attack was meant to underline demands for
the release of a missing unionist allegedly arrested by security
forces and to call for an end to repression by government security
forces.
   However, rebel leaders in El Salvador said in statement, ``It is
totally false that urban commandos from the FMLN killed Miss Isabel
Casanova, and we reiterate it is not FMLN policy to attempt against
the lives of relatives of military chiefs.''
   The rebel leaders said the slaying was part of ``psychological
warfare'' that the Salvadoran military high command's intelligence
division and the press office is waging against them.
   ``It is highly suspicious that this occurs just when this
meeting is taking place and the intention to speedily blame the
FMLN for the attack,'' the rebel leaders said in the statement,
which was also handed out in San Jose.
   ``Anyone can pick up the telephone and say he's from the FMLN,''
rebel spokeswoman Nidia Diaz told reporters as she distributed the
statement.
   There has been little progress reported in the two days of talks
between the rebels and the rightist government of President Alfredo
Cristiani. The government has proposed a cease-fire without the
economic, political and legal reforms the Farabundo Marti National
Liberation Front guerrillas insist on.
   Gregorio Rosa Chavez, auxiliary bishop of San Salvador and a
witness at the talks, said the negotiating process ``allows hope,
not for spectacular results, but for them, at the end, to reach a
minimal agreement that allows work to continue so that a peace
agreement finally is signed.''
   Rebels said the assassination of the colonel's daughter, like
the removal of rebel sympathizers during a peace vigil at the
Metropolitan Cathedral in San Salvador, would not interrupt the
talks.
   The Costa Rica talks are the second meeting between the
government and rebels since the opening session occurred in Mexico
City in September.
   A previous round of dialogue between the government and rebels,
in October 1987, was broken off because of the assassination of
Herbert Anaya, leader of a leftist human rights group.
   The Front said Tuesday it proposed purging the armed forces of
its top officers, including Defense Minister Gen. Humberto Larios;
Gen. Juan Rafael Bustillo, the air force chief; and Col. Rene
Ponce, chief of the joint chiefs of staff'
   ``The majority of those officers have accumulated large economic
interests through corruption,'' the rebel proposal says. ``They are
involved or directly linked to acts of repression and crime.''
   Rosa Chavez, who with Archbishop Arturo Rivera Damas has
mediated contact between the guerrillas and government for several
years, said the two sides were trying Tuesday to agree on what
constitutes a cease-fire in the war, which has killed an estimated
70,000 people, most of them civilians.
</TEXT>
