<FIRST>u a AM-CustodyDispute 1stLd-Writethru a0754 10-17 0727</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Custody Dispute, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0754,0750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Women Wage Battle for Custody of Child</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `The girl ...,' to UPDATE with girl allowed to
return to McCaslin home.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HILLIARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities are trying to determine whether a
12-year-old girl was kidnapped in infancy or was given away by her
mother, who now wants her back from the woman who has raised her
ever since.
   Cynthia Anderson, 31, the girl's biological mother, was in a
grocery store Friday when she heard the voice of Maxine McCaslin,
43, who used to work for her as a baby sitter. She had not seen
McCaslin since 1977, when McCaslin and Anderson's 6-month-old
daughter both vanished.
   Anderson got McCaslin's license number and notified police.
Detective Mona Jaramillo said the women had lived just 17 blocks
apart for the last two years.
   The girl, who did not know about her biological mother until
Friday, was in a foster home until Tuesday, when Denver Juvenile
Court allowed her to return to McCaslin until the custody case can
be resolved, officials said.
   McCaslin, who reared the child from infancy, told police
Anderson asked her to care for the child because Anderson could not.
   ``It was hell keeping the secret,'' police quoted McCaslin as
saying.
   Anderson claims now that her daughter was kidnapped.
   However, Jaramillo said that in 1977 Anderson filed a complaint
against McCaslin over the custody of the child, but not a
kidnapping complaint.
   ``Our records indicated that the natural mother had turned this
child over to the other woman. It was not regarded as a kidnapping
back then,'' the detective said.
   There was no immediate explanation where McCaslin and the girl
had been until two years ago, why police had never located them, or
whether Anderson could have cared for the girl. There also was no
information immediately available about the girl's father.
   Jaramillo said police were unable to comment on the women's
whereabouts over the years because it is part of the investigation.
   McCaslin had an unlisted telephone number and could not be
reached for comment Tuesday. Anderson's lawyer, Dennis Blewitt of
Boulder, was out of his office and did not immediately return
calls. And police records are incomplete.
   ``I just can't give up hope _ and that's all I can say,''
Anderson said in a statement Monday. She could not be located for
additional comment Tuesday; no telephone number is listed for her.
   ``She's very distraught,'' Blewitt said, adding that Anderson
has bought birthday presents each year, hoping someday to locate
her daughter.
   ``Today, the Denver Department of Social Services refused to let
the mother see her daughter,'' Blewitt said. ``I don't know why,
but they said we `leaked' this to the press. We didn't, but
somebody did.''
   Blewitt said he knew nothing about the father.
   McCaslin told the girl of her history after both were taken to
police headquarters Friday night, police said.
   No charges had been filed.
   ``The stories are so conflicting it was impossible to prove the
case beyond a reasonable doubt,'' said Denver District Attorney
Norm Early.
   ``We are not sure whether we will file criminal charges against
McCaslin at this point,'' said Capt. Jim Fitzpatrick. ``The main
person we and the courts are concerned about at this point is the
victim.
   ``It's been hard on her. She never knew there was another woman
who claims to be her mother.''
   ``She has been well treated, has been raised in an excellent
environment and is a bright little girl,'' said Fitzpatrick.
   Detective Sgt. Gordon Reed, also involved in the investigation,
said there are many mitigating factors on both sides.
   ``The one real victim is the little girl. Her life, as she knew
it, has been destroyed,'' he said.
   Reed described it as ``probably the most tragic case I've seen
in 21 years with the Denver Police Department.''
   Authorities say many reports from the case have vanished in the
intervening years. Because of the complexity of the case police may
have to rely on memories of other police officers who investigated
the case 12 years ago, police said.
   Neighbors and school officials said the girl is a well-adjusted
seventh-grader, a B-plus student and a volleyball player at a
private school.
   A neighbor who tutors the child in math described her as ``a
wonderful little girl, a very well-mannered kid.''
</TEXT>
