<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-89 1253EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-APonTV-Denehy Adv18   10-17 0781</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP on TV-Denehy, Adv 18,0805</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv18</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PM Wed Oct. 18, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Brian Denehy: Gradual Success Better Than Overnight Kind</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY SHARBUTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brian Denehy left Vietnam and the Marine Corps
in 1965, having, he says, ``seen a lot about what life is and how
fragile life is.'' He decided then what he wanted to do with the
rest of his life.
   He wanted to act.
   He has done that, and then some. At 51, he's one of the busiest
``name'' character actors around. The roles include a rotten
sheriff in ``Silverado,'' a tough New York cop in ``Gorky Park,'' a
philosophical barkeep in ``10.''
   On Oct. 28, he'll co-star in a Home Box Office movie, ``Perfect
Witness,'' essaying a cynical, ambitious, yet sentimental U.S.
attorney in a drama about an eyewitness to a contract killing in a
working-class bar here.
   Later this year, he'll return on behalf of the law as a
prosecutor in a new movie, ``Presumed Innocent,'' playing Harrison
Ford's boss.
   It hasn't been an overnight trip to the big bucks, the better
roles. ``My career has been gradual,'' he says. ``Which is good in
a way. Because you stay around longer in a way.''
   There have been reports that Denehy came to his calling
relatively late in life, in his mid-thirties. Not so, he says:
   ``I was always trying to be an actor, but with three kids to
support'' _ all daughters _ ``I was also driving a truck, also a
cab. I even worked as a stockbroker for a while. I was the worst
stockbroker in the history of the market.''
   ``It wasn't so much that I came late to acting. It was that
success came late to me. I was 35 or 36 before I started to get the
ball out of the infield.''
   The major breakthrough, in 1979, was ``10,'' the Bo Derek-Dudley
Moore comedy. Denehy, who has a degree in history from Columbia
University, chuckled when asked if, during his scuffling days, his
kids ever asked when he was going to hang it up and get a real job.
   ``No, but my old man certainly did,'' he said. ``Thank God he
saw it all happen before he died. He got a big kick out of it, he
loved it. But it was a long time between drinks of water for him,
too.''
   His father, Ed Denehy, was a respected Associated Press editor
in New York.
   One lesson learned by watching and listening to his father
always stuck with Denehy: ``He had passion, he really loved his
job. He cared about his work, and it was everything to him.
   ``That's the kind of life I try to live _ to find something that
makes you passionate and then do it. I've tried to communicate that
to my kids and I think I've done it.''
   He mock-sighed. ``Unfortunately, I may have done it a little too
successfully, since two of them are actors.''
   Denehy, whose scuffling days as an actor started in New York
theater, is starting to revisit the stage. He returned here last
year in an acclaimed production of ``The Cherry Orchard'' at the
Brooklyn Academy of Music.
   Next spring, in Chicago, he hopes to play what he calls ``the
big one'' for any Irish-American actor _ Hickey in Eugene O'Neill's
``The Iceman Cometh.''
   But next month, he only intends to relax in Santa Fe, N.M.,
where he and his wife moved last year. They bought an old adobe
house and fixed it up.
   They formerly lived in Los Angeles, where it is said you can
hear the sparrows coughing at dawn. Los Angeles wasn't bad, he
insists. But the traffic got to him. He hasn't that problem in
Santa Fe.
   ``I just love it,'' he says. ``I just love to leave my house and
walk up into the mountains. I can be there in 10 minutes.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in Television:
   ``TODAY'' DRAMA MAY RESOLVE _ After weeks of speculation, NBC
probably will have an announcement by the end of the week on if and
when ``Today'' co-anchor Jane Pauley will leave the show, an NBC
spokeswoman said Tuesday.
   Pauley, with the show for 13 years, is said to want out of the
show because she is unhappy with recent changes there, including a
new layer of management and Deborah Norville's installation as the
show's news anchor.
   NBC says Pauley, who has two years to go on her contract, will
remain at NBC News. Pauley, who also says that, has refused to
comment on anything else. ``Today,'' incidentally, is broadcasting
from Chicago today through Friday.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv For Wed Pms Oct. 18</NOTE>
