<FIRST>u f BC-Pepperell-CluettPeabody     10-17 0214</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Pepperell-Cluett Peabody,0222</SECOND>
<HEAD>West Point-Pepperell Agrees To Sell Cluett Peabody Divisions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Point-Pepperell Inc. has agreed to sell
three of Cluett Peabody &amp; Co.'s four principal divisions to a
French fashion and apparel firm for $600 million.
   Cluett Peabody Acquisition Corp., a subsidiary of Bidermann
Industries USA, said it would acquire the divisions from the
Georgia-based textile giant. The French company did not specify
which three divisions were involved.
   The deal is expected to be completed by the end of November.
   William Farley, chairman of West Point-Pepperell, said in a
statement Monday, ``We are very pleased by the execution of this
agreement to sell Cluett to Bidermann.''
   Farley Inc., Farley's Chicago-based holding company, acquired
Pepperell earlier this year. It reportedly wants to sell Cluett
Peabody divisions to pay off some of the debt it took on in the $3
billion Pepperell deal.
   Cluett Peabody manufactures men's clothing such as Arrow shirts,
Schoeneman suits and Gold Toe socks. Bidermann Industries is the
principal subsidiary of Bidermann Group, which makes and markets
men's and women's branded and designer collections.
   Cluett is worth $450 million and $500 million, said Josie
Esquivel, a textile and apparel analyst with Shearson Lehman Hutton
Inc. Farley had reportedly sought $700 million to $800 million for
the company.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891017-0216 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-89 0147EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     10-17 0938</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0977</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wall Street averted another Black Monday and had
a Blue Chip Monday instead, as some of the heaviest trading in
history produced a rally in big-name stocks and losses in many
smaller issues.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, benefiting from a
``flight to quality,'' rose 88.12 points, or 3.4 percent, to
2,657.38, erasing nearly half the losses suffered in last week's
Friday the 13th plunge.
   The gain was the fourth-biggest point rise on record, although
it did not rank among the top percentage gainers. Volume totaled
416.29 million shares, also the fourth largest in history.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock markets around the world tumbled as foreigners reacted to
Wall Street's Friday plunge with a deluge of sell orders that
clogged exchanges from Tokyo to Lisbon.
   But analysts said that despite sharp drops in stock prices
Monday, the global backlash was nowhere near what it was two years
ago in the wake of Wall Street's Black Monday collapse.
   In Tokyo, the key 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average closed down
647.33 points, or 1.8 percent, at 34,468.69. London's Financial
Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index was down by more than 9
percent at one point but finished at its high of the day, off 70.5
points, or 3.2 percent, at 2,163.40.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush provided reassuring words in an
effort to calm gyrating financial markets while the Federal Reserve
backed up the words with $2 billion in cash poured into the U.S.
banking system.
   The Fed's supply of cash was viewed as a sizable effort on the
part of the central bank to contain the Friday the 13th stock
market plunge and make sure it did not have disastrous ripple
effects through the rest of the economy.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration conferred closely with
foreign allies, the Federal Reserve Board and Wall Street officials
through the weekend in mapping a strategy for averting a ``Black
Monday'' crisis that, in the end, never developed, sources said.
   Within the first hour of trading Monday on the New York Stock
Exchange, President Bush pointedly told reporters, ``I'm not
worried.'' Behind the business-as-usual image, however, the sources
said, was a weekend of intensive private consultations intended to
forestall an escalation of Friday's 190-point drop in the Dow Jones
Industrial Average.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donald Trump scrapped his proposed $7 billion
offer for AMR Corp. but said he was still considering making a
lower bid for the parent of American Airlines.
   Trump said Monday he was withdrawing his offer because of the
market volatility and its effect on AMR's stock. But he said he was
also considering increasing his holdings in AMR or selling his
stock.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   UAL Corp. stock plunged as the market followed
the lead of key banks that rejected financing for a $6.75 billion
cash buyout offer made for the parent of United Airlines by a
management-pilot group.
   Analysts differed Monday on whether the sharp fall in UAL stock
prices meant the death of a deal that collapsed Friday when the
buyout group announced it could not obtain financing for its
$300-a-share offer.
   Parties to the buyout said Monday that all sides were working to
restructure the offer. UAL stock plunged Monday nearly $60 a share
to close at $219.34.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan, in a
pitch for strong capital standards, told bankers at their annual
convention that banks like many other corporations today are highly
leveraged.
   Greenspan, addressing the American Bankers Association, on
Monday cited recent efforts by banks to build their capital, the
cushion that protects government insurance funds and by extension
the taxpayers from losses.
   But, he added, ``despite the progress many of you have made in
recent years ... capital levels for the industry remain at the low
end of their broad historical range.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Business sales far outpaced inventory
accumulation in August, the government said in a report that
suggested unsold goods aren't piling up and the economy is in
fairly strong shape.
   The Commerce Department said inventories edged up 0.3 percent to
a seasonally adjusted $789.9 billion while sales advanced a steep
3.1 percent to $526.8 billion. The pace in inventories was down
from a 0.9 percent hike in July while sales rose from a 0.9 decline
the previous month.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking Boeing Co. workers welcomed news that
contract talks with the company would resume Wednesday, but
wondered whether the aerospace giant would offer anything new.
   Boeing and the Machinists union were told Monday a meeting would
be held Wednesday in the offices of federal mediator Douglas
Hammond, two weeks after 57,800 workers walked off the job.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Blue-chip stocks bounded ahead Monday after a sharp wave of
early selling but prices of many other stocks trailed behind. The
Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, knocked down by a powerful
selling wave in the opening minutes of trading, later rallied 88.12
points to close at 2,657.38.
   The dollar finished mixed in hectic U.S. trading but above its
closing levels earlier in the day on overseas markets.
   Treasury bonds returned most of their gains from the year's
biggest rally last week as investors cashed in on a previous move
to safer fixed-income investments.
   Stock-index futures prices soared on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, erasing some investor fears and more than half of last
Friday's losses while easing jitters on other commodity markets.
Copper futures fell sharply while precious metals gained; grains
and soybeans rallied; livestock and meat futures retreated and
energy futures sagged.
</TEXT>
