<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-89 0150EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Markets-Explainer     10-17 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Markets-Explainer,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>With PM-Markets Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Will be updated with today's Japan and London stock index figures.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is look at the stock market's performance
Monday and why it happened.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>WHAT HAPPENED:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The Dow Jones industrials average of 30 major stocks rose 88.12
points, or 3.4 percent, to 2,657.38. The rebound, the fourth
largest in history, erased nearly half the losses suffered in last
week's Friday the 13th plunge, when the Dow Jones average fell
190.58 points.
   Volume totaled 416.29 million shares, the fourth highest ever.
   Broader indicators of the market were mixed. Declining issues
outnumbered gaining ones 5 to 4 in the overall tally of New York
Stock Exchange issues. The American Stock Exchange index and
over-the-counter index fell, but the New York Stock Exchange index
and Wilshire Equity Index were higher.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>WHY IT HAPPENED:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Analysts said many traders concluded that Friday's sharp drop
was an overreaction, and that the lower prices for stocks presented
buying opportunities. Investors concentrated their buying in
blue-chip stocks such as the Dow Jones industrial average
components because they were nervous about the market's outlook and
preferred high-quality issues, especially ones that would stand up
well in case of a recession.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>WHAT IT MEANS:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market historically has been regarded as a barometer
and forecaster of economic health, so the gyrations of Friday and
Monday raised questions about the outlook for the broader economy.
But economists say the short-term behavior of the market does not
give any clear picture about whether inflation or recession is more
or less likely.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>REFORMS SINCE THE CRASH:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   After Black Monday, Oct. 19, 1987, the nation's major stock and
futures exchanges voluntarily began cooperating to avoid panicky
selling that could contribute to similar collapses in the future.
   Few of those provisions went into effect Monday. One feature was
tripped when Standard &amp; Poor's 500 index futures contracts fell 5
points at the opening. An opening 5-point drop in those contracts
traded on the Chicago Merc triggers a 10-minute period during which
those contracts cannot be traded at any lower price.
   A spokeswoman for the Merc, Julie Jacobs, said that on Monday
buyers surfaced within seconds at prices matching or higher than
the opening price and trading was never interrupted.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>IMPORTANT MARKET INDEXES:</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   New York _ Dow Jones industrial average, closed Monday at
2,657.38, up 88.12.
   London _ Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index, closed
Monday at 2,163.4, down 70.5.
   Tokyo _ Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, closed
Monday at 34,468.69, down 647.33.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
