<DOCNO> AP891017-0223 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-89 0152EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Markets-Takeovers     10-17 0581</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Markets-Takeovers,0601</SECOND>
<HEAD>Takeovers Down, But Not Out, Observers Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Markets Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donald Trump's $7.5 billion buyout proposal for
AMR Corp. was one of the casualties of the upheaval on Wall Street,
but observers expect the takeover business to recover.
   Trump himself indicated Monday that he doesn't think the
takeover game is over. Although he shelved his $120-a-share bid for
AMR, he said he may yet make another offer at a lower price for the
parent of American Airlines.
   The developer attributed his withdrawal to the drop in AMR's
stock price _ he canceled his proposed bid after the price tumbled
$13.75 a share to $84.87{ _ and the volatility on Wall Street. AMR
closed $22.12{ lower on the day at $76.50.
   The Dow Jones industrial average recovered 88 points Monday
after plunging 190 points Friday, but other stocks lagged behind
blue-chip issues.
   If the takeover business follows the precedent set after the
market collapse of October 1987 _ when the Dow Jones average lost
508 points on Black Monday alone _ it will go through a lull and
then emerge from this crisis largely unscathed.
   Two years ago, several takeover deals were abandoned or put on
hold because the plunge in stock prices made the pre-crash offers
too expensive.
   Carl Icahn, chairman of Trans World Airlines Inc., postponed his
plans to take the airline private, and Dart Group Corp. gave up its
$6.62 billion bid for the retailer Dayton Hudson Corp.
   But Icahn achieved his goal a year later, and although Dart did
not renew its offer for Dayton Hudson, the company was back on the
takeover trail just three months after the crash with an
unsuccessful bid for Stop &amp; Shop Cos. Inc.
   And if you look at the broader picture, some of the biggest
takeovers of all time _ including the record $24.53 billion buyout
of RJR Nabisco Inc. by Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co. and the $12.9
billion acquisition of Kraft Inc. by Philip Morris Cos. Inc. _ were
under way within a year of Black Monday.
   ``I don't think (the market scare) will have any long-term
impact,'' said Israel Shaked, a professor at Boston University's
School of Management, looking at the record of takeovers since the
1987 crash.
   ``As long as we have companies that are undervalued and
companies that are mismanaged, takeovers will exist,'' Shaked said.
   There may be changes in how deals are financed, however,
especially because of recent reverses in the market for high
yielding junk bonds.
   The junk-bond market was shaken recently after several big
buyouts, including Campeau Corp.'s $6.6 billion takeover of
Federated Department Stores Inc., ran into trouble because the
target firms weren't generating enough cash to meet interest
payments on the risky debt securities.
   And although the planned employee-management buyout of UAL Corp.
didn't involve junk bonds, the failure of banks to come up with
loans to finance the $6.75 billion deal helped trigger Friday's
market tailspin.
   Bernard Black, a corporate finance professor at the Columbia
University School of Law, said buyers may be forced to depend more
on equity and less on debt to complete their deals.
   Still, deals will be aided by lower stock prices, because the
cost of buying a company falls along with the price of the firm's
shares.
   ``Low stock prices should be good for takeovers, not bad,''
Black said. ``We had nice healthy takeovers in 1983-86 with
substantially lower prices.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891017-0224 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-89 0125EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Markets-Analysis Bjt   10-17 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Markets-Analysis, Bjt,0598</SECOND>
<HEAD>Analysts: Stock Antics No Reason To Get Frantic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>An AP News Analysis</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the results of the past few tumultuous days
on Wall Street are eventually added up, many analysts contend they
will mean more pluses than minuses for American consumers and
businesses.
   Monday's 88.12-point rally in the Dow Jones industrial average,
to 2,657.38, went a long way toward calming fears that the stock
market was headed for some sort of replay of the Crash of 1987.
   In addition, the rebound seemed to buttress the view that
Friday's 190-point drop in the Dow stemmed mainly from concerns
about a single question _ the fading boom in corporate buyouts
financed with borrowed money.
   Stocks of two airline holding companies, UAL Corp. and AMR
Corp., plunged in Monday's trading, responding to news that
takeover proposals had run into snags or been withdrawn.
   But in marked contrast to Friday's session, the shares of many
blue-chip companies not involved in takeover news or rumors staged
a strong advance.
   If takeover speculation is indeed on the wane, observers say, it
would take away one of the prime forces that carried the stock
market to record highs as recently as a week ago Monday.
   However, they argue, it also could reduce the perils of credit
risk in the economy.
   ``The unwinding of excesses in leveraged buyouts and junk bonds
is very healthy,'' said Edward Yardeni, an economist at
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   Since the collapse of stock prices two years ago,
economy-watchers have come to see sudden swings in the financial
market in a new light.
   Unlike many past debacles, the Crash of 1987 neither
foreshadowed nor caused a recession. In fact, many analysts
contend, it may have helped keep the economy in healthy shape, in
part by prompting the Federal Reserve to relax its credit policy.
   Similarly, the jolt of Friday's selloff ``is likely to shake the
Fed into a more accommodative stance than it would have otherwise
pursued,'' said David Resler, an economist at Nomura Securities
International in New York.
   ``If we do see a recession in 1990, I don't think it would be a
result of this market drop.''
   If anything troubled observers about the stock market's recent
behavior, strange as it may sound, it was not so much Friday's
slump as it was the abrupt rebound Monday.
   The comeback seemed to betoken complacency, and perhaps an
all-too-eager readiness to dismiss the pre-weekend scare as a
harmless ``correction.''
   Yardeni, for one, suggested that the optimists might be
overlooking a developing downward trend in corporate profits and
other vital signs of the pace of business activity. ``There is some
genuine softness in the economy,'' he said.
   But as the market closed Monday evening, few observers claimed
they would have been preferred to go through another full-blown
crash.
   As for investors in stocks, mutual funds and other securities,
the markets' wild gyrations seemed to make a new and compelling
case for taking a long-term perspective.
   The volatile hour-by-hour atmosphere was full of potential
pitfalls for anyone who tried to anticipate or react to short-term
price fluctuations. For those who chose instead to ride out the
storm, the Dow Jones industrials' Monday close left it less than
two points away from where it stood three weeks earlier, at
2,659.19 on Sept. 25.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Business Writer Chet Currier has covered Wall
Street for The Associated Press since 1976.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
