<DOCNO> AP891017-0228 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-89 0215EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Banks-Greenspan     10-17 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Banks-Greenspan,0539</SECOND>
<HEAD>Greenspan Says Banks Are Too Highly Leveraged</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan, in a
pitch for strong capital standards, told bankers at their annual
convention that banks like many other corporations today are highly
leveraged.
   Greenspan, addressing the American Bankers Association on
Monday, cited recent efforts by banks to build their capital, the
cushion that protects government insurance funds and by extension
the taxpayers from losses.
   But, he added, ``despite the progress many of you have made in
recent years ... capital levels for the industry remain at the low
end of their broad historical range.''
   ``Current levels (of 6.3 percent of assets) are one-sixth the
levels of the mid-1800s, and are less than one-half the level some
50 years ago,'' he said.
   In some ways, the trend for banks mirrors the trend for
corporations generally, which in recent years have taken on more
debt, keeping their equity ratios low.
   Greenspan pointedly refrained from commenting on the sharp
dispute dividing two other banking agencies _ the Federal Deposit
Insurance Corp. and the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency.
   Both agencies have agreed on a new risk-based capital standard
that gives banks a break for holding relatively safe investments
such as government securities and home mortgages. However, they
disagree over a second capital standard, called a leverage ratio,
meant to stop banks from sharply reducing their capital by
restructuring their holdings.
   The FDIC, which insures bank deposits, is pushing for a leverage
ratio of 4.5 percent, but the comptroller's office, an arm of the
Treasury Department which charters national banks, wants 3 percent.
   FDIC Chairman L. William Seidman said the comptroller's proposal
would reduce standards for 90 percent of the nation's banks,
allowing the industry as a whole to hold $8 billion less of a
safety cushion. However, Comptroller Robert L. Clarke said
Seidman's proposal would dampen the features of the risk-based
standard designed to encourage banks to make safe investments.
   ``I do not wish to debate the details of which specific ratios
or standards are most appropriate to assess capital adequacy,''
Greenspan said. But ``it is important to keep in mind that, in both
relative and absolute terms, banking is a highly leveraged
industry.''
   He said bank owners have an incentive to minimize their capital
as a way of maximizing their stockholders' return. However, when a
financial institution holds inadequate capital, its owners do not
have the proper exposure to limit risky activity, he said.
   Moreover, the risks in banking today are arguably higher than
they were in the days when banks had higher capital ratios, the
chairman said.
   ``The number and size of failures we have seen in both the
banking and thrift industries demonstrate clearly that depository
institutions must maintain sound capital positions and be able to
deal with unexpected events,'' he said.
   Greenspan made only a brief reference to the turmoil in world
stock markets on Friday and Monday. Greenspan said the Fed had also
been in ``productive contact'' with foreign governments, but did
not elaborate on what actions the United States and other
governments were taking.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
