<FIRST>r f PM-Market-IndexFutures     10-17 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Market-Index Futures,0403</SECOND>
<HEAD>Program Traders Sit Out Markets' Rebound</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Markets-What A Day, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Program traders were notably absent as the stock
and stock-index futures markets rebounded, experts said.
   But it wasn't for lack of opportunity, as Standard &amp; Poor's 500
index futures sometimes traded at wide variances to the underlying
cash index Monday, offering potential profits for those willing to
buy one and sell the other.
   Futures ended the session at a sizeable premium. The contract
for December delivery of the 500 stocks tracked by the S&amp;P 500
index settled 15.65 points higher at 344.50 on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange while the cash index finished at 342.86.
   Traders and analysts speculated that program traders sat out the
session either out of caution or concern that their large-scale
trades might unnerve smaller investors.
   ``I would assume the firms that do program trading knew it was a
crucial day for people to have confidence in the market,'' said
William Finke, a vice president of Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in
Chicago.
   John Legittino, vice president of Elders Futures Inc., guessed
that the computer traders were ``sitting on the sidelines to see
how the whole thing unfolds.''
   Stock-index futures are contracts to buy or sell baskets of
stocks at specified prices by a specified date.
   Program trading employs computers to buy and sell huge blocks of
stocks and index futures in an attempt to profit from minute
differences in prices on the two markets. The practice can cause
rapid price swings and is believed by some to have accelerated the
stock-market collapse of Oct. 19, 1987.
   Traders and analysts attributed Monday's rally to a resurgence
of investor confidence following a 30-point plunge in the S&amp;P 500
futures on Friday, when the Dow Jones industrial average plunged by
190 points.
   The Dow rallied by just over 88 points on Monday.
   In addition to the dearth of program trading, experts said
supportive factors included the encouraging performance of the
Tokyo Stock Exchange earlier Monday, where the main market
barometer fell by a modest 1.8 percent, and the stated
determination of British Airways PLC to continue with an
employee-management group to seek to buy United Airlines' parent
UAL Corp.
   Failure of the buyout group to arrange financing of the deal
helped trigger Friday's market plunge.
</TEXT>
