<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru   10-17 0557</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru,0575</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tokyo Stocks Rebound Sharply Follow New York's Lead</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 14th graf pvs, Elsewhere in ..., to UPDATE with Hong Kong
close</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange rebounded
sharply today and the dollar rallied as Monday's strong recovery on
Wall Street restored confidence in the financial markets.
   Other Asian stock markets also surged ahead today, apparently
reassured that a repeat of the global crash of 1987 wasn't in the
making.
   News that the Dow Jones industrial average rose by more than 88
points on Monday, reversing almost half of Friday's big 190-point
selloff, helped propel the Tokyo market to its second-biggest point
gain of the year.
   The Nikkei Stock Average jumped by 527.39 points, or 1.53
percent, to 34,996.08. The rally erased most of Monday's
647.33-point plunge.
   Traders said volume was a moderate 650 million shares, up from
Monday's thin total of 520 million shares.
   Japanese Finance Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto praised coordination
between financial authorities of the Group of Seven leading
industrial nations during the stock crisis. He also repeated
remarks he made Monday that he wasn't seriously concerned about the
impact of Friday's plunge in New York.
   ``I don't think markets moved that sharply,'' he said at a press
conference after a regular Cabinet meeting.
   A dealer at Nomura Securities, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said one reason Friday's Wall Street plunge didn't lead
to another crash was because interest rates are lower today than
two years ago.
   ``The crash in New York (on Friday) was not linked to uneasiness
about funds, as was the crash of Black Monday,'' the dealer said,
referring to the record 508-point fall in the Dow industrials on
Oct. 19, 1987.
   But Haruhito Ichimura, a trader with Nippon Kangyo Kakumaru
Securities, said it was too early to tell whether Wall Street had
recovered completely from its fall.
   Mitsuhiko Kinugasa, a dealer with Daiwa Bank, said there were
rumors Tuesday that Japanese banks again were backing away from a
revised plan for financing a buyout of United Airlines' parent
company, although they had little impact on share prices.
   The refusal of banks, many Japanese, to support the proposed
$6.75 billion buyout helped trigger last Friday's plunge on Wall
Street. A Citibank spokesman in Tokyo said the bank was presenting
a revised financing package for a bid of $250 a share, down from
$300 a share under the original plan, but United's pilots denied
there was any formal offer at the lower price.
   The U.S. dollar ended trading at 142.25 yen in Tokyo, up 1.50
yen from Monday. It moved within a range of 141.80 yen to 142.35
yen during the day.
   Elsewhere in Asia Tuesday, Hong Kong's Hang Seng Index surged
94.20 points to close at 2695.90, recovering some of the ground
lost Monday when it fell 6.5 percent.
   Indexes in Australia and New Zealand, which fell about 8 percent
on Monday, finished today with gains of 3.8 percent and 5.7
percent, respectively.
   Taiwan's stock index gained 410.32 points to close at 10,100.52.
It was the market's biggest one-day point gain ever and more than
erased Monday's decline of 329.48.
   ``The recovery on Wall Street relieves worries over a worldwide
crash and draws bargain-hunters,'' said one Taiwan broker, who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Share prices rebounded in Thailand and the Philippines.
</TEXT>
