<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet10am     10-17 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 10am,0390</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An unexpectedly poor U.S. trade report knocked
some buying enthusiasm out of the stock market this morning and
Wall Street got off to a weak start.
   But a barrage of sell orders in the opening minutes appeared to
be subsiding. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks, off
more than 20 points in the first quarter hour of trading, was down
12.92 at 2,644.46 at 10 a.m. EDT.
   In the broader market, declining issues outnumbered advances on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 761 down, 330 up and 472
unchanged.
   The NYSE composite index of all its listed common stocks was 1
point lower at 188.76.
   Much of today's initial selling was traced to news that the U.S.
trade deficit, after two straight monthly declines, rose to $10.77
billion in August. The Commerce Department said the August
shortfall represented nearly a 31 percent increase from the revised
July deficit of $8.24 billion.
   But market analysts also said stocks were vulnerable after
Monday's uneven recovery, which was concentrated mainly in the blue
chip sector.
   In the early going, blue chip issues again dominated the list of
actively traded NYSE stocks.
   Philip Morris lost 1 to 42\, International Business Machines
fell 1| to 101], American Telephone &amp; Telegraph dropped | to 42],
Chevron gained [ to 64 and General Electric was off ] to 56[.
   Ford Motor, which announced it has raised its stake in Jaguar to
10.4 percent from 5 percent, fell } to 50.
   AMR, which tumbled Monday after investor Donald Trump said he
was withdrawing his $7 billion for the airline holding company,
lost another 2} to 73}.
   On Monday, the Dow Jones industrial average recouped almost half
of its Friday the 13th 190-point loss, jumping 88.12 to 2,657.38.
It was the fourth biggest point gain on record.
   NYSE volume totaled 416.29 million shares, the fourth heaviest
ever, and significantly more than the 251.17 million shares that
changed hands in Friday's selloff.
   Declining issues outnumbered advancing ones in nationwide
trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed shares by about 4 to 3,
with 975 stocks down in price, 749 up and 279 unchanged.
   The NYSE's composite index rebounded by 4.20 to 189.76.
</TEXT>
