<FIRST>u f PM-Budget 1stLd-Writethru   10-17 0621</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Budget, 1st Ld-Writethru,0639</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thorny Issues Holding Up Deficit-Reduction Bill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 8 grafs new, updating with new meetings today; picks up
8th graf pvs, Panetta and Speaker.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House and Senate Democratic leaders met today
to map out strategy for completing an emergency deficit-reduction
bill that would roll back automatic spending cuts mandated by the
Gramm-Rudman law.
   But the White House said it may no longer accept legislation to
reverse the arbitrary cutbacks, which slash more than $8 billion
each from defense and domestic programs to reduce the federal
deficit.
   ``There is some feeling here that (the automatic cuts) are the
way to go. It will reduce spending in a very effective fashion,''
said Marlin Fitzwater, the White House spokesman who announced
Monday night that President Bush had ordered the cuts as required
by the Gramm-Rudman law.
   The White House and the Senate had pushed the House to accept
Monday their deal on a ``stripped-down'' deficit package, which
would have allowed Bush to avoid ordering the cuts.
   The House brushed aside that suggestion. Leaders of both parties
said they could not so easily jettison their version of the budget
bill, which included action on some of the year's most contentious
issues.
   In two weeks of sometimes furious debate, the House voted to cut
the capital gains tax, multiply federal aid for child care and
repeal the Medicare catastrophic illness plan _ along with a host
of other political favorites.
   ``We're not suddenly going to abandon them,'' said Rep. Leon
Panetta, D-Calif., chairman of the House Budget Committee.
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, met with House
Democratic leaders on the topic this morning. He said formal
negotiations between the two chambers could begin as early as this
afternoon.
   Panetta and Speaker Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash., spent Monday
meeting with other House leaders. Panetta said they hope to develop
a plan this week to produce a House-Senate deficit reduction bill
and send the Senate a separate bill including the other issues
without forcing new House votes.
   Rep. Bill Frenzel, R-Minn., the ranking Republican on the Budget
Committee, said GOP members wanted to make sure their favorite
measures in the old House bill retained their status.
   ``We are anxious to work with the Democrats to obviate the
need'' for the Gramm-Rudman cuts, he said. But Republicans, he
said, were ``a little less frantic.''
   The order signed by Bush Monday night cut 4.3 percent from
Pentagon programs and 5.3 percent from domestic agencies, except
for Social Security and poverty programs.
   The cuts would reduce the deficit for fiscal 1990 by $16.1
billion. They were required by the Gramm-Rudman law because
Congress and the president have not been able to agree on an
alternative way to cut the projected deficit below $110 billion.
   Although few immediate disruptions were expected in the short
term, the cuts could have widespread effects if not reversed.
Layoffs in the military, furloughs of air traffic controllers and
cancellation of thousands of student loans could be expected.
   Richard Darman, the president's budget director, also said he
thought sticking with the across-the-board cuts might be better
than accepting legislation to undo them.
   Sen. James Sasser, D-Tenn., the chairman of the Senate Budget
Committee, said the deficit bill could have been in place weeks ago
except for the administration's ``obsession'' with attaching to it
the president's cherished capital gains tax cut.
   He said if the automatic cuts were to remain in place, it would
put ``a real torpedo in the side of education'' and other important
programs, such as defense and fighting illegal drugs, which Bush
supports.
   Darman's ``bellicose statements'' that he'd accept the cuts
amounted to ``a lot of breast-beating,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
