<DOCNO> AP891017-0238 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-89 1109EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Boeing     10-17 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boeing,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boeing, Machinists To Talk Wednesday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Boeing Co. has agreed to resume negotiations
with striking Machinists but called off talks with engineers
seeking a new labor contract because of ``grossly excessive''
pay-raise demands.
   Boeing spokesman Harold Carr said the company and the Seattle
Professional Engineering Employees Association met Monday, the
first of two days of negotiations.
   ``The company has advised SPEEA that because of its unrealistic
and grossly excessive economic proposal,'' Boeing canceled a
meeting scheduled for today, Carr said Monday.
   The union, which represents 28,000 engineers and technical
support workers, said last week it was seeking pay raises of 19
percent in the first year and 8 percent in the second and third
years of a three-year contract. The current contract expires Dec. 1.
   Dan Mahoney, engineers' union spokesman, late Monday had no
comment on Boeing's action.
   Sepparately, Boeing agreed to return Wednesday to the bargaining
table with the Machinists. Federal mediator Doug Hammond said he
believes the time is right to resume talks.
   A strike by 57,800 members of the International Association of
Machinists and Aerospace Workers enters its third week Wednesday.
   Carr refused to say if the company had improved its offer.
   ``We welcome a chance to see whether Boeing has re-evaluated its
position,'' union spokesman Matt Bates said.
   The Machinists walked out on Oct. 4. They voted 85 percent
against a new contract offer from the world's largest commercial
jet builder, which is enjoying its fifth straight year of
record-high orders.
   About 43,300 strikers are in the Seattle area, 12,000 in
Wichita, Kan., 1,700 in Portland, Ore. and lesser numbers at a
half-dozen other locations.
   Boeing's three-year offer to the Machinists included wage hikes
of 4 percent, 3 percent and 3 percent, bonuses of 8 percent of
gross pay this year and 3 percent in 1990, a cost-of-living clause
almost matching inflation, a reduction in mandatory overtime and
increases in some benefits.
</TEXT>
