<SECOND>BC-Jaguar-Ford,0171</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ford Increases Stake in Jaguar to 10.4 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. said Tuesday it raised its stake in
the luxury car maker Jaguar PLC to 10.4 percent from 5 percent.
   The U.S. auto maker said it held 19 million Jaguar shares at the
end trading Monday.
   The increase signals Ford's commitment to pursue the purchase of
up to 15 percent of Jaguar, possibly as the prelude to a full bid.
   Some analysts had speculated that Ford might withdraw its plans,
announced in mid-September, because of an expected production and
equity-sharing link between Jaguar and General Motors Corp.
   Jaguar is negotiating a deal with GM that would maintain the
British company's independence, and Jaguar has spurned Ford's
approaches.
   Under Jaguar's by-laws, Ford and other outside shareholders are
prohibited from acquiring more than 15 percent of the company until
the end of next year.
   The condition was imposed by the British government when it
privatized Jaguar in 1984.
