<FIRST>u f PM-Markets-Bonds     10-17 0576</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Markets-Bonds,0607</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bonds Up, Again Taking Different Path From Stocks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: stand for PM-Bonds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Treasury bonds made moderate price gains
today as the market once again rallied at the expense of an
unsteady stock market.
   Market analysts said a downturn in stock prices today, following
Monday's partial rebound from the sharp loss on Friday, sent many
investors and to the relative safety of bonds.
   ``The outlook seems to have worsened for stocks,'' said Robert
A. Brusca, chief financial economist for Nikko Securities Co.
International.
   At noon EDT, the Dow Jones industrial average was down 27.87 at
2,629.51.
   The stock market was concerned, in part, over the release of a
government report today showing the nation's August trade deficit
widening to $10.77 billion from a revised July deficit of $8.24
billion.
   Bond investors weren't as worried, analysts said.
   ``Depsite the fact that the trade deficit was worse than people
had generally looked for, it gave evidence that production in the
U.S was sluggish and the economy of the U.S. is not strong at the
moment,'' explained Carol A. Stone, senior economist for Nomura
Securities Inc.
   Fanning that feeling about the economy, as well as hopes that
interest rates had room to decline, was another government report
today showing industrial production edging down 0.1 percent in
September, she said.
   By midday today in the secondary market for Treasury bonds, the
bellwether 30-year issue was up | point, or $6.25 per $1,000 face
amount. Its yield, which moves inversely from its price, fell to
7.91 percent from 7.97 percent.
   The closely watched issue fell around $17.50 on Monday, wiping
out nearly all of the huge gains from Friday's rally.
   Prices of short-term government issues were up around \ point,
intermediate maturities rose between \ point and ] point and
long-term issues rose between ] point and } point, according to
figures provided by Telerate Inc., a financial-information service.
   The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the
price of a bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Hutton Daily Treasury Bond Index, which
measures price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with
maturities of a year or longer, stood at 1,191.08, up 1.93.
   Meanwhile, yields on three-month Treasury bills fell to 7.48
percent as the discount fell 10 basis points to 7.26 percent.
Yields on six-month bills fell to 7.77 percent as the discount fell
2 basis point to 7.39 percent. Yields on one-year bills fell to
7.69 percent as the discount fell 14 basis points to 7.20 percent.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, traded at 8 11-16 percent, up from 8| percent late Monday.
   In corporate bond trading, highly rated issues gained ground.
Moody's Investment Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures total
return on a portfolio of 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five
years or longer, rose 0.39 to 337.04.
   High-yield ``junk'' bonds continued to improve from Friday, when
trading was at a near-standstill. Traders said prices of the more
widely traded issues ranged from { point down to { point up.
   But unlike the Treasury market, the junk market was moving in a
closer direction to stocks.
   ``They're tracking equities,'' said Robert Lupo, a managing
director Smith Barney, Upham &amp; Co. ``They seem to be married to
each other.''
   In the tax-exempt market, prices of municipal bonds were mixed,
traders said.
