<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-89 1243EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Continental-Options     10-17 0584</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Continental-Options,0606</SECOND>
<HEAD>Firm Rocked by Market's Slide Gets Guarantees</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two financial exchanges are among parties that
have agreed to help guarantee backing for an options trading firm
hit hard by Friday's stock market collapse, a spokesman for
Continental Bank's options unit said Tuesday.
   Under the rescue plan, most of the customer accounts of
Chicago-based Fossett Corp. are being transferred to First Options
of Chicago, the bank's option's unit, said First Options spokesman
Bill Murschel.
   The unit agreed over the weekend to acquire Fossett's customer
accounts in exchange for financial guarantees from the Chicago
Board Options Exchange, the American Stock Exchange and
Chicago-based Options Clearing Corp., Murschel said in a telephone
interview.
   About 200 Fossett accounts are being transferred to First
Options in a transaction expected to be completed Tuesday, he said.
   The clearing corporation, which is owned by the nation's options
markets, pledged $20 million, while the CBOE offered $8 million in
guarantees and the American Stock Exchange offered $4 million, the
Chicago Tribune reported in Tuesday's editions, citing sources it
did not identify.
   Stephen Fossett, the company's president, pledged about $18
million to the Continental operation for a total of $50 million.
   Fossett was not in his office and did not immediately return a
telephone message seeking comment on how much his firm lost last
Friday.
   But sources who asked not to be identified told The Associated
Press $50 million is the worst loss Fossett would face if the
market continues to slide.
   That loss would have had to appear to be likely for Fossett to
agree to the transfer, sources said, adding that it probably won't
be determined until the end of the week if the guarantees will be
needed.
   The transfer of accounts is not unusual, the sources said, but
the guarantees offered by the exchanges are unprecedented.
   ``If a given firm is experiencing troubles, and it was obvious
late Friday that this firm was experiencing troubles, the clearing
organization can step in and work with that firm ... and transfer
accounts of that firm to a healthy firm,'' said a source who asked
not to be identified.
   The Fossett firm processes and guarantees trades of close to 200
professional options traders known as market makers. There was
concern that the firm wouldn't be able to meet numerous demands for
cash to back losing options positions if Friday's market decline
spilled over into Monday.
   Murschel said the transfer of accounts was taking place despite
the market's imrpovement Monday.
   Under the agreement, assets of the firm and its president would
be used first, followed by those of the clearing corporation, the
CBOE and Amex.
   ``We felt it was very important that Fossett not be allowed to
liquidate,'' said Alger Chapman, CBOE chairman. ``So did the
Options Clearing Corp. and the American Stock Exchange.
   ``It was simply not in the market's interest to have to
liquidate a firm coming on the heels of Friday, when the market
dropped 190 points,'' Chapman said.
   ``It is the first time we have taken such a step, and hopefully
it will be the last,'' he said.
   Continental and its federal regulators wanted the guarantees to
limit the bank's exposure in the event of a continued market
collapse, the newspaper said.
   Again citing unidentified sources, the Tribune said Continental
was especially concerned about the potential damage because of its
own options troubles during the stock market crash two years ago.
   Heavy losses at that time saddled the bank unit with a $90
million loss.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
