<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-MCI     10-17 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-MCI,0228</SECOND>
<HEAD>MCI Posts Strong Profit and Revenue Gains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   MCI Communications Corp., the nation's second
largest long-distance telephone company, Tuesday reported nearly a
60 percent gain in third-quarter earnings on 23 percent revenue
growth.
   Income in the quarter ended Sept. 30 came to $165 million, or 62
cents a share, compared to $104 million, or 38 cents a share, a
year earlier.
   Revenue rose to $1.67 billion from $1.36 billion in 1988's third
quarter.
   MCI reported that the volume of residential calls increased
faster than business volumes, due largely to the introduction of a
new PrimeTime calling plan and expansion of operator and pay
telephone services.
   During the quarter, the Washington-based company announced
several major commercial contracts to provide telecommunications
services, including a deal with Congress.
   ``The company continued to garner a greater share of the
business market, and is making new inroads into the $23 billion
consumer market,'' said Bert C. Roberts Jr., MCI president and
chief operating officer.
   For the first nine months of this year, MCI's after-tax earnings
more than doubled to $450 million, or $1.69 a share, from $224
million, or 78 cents a share, in the corresponding 1988 period.
   Revenue rose about 28 percent to $4.76 billion from $3.71
billion for the first nine months of last year.
</TEXT>
