<HEAD>Honeywell Reports Third-Quarter Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honeywell Inc., helped by a strong
performance in its space and aviation division, Tuesday reported
third-quarter earnings of $74.4 million compared with a $41.4
million loss a year earlier.
   But sales sagged to $1.726 billion from $1.729 billion.
   Last year's third-quarter results included a pre-tax charge of
$108 million related to unrecoverable contract costs, which was
partially offset by a pre-tax real estate gain of $12.3 million.
   Earnings per share of $1.73 for the three months ended Oct. 1,
compared with a per-share loss of 98 cents in the comparable 1988
quarter.
   Nine-month net income was $212.1 million, compared with $47.9
million in the corresponding 1988 period. Nine-month earnings per
share were $4.92, compared with $1.13 last year.
   Sales for the first nine months of 1989 were $5.17 billion, off
about 0.8 percent from $5.22 billion in 1988.
   Nine-month 1988 figures included pre-tax charges related to
unrecoverable contract costs and a discontinued product line of
$177 million and real estate gains of $27.2 million, Honeywell said.
   Honeywell Chairman and Chief Executive Officer James J. Renier
said Space and Aviation Systems operating profit increased
significantly in the third quarter, reflecting continued strong
performance in commercial flight systems and recovery in military
avionics systems.
   Home and Building Automation and Control operating profit also
was up strongly, reflecting strength in building services and
continued satisfactory performance in a difficult new-construction
market, he said.
   Honeywell said it expects to complete the sale next week of
approximately 16 percent of the outstanding common stock of its
Tokyo-based partner, Yamatake-Honeywell, for approximately $280
million.
   Proceeds from the sale will be used in the company's previously
announced program to repurchase up to 10 million of its shares.
