<FIRST>r f AM-Showbiz     10-17 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Showbiz,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>Company in the Spotlight After Monday Night Football Exposure</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAND ISLAND, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The telephone was ringing off the hook
Tuesday at a company that specializes in belly dancers and ``exotic
apes,'' courtesy of some unexpected advertising on Monday Night
Football.
   The ABC telecast pitting the Los Angeles Rams and Buffalo Bills
showed a classified ad placed last week in the Buffalo News
designed to recharge the Bills' sluggish defense.
   But the camera shot also took in the ad that appeared just above
it in the News: ``BELLY &amp; hula dancers, exotic apes, male dancers,
773-2433.''
   ABC announcers Frank Gifford and Dan Dierdorf joked about the
belly dancers and emphasized they weren't advising people to call
the number. That, of course, caught the attention of a nationwide
audience looking for some thrills during what had been a dull game
up to that point.
   As of Tuesday, at least 75 people phoned the Showbiz
Entertainment Service run by Nick and Marlene Sidoti out of their
home in Grand Island, located just north of Buffalo.
   ``For a $4 ad, I got myself $75,000 or $100,000 worth of
advertising,'' Sidoti said. ``Thank you, ABC.''
   From Connecticut to California, from West Virginia to Utah, fans
decided to have a little fun _ by ordering out for a hula dancer.
   ``They were asking if we could send entertainment over for
halftime,'' Sidoti said. ``One guy said, `Why did you put the ad
on? Why didn't you just put the belly dancers on?'''
   Some callers asked about a job as a dancer. Some businessmen
called to ask how the Sidotis had arranged the nationwide
publicity. And some callers were just grateful.
   ``One lady from South Carolina said, `It was very nice of you to
sponsor the game, so I can see it on TV.'''
   Asked on Tuesday why the ad seemed to catch people's fancy,
Sidoti told the Buffalo News, ``People sit down, watch TV, get all
psyched and they get crazy. So there is a whole market out there.
There's definitely a captive audience.''
</TEXT>
