<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-89 1544EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-PepsiCo     10-17 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-PepsiCo,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>Posts 11.5 Percent Increase in 3rd-Qtr Profit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PepsiCo Inc. said Tuesday that third-quarter
profit rose 11.5 percent, reflecting advances in the company's soft
drink, snack food and restaurant businesses.
   The Purchase, N.Y.-based company said earnings rose to a record
for any quarter of $269.3 million, or $1.02 per share, in the three
months ended Sept. 9 compared with $241.6 million, or 91 cents a
share, a year earlier.
   Third-quarter revenue rose to $3.90 billion from $3.13 billion a
year earlier.
   The 1988 figures included an after-tax loss of $5.9 million on
the sale of a winery in Spain.
   In the latest quarter, operating profit in the soft drink
business rose 36 percent to $205.7 million on a 26 percent sales
increase to $1.55 billion.
   Excluding the loss on the winery sales and the impact of recent
acquisitions and sales in the domestic soft drink business,
operating profits were up 12 percent, PepsiCo said.
   Improvement in domestic operating margins and higher prices
offset a decline in international results that reflected
acceleration of concentrate shipments and higher marketing spending.
   Operating profit from snack foods including Frito-Lay products
rose 30 percent to $211 million while sales rose 27 percent to
$1.06 billion in the quarter.
   The results included strong worldwide volume gains and
continuing margin improvements as well as the acquisition in July
of Smiths and Walkers, two leading snack chip companies in the
United Kingdom.
   Worldwide earnings from restaurant operations rose 25 percent to
$139.1 million while sales rose 22 percent to almost $1.3 billion
in the quarter.
   Operating earnings jumped 33 percent to $62.2 million at Pizza
Hut and 50 percent to $40.5 million at Taco Bell, but fell 4
percent to $36.4 million at Kentucky Fried Chicken, where a strong
international performance was offset by a decline in domestic
operations due to lower customer counts, higher labor costs and
higher chicken prices.
   For the first nine months of the fiscal year, PepsiCo said it
earned $699.3 million, or $2.64 a share, up 21.7 percent from
$574.5 million, or $2.18 a share, a year ago.
   Nine-month revenue rose 22.8 percent to $10.45 billion from
$8.51 billion a year earlier.
   The 1989 results included an after-tax net credit of $15.0
million stemming mainly from a decision to retain a foreign
bottling operation once held for sale, while the 1988 results
reflected an after-tax charge of $16.3 million for reorganizing
domestic soft drink operations and the winery loss.
</TEXT>
