<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Media 1stLd-Writethru   10-17 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Media, 1st Ld-Writethru,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>McGraw Hill, Scripps Have Higher Earnings</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Rewrites thruout to UPDATE with McGraw-Hill, Scripps earnings.
No pickup. ^Precedes ITHACA, N.Y.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   McGraw-Hill Inc. reported Tuesday that third-quarter earnings
gained 9 percent from a year ago, while another large media
company, E.W. Scripps Co., said quarterly earnings jumped 35
percent.
   Park Communications Inc., a smaller communications concern based
in Ithaca, New York, said earnings fell 2 percent in the third
quarter.
   New York-based McGraw-Hill's earnings for the three months ended
Sept. 30 totaled $64.11 million or $1.31 a share, compared with
earnings of $58.75 million or $1.21 per share in 1988. Revenue rose
8.5 percent to $452.18 million from $416.69 million.
   Scripps, based in Cincinnati, said it earned $18 million or 23
cents a share in the third quarter on revenue of $304.25 million.
That compared with earnings of $13.4 million, or 17 cents a share
on revenue of $293.24 million.
   Park said quarterly earnings totaled $3.86 million, down from
$3.95 million a year earlier. Earnings per share remained at 19
cents, reflecting the impact of a 3-for-2 stock split. Revenue
totaled $39.26 million, up from $39.11 million.
   McGraw-Hill Chairman Joseph L. Dionne said the company had
growth in its publishing division, partly because of a solid
performance by its weekly magazine Business Week, and its financial
services companies. However, he said the information services
division showed a slight decline.
   For the first nine months of this year, McGraw-Hill earned
$146.05 million or $2.99 a share on $1.27 billion in revenue. Last
year earnings totaled $130.53 million or $2.69 a share on $1.19
billion in revenue.
   Scripps President Lawrence A. Leser said the company had strong
improvement in its publishing segment but that broadcasting results
came under pressure from weak advertising.
   In the first three quarters, Scripps' earnings totaled $58.3
million or 74 cents a share, vs. $47.6 million or 64 cents a share
a year earlier. Revenue rose 4.7 percent to $920.05 million from
$878.74 million.
   Roy Park, Park Communications' chairman, said broadcast revenue
for the third quarter was flat, while newspaper revenue rose
slightly.
   For the first nine months, Park Communications' earnings fell to
$12.54 million from $12.70 million. Earnings per share were 61
cents, the same as in 1988. Revenue was $119 million, up $1.7
million over 1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
