<FIRST>u f AM-Markets-Europe     10-17 0643</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Markets-Europe,0669</SECOND>
<HEAD>Most European Markets Regain, But Not London</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Markets Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most of Europe's stock markets partly recovered
Tuesday in a seesaw session, but the key London market fell and
nervousness about Wall Street's behavior persisted.
   Frankfurt, which suffered a record drop Monday, saw big gains in
urgent buying. Market indexes also finished higher in Paris,
Amsterdam, Milan, Zurich, Madrid, Athens, Vienna, Stockholm and
Oslo.
   The upward and downward moves were much less dramatic than
Monday's gyrations, which followed Wall Street's Friday the 13th
slump.
   Trading disruptions continued in Europe Tuesday. The Brussels
exchange had computer problems for a second day, preventing
significant trading since Friday.
   ``Once the confidence of the small investors has been hurt, it
will be difficult to return to a sustained upward trend,'' said
Jens Wiecking, institutional adviser at the Duesseldorf investment
firm Merck, Finck and Co.
   In the morning, European stock prices followed Tokyo's climb on
relief over New York's relatively strong finish Monday, which
suggested that an all-out crash appeared to have been averted.
   Earlier in Tokyo Tuesday, the Nikkei index closed 527.39 points,
or 1.3 percent, higher at 34,996.08, recouping most of the 1.8
percent lost on Monday.
   But European share prices fell in the afternoon on
worse-than-expected U.S. trade figures and on a subsequent weak
opening on Wall Street.
   The U.S. trade deficit rose to $10.77 billion, compared with
market expectations of around $9.1 billion.
   In London, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index
fell 27.9 points, or 1.3 percent, to close at 2,135.5.
   The Financial Times 30-share index ended 29.6 points lower at
1,730.7. The Financial Times 500-share index fell 8.63 points to
close at 1,181.74.
   Volume totaled 643.4 million shares Tuesday vs. 959.3 million
shares Monday.
   The London session was jittery with the key index swinging 61.5
points from a session high of 2,182.3 in the first 15 minutes of
official dealings to a low of 2,120.8 in the last 40 minutes of
trading.
   But that was less dramatic than Monday, when the London index
fell more than 200 points and then mostly recovered to finish with
a 70.5 point decline.
   Dealers said London was buffeted throughout the session by
crosscurrents from Wall Street and fears about the U.S. trade
figures.
   ``Our market is behaving like a puppet on a string,'' said a
senior dealer at Barclays de Zoete Wedd Ltd. ``All markets are, and
Wall Street is controlling the strings.''
   The Dow Jones industrial average was down 27.87 points, or 1
percent, at 2,629.51 at about the time London closed.
   The Dow Jones industrial average bounced back 88 points Monday
after its 190-point plunge on Friday.
   ``Everyone is still very nervous about the down side,'' said a
dealer with the London investment firm UBS Phillips and Drew.
``Also buyers who passed up bargains Monday decided to hold off
today to see if they'd come back later in the week.''
   The German Stock Index (DAX), which had plunged 12.8 percent in
its worst one-day drop ever Monday, soared 89.72 points, or 6.4
percent, to 1,475.44.
   Frankfurt's trading volume even surpassed Monday's frenzied pace
as small retail investors rushed to buy back some of the stocks
they had dumped, and institutional funds exploited lower prices to
boost their holdings.
   But the early enthusiasm soon gave way to a more sober
assessment and profit-taking late in the session, which was
extended by one hour to process all the orders.
   The Madrid Stock Market's General index rose 5.96 points, or 2
percent, to a close at 311.18. The index fell 6.5 percent Monday.
   In Zurich, the Swiss Market Index rose 82.3 points, or 5.1
percent, to 1,705.2. It declined 10.5 percent in the previous
session.
   The Athens Stock Exchange General Index rose 42.65 points, or
9.4 percent, to 497.79. It dropped 10.05 percent on Monday.
</TEXT>
