<FIRST>u f PM-MarketsRdp 8thLd-Writethru   10-17 0801</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Markets Rdp, 8th Ld-Writethru,0828</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dow Falls Again, Stocks Retreat After Two Wild Sessions</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to UPDATE with closing Dow Jones average,
picks up 3rd graf pvs, The Dow...; SUBS grafs 15-16, Traders were ... million
shares., with 2 grafs to UPDATE with details on stock market. Picks up
17th graf pvs, Stocks rallied ...</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos, LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks retreated today following two of the
wildest sessions on Wall Street since the October 1987 market crash.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks fell 18.65 points
to 2,638.73 after spiking down as much as 63 points around 11:30
a.m. Broader market indicators also fell.
   The Dow average had plummeted 190.58 points on Friday and
bounced back with an 88.12-point gain on Monday, leaving investors
groping for stable ground.
   The Commerce Department handed the market some bad news today
with its report that the merchandise trade deficit rose nearly 31
percent in August to $10.77 billion from a revised July deficit of
$8.24 billion.
   But analysts did not all agree that the big trade deficit was a
major factor in today's stock decline. Some noted that bonds and
the dollar _ which are most sensitive to bad trade figures _ held
up relatively well.
   The dollar recovered after a sharp drop that followed the trade
report, while bonds were mixed _ an indication that investors were
not seriously worried about worsening inflation and higher interest
rates.
   The Federal Reserve injected another $1.5 billion into the
banking system today after adding $2 billion in reserves on Monday.
   Banks will be able to use the new reserves to make loans,
including coming to the assistance of brokerage firms caught in a
cash squeeze because of the drop in stock prices.
   The Fed adds reserves by repurchasing Treasury securities from
the banks, and that puts fresh cash in the banks' hands.
   Stocks remain somewhat unstable after the drastic moves of the
past two sessions, some analysts said.
   ``There's much more going on in the stock market at the moment
than the trade numbers,'' said Lawrence A. Veit, international
economist at Brown Brothers Harriman &amp; Co.
   ``You'll tend to see somewhat accentuated volatility this week
and next,'' said Giulio Martini, economist at Sanford C. Bernstein
&amp; Co.
   Monday's gain was concentrated in blue-chip stocks, which
benefited from a ``flight to quality'' by nervous investors. It
came on trading volume of 416.29 million shares, the heaviest ever
except for the week of the 1987 market crash. The index's gain was
the fourth-biggest point gain, although it was not among the
biggest percentage gainers.
   Many economists had expected the latest trade deficit to be
about $9 billion, and Veit said he believed the sharp rise could
turn out to be a statistical freak.
   Traders were worried about the outlook for the
employee-management buyout proposal for UAL Corp. The stock fell
another $25.67{ a share to $197.25 after tumbling about $57 a share
Monday, and that contributed to the overall market weakness.
   In the overall New York Stock Exchange today, declining issues
outpaced advances by almost 3 to 2. Volume on the New York Stock
Exchange totaled a heavier-than-usual 224.07 million shares, with
the heaviest action in the early going.
   Stocks rallied in Tokyo in response to Wall Street's strength of
Monday, but London's market lost ground in sympathy with today's
weakness on the New York Stock Exchange.
   In Tokyo, where Tuesday trading ended before New York opened for
business, the Nikkei Stock Average jumped by 527.39 points, or 1.5
percent, to 34,996.08 today. The gain was the second biggest on the
Japanese market this year and erased most of Monday's 647.33-point
decline.
   In London, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index
fell 27.9 points, or more than 1 percent, to close at 2,135.5.
   In New York on Monday, declining issues outnumbered advancing
ones by a 5-4 margin on the New York Stock Exchange. Indexes of the
American Stock Exchange and over-the-counter stocks fell, while the
New York Stock Exchange composite index and Wilshire Equity Index
rose.
   Friday's 190-point drop had raised fears of a repeat of October,
1987, when a Friday decline turned into an Oct. 19, Monday rout
that knocked a record 508 points off the average. That did not turn
out to be the case this time.
   Traders said the stock market benefited Monday from the
experience gained in the 1987 crash. The New York Stock Exchange
managed to handle the heavy trading volume because of a big
investment in technology made after the crash.
   In addition, traders were soothed by a promise over the weekend
by the Federal Reserve to supply fresh money to the financial
system if necessary to make sure banks kept loans flowing to
traders who lost money.
</TEXT>
