<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     10-17 0612</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0632</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar recovered from an early loss Tuesday
and finished mixed in U.S. trading after falling against most major
currencies in trading in Europe on news of a bigger-than-expected
U.S. trade deficit.
   Gold prices edged higher in New York after a mixed showing
overseas. Republic National Bank of New York quoted a late bid for
gold of $366.40 a troy ounce, up 60 cents from Monday's late bid.
   The dollar dropped early in the day on news that the U.S. trade
deficit widened in August to $10.77 billion when many traders were
expecting a deficit of about $9.5 billion.
   A rising deficit suggests the dollar is too expensive, making
American goods less competitive in foreign markets and making
foreign goods cheaper in the United States.
   But Graham Broyd, vice president in the foreign exchange
department at Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co., said the dollar
bounced back fairly quickly as traders focused for another day on
price movements in the U.S. stock market.
   ``From that point on, the dollar tracked movements of the stock
market,'' he said.
   The dollar fell as the Dow Jones industrial average dipped about
60 points early in the day, but then the currency recovered to
finish above the closing levels reached earlier in Europe as the
Dow Jones average retraced lost ground. The Dow Jones average
finished with a loss of about 19 points.
   One reason for the interaction between the two markets is that
the Federal Reserve may encourage lower interest rates if the stock
market were to come anywhere near Friday's 190.58-point decline in
the Dow Jones industrial average. Falling interest rates would make
the dollar less attractive to foreign investors.
   But Broyd said another reason is that many currency traders view
the U.S. stock market's recent volatility as more of a U.S. than a
worldwide problem. The volatility has been blamed by many
strategists on excessive borrowing for corporate takeovers.
   As a result, Broyd said currency traders feel a U.S. stock
market crash would hurt the dollar more than it would other
currencies.
   In Tokyo, the dollar rose to 142.25 Japanese yen from 140.75 yen
at Monday's close. Later in London it edged up further to 142.35
yen. In New York, the dollar rose to 142.70 yen from 141.80 yen on
Monday.
   The dollar weakened against the British pound. In London, the
British pound rose to $1.5835 from $1.5820 late Monday. Later in
New York, the pound edged up to $1.57575 from $1.5750 late Monday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York compared with late rates
Monday included: 1.8672 West German marks, down from 1.8680; 1.6365
Swiss francs, up from 1.6340; 6.3475 French francs, down from
6.3480; 1,400.375 Italian lire, up from 1,374.50; and 1.17555
Canadian dollars, down from 1,17675.
   Late dollar rates in Europe compared with late Monday included:
1.8520 West German marks, down from 1.8650; 1.6227 Swiss francs,
down from 1.6345; 6.2960 French francs, down from 6.3365; 2.0867
Dutch guilders, up from 2.0805; 1,365.00 Italian lire, down from
1,372.50; 1.1755 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1765.
   On New York's Commodity Exchange, gold for current delivery rose
10 cents a troy ounce to $367.40.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid of $367.75 a troy ounce, up
from $366.50 bid late Monday. In Zurich, the metal fell to a
closing bid of $366.90 from $367 bid late Monday. Earlier, in Hong
Kong, gold fell 42 cents to close at a bid $366.66.
   Silver for current delivery slipped 0.2 cent to $5.102 a troy
ounce on New York's Comex. In London, silver rose to a late bid of
$5.12 from $5.11 late Monday.
