<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0698</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trade Rumors Send Soy Soaring</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIO FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rumors of more U.S. trade with communist nations sent futures
traders scurrying to buy soybeans and corn Tuesday, eclipsing
stock-index futures as the the center of action in the commodity
pits.
   Futures prices for soybeans and corn were mostly higher while
wheat prices were steady on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Stock index futures settled slightly lower on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange after a big recovery the previous session that
helped erase much of the anxiety left from Friday, when prices
plunged and played a role in a big stock selloff.
   The contract for December delivery of stocks tracked by the
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 Index, which jumped a record 15.65 points
Monday, settled .50 point lower at 344 points Tuesday. Each point
is worth $500.
   ``The main story was soybeans _ where there were strong rumors
that the Soviets are in the market for beans and meal, and a fairly
large quanity,'' said Ted Mao, a grains analyst with Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc.
   Soybeans contracts for delivery this winter had gained as much
as 10 cents just before the closing bell, then slipped.
   Steve Freed, a Chicago-based analyst with Dean Witter Reynolds
Inc., also credited rains in U.S. central states harvest areas for
supporting soybeans.
   Corn was bolstered by Chinese demand, said Mao.
   Traders were talking about the possibility that the Chinese
could be buying as much as 500,000 metric tons. China purchased
150,000 metric tons of corn on Monday.
   Wheat settled unchanged to 1{ cents lower, with the contract for
delivery in December at $4.09{ a bushel; corn was { cent to 2{
cents higher, with December at $2.38} a bushel; oats were 1 cent to
1{ cents higher, with December at $1.43} a bushel; and soybeans
were unchanged to 8{ cents higher with November at $5.55{ a bushel.
   On the Chicago Mecantile Exchange, livestock and pork prices
moved higher.
   Frozen pork bellies led the way, with prices settling as high as
190 points or 1.90 cents above Monday's close.
   ``The market ignored lower cash prices,'' said Phil Stanley of
DEC Futures Inc. ``Traders just believe demand will remain good for
pork and this remains a strong psychological factor.''
   Meanwhile, packing company interest at higher prices supported
cattle futures, he said.
   Cattle settled cent.32 to .93 cent higher, with the contract for
delivery in October at 73.67 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20
cent to .47 cent higher, with October at 83.10 cents a pound; live
hogs were .10 cent to .72 cent higher, with October at 48.00 cents;
and frozen pork bellies were 1.82 cents to 1.90 cents higher, with
February at 52.52 cents a pound.
   Energy futures prices were generally higher on the New York
Mercantile Exchange.
   ``Heating oil was the star performer, pulling crude and gasoline
higher,'' said Jim Ritterbusch, vice president of trading and
research for Carson Petroleum Co. in Chicago.
   Heating oil was strengthened by overseas demand and rising
concerns about the availablity of natural gas from the Soviet Union.
   Crude oil settled 14 cents to 16 cents higher, with the contract
for delivery in November at $20.75 a barrel; heating oil was .45
cent to .72 cent higher, with November at 61.05 cents a gallon; and
unleaded gasoline was .01 cent lower to 1.00 cent higher, with
November at 55.84 cents a gallon.
   Precious metals were steady on the Commodity Exchange in New
York.
   Craig Sloane, an analyst in New York for Smith Barney, Harris
Upham &amp; Co., said there was a brief flurry of gold buying during
the day due to the 60-point dip in the Dow Jones Industrials and a
decline in the U.S. dollar.
   But when the dollar and New York Stock Exchange recovered, gold
prices also drifted lower, he said.
   Gold settled unchanged to 20 cents higher, with the contract for
October at $367.40 a troy ounce; and silver was .2 cents to .7
cents lower, with October at $5.10 a troy ounce.
</TEXT>
