<HEAD>Prices Finish Lower</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: With AM-Markets Rdp. Stands for AM-Bonds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Treasury bond market ended lower in
brisk, choppy trading Tuesday as investors moved in step with an
unsteady stock market.
   Market analysts said bonds relinquished earlier gains as prices
of stocks started to improve.
   ``Those that had bought are now giving up the hope that the
stock market will continue to tumble and that the flight to quality
into bonds will continue,'' said Jay Goldinger, a principal at the
Beverly Hills, Calif., investment firm Capital Insight Inc.
   The closely watched Dow Jones industrial average closed down
18.65 points at 2,638.73 Tuesday, after losing as much as 63 points
in late-morning trading. Analysts said the credit markets generally
shrugged off a government report that the merchandise trade deficit
rose in August to $10.77 billion from a revised July gap of $8.24
billion. The government also said industrial production edged down
0.1 percent in September.
   Both reports initially were intepreted by the credit markets to
mean that the economy was sluggish and interest rates had room to
decline.
   But as Robert A. Brusca, chief financial economist with Nikko
Securities Co. International, explained, ``The market was not at
all behaving to fundamentals.''
   The credit markets also showed little reaction to news that the
Federal Reserve injected another $1.5 billion into the banking
system Tuesday after adding $2 billion in reserves on Monday.
   In the secondary market for Treasury bonds, the bellwether
30-year issue, fell about | point, or $6.25 per $1,000 face amount,
after rising around $6.25 by midday. Its yield, which moves
inversely from its price, jumped to 8.03 percent from 7.97 percent.
   The closely watched issue had fallen around $17.50 on Monday,
wiping out nearly all of the huge gains from Friday's rally.
   Prices of short-term government issues were off around 1-32
point, intermediate maturities fell between [ point and 5-16 point
and long-term issues lost around | point, according to figures
provided by Telerate Inc., a financial-information service.
   The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $10 in the
price of a bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Hutton Daily Treasury Bond Index, which
measures price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with
maturities of a year or longer, stood at 1,186.58, down 2.57.
   Meanwhile, yields on three-month Treasury bills rose to 7.75
percent as the discount gained 15 basis points to 7.51 percent.
Yields on six-month bills rose to 7.91 percent as the discount
gained 11 basis points to 7.52 percent. Yields on one-year bills
rose to 7.87 percent as the discount gained 2 basis points to 7.36
percent.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, traded at 8 11-16 percent, up from 8| percent late Monday.
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds rose 2-32 point to 93 3-32. The average
yield to maturity increased to 7.29 percent from 7.28 percent.
   In corporate bond trading, highly rated issues were unchanged to
slightly higher. Moody's Investment Grade Corporate Bond Index,
which measures total return on a portfolio of 80 corporate bonds
with maturities of five years or longer, rose 0.02 to 336.02.
   The $200 billion high-yield ``junk'' bond market continued to
improve from Friday, when trading was at a near-standstill. Traders
said activity was picking up and prices of the more widely traded
issues ranged from { point down to { point up.
