<FIRST>r f AM-Trade-WhatItMeans     10-17 0121</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trade-What It Means,0125</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Trade Deficit Increase: What It Means</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 31 percent increase in the nation's trade
deficit in August means Americans dug themselves deeper into debt
with the rest of the world.
   The trade deficit is the imbalance between what Americans buy
from overseas and what they ship to foreign customers. It rose in
August because exports declined a slight 0.2 percent while imports
jumped by 6.4 percent.
   The imbalance threatens jobs because it means consumers are
buying products made abroad instead of ones made by American
workers.
   Nations that run trade surpluses with the United States are
accumulating piles of dollars that they use to buy U.S. stocks,
bonds, factories and real estate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
