<FIRST>u f AM-IntegratedResources     10-17 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Integrated Resources,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>Calls Off Talks With Unidentified Buyer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Integrated Resources Inc. said Tuesday it had
abandoned talks to sell core financial businesses to an
unidentified buyer and raised its estimate of second-quarter losses
above the previously announced $600 million.
   But Integrated said a group of senior executive officers had
advised the firm that it intends to make a proposal to buy three of
the five principal financial businesses.
   The struggling investment concern, which defaulted on debt
payments in June, had been negotiating to sell key assets to raise
money to pay some of its $1.75 billion in outstanding debt and
avoid a bankruptcy filing.
   The annoucements Tuesday sent Integrated stock falling 25 cents
to $1.25 on the New York Stock Exchange. Integrated was trading
around $16 a share in May.
   Integrated's principal financial businesses are Integrated
Resources Equity Corp. of Englewood, Colo., its principal
broker-dealer subsidiary; Resources Trust Co.; and Integrated
Resources Asset Management Corp., an investment adviser.
   The firm also is seeking to sell two of its life insurance
companies, Integrated Resources Life Insurance Co. of Des Moines,
Iowa, and Capitol Life Insurance Co. of Denver.
   ``If we can arrange the sale of these three core companies, we
feel that we will be in a stronger position to sell Integrated
Resources Life Insurance Co. and maximize its value,'' Integrated
Chairman Stephen Weinroth said in a statement.
   ``Accordingly, we feel that this proposal should be considered
in order to further our overall restructuring plan,'' he said.
   Integrated said last week it was negotating with an unidentified
third party for the sale of the five principal financial companies
after a $310 million deal with Whitehall Financial Group fell
through.
   Privately held Whitehall said it could not obtain financing for
the planned $310 million transaction, citing worsening conditions
in the nation's debt financing markets and concerns over the value
of the businesses.
   Integrated has not paid any principal or interest to bondholders
since June, when it said it would have to default because of
worsening troubles stemming from its difficulty in diversifying out
of real estate into financial services.
   Integrated said its previously announced estimate of $600
million in second-quarter losses after taxes was based partly on
the planned sale of its core financial businesses.
   The firm said it expects to report a higher loss because ``of
the change in its expectations as to the proceeds from a sale of
the core businesses as well as other events which have occurred
subsequent to Integrated's previous announcement.''
</TEXT>
