<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-89 2058EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Grain-China     10-17 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Grain-China,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Buys More U.S. Wheat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China has bought additional U.S. wheat under a
price subsidy program, the Agriculture Department said Tuesday.
   F. Paul Dickerson, general sales manager for the department's
Foreign Agricultural Service, said three private exporting
companies made the deals for a total of 300,000 metric tons under
the department's Export Enhancement Program, or EEP.
   Dickerson said the sales were part of 2 million tons authorized
China under EEP last Feb. 27.
   With the latest EEP approvals, China has 340,000 tons remaining
to be used under the current authorization.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels
of wheat. The latest sales would be about 11 million bushels. At
current prices estimated by USDA at $3.85 per bushel, the wheat
would have a farm value of around $42 milion.
   Under EEP arrangements, private exporters can sell U.S.
commodities at reduced prices to meet foreign competition in
selected overseas markets and then collect free government
surpluses of grain or other commodities as bonuses, or subsidies.
   Dickerson said the latest subsidies averaged $12.81 per ton, or
about 35 cents per bushel.
   The subsidized sales were handled by the Peavey Co., 210,000
tons; Cargill Inc., 50,000; and Bunge Corp., 40,000.
   With the latest sales, China has bought about 4.3 million tons
of U.S. wheat for delivery in the 1989-90 marketing year that began
on June 1, most of it without subsidies. In 1988-89, China bought
more than 8 million tons of U.S. wheat, all of it under the EEP
program.
</TEXT>
