<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-89 2133EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Polaroid     10-17 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Polaroid,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reports Earnings of $29.9 Million In Third Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polaroid Corp. on Tuesday reported third
quarter earnings of $29.9 million, compared with a loss the company
took during the same period in 1988 amid an anti-takeover
restructuring.
   The camera and film maker had a $54.1 million loss in the third
quarter last year, or a loss of 77 cents per share. For the third
quarter of 1989, which ended Oct. 1, the company reported earnings
of 40 cents per share.
   The 1988 loss included a $97 million charge to cover costs
associated with the restructuring plan, which included the
elimination of more than 1,000 jobs under a voluntary severance
plan.
   The restructuring plan was intended partly to thwart a takeover
attempt by Shamrock Holdings, an entity controlled by Roy E.
Disney, nephew of Walt Disney.
   In a prepared statement, I. MacAllister Booth, president and
chief executive officer, said: ``We continue to show improvement in
both gross margin and overhead spending resulting in increases in
operating profits for the third quarter and for the year to date.''
   For the first nine months of this year, earnings were $98.5
million, or $1.27 per share, compared with a loss of $15.1 million,
or 23 cents per share, during the same period last year.
   Total sales for the quarter were $437.7 million, a slight
increase from $436.3 million in 1988. For the first nine months,
sales were $1.36 billion, compared with $1.33 billion in the same
period last year.
   The company, known for its instant photography, said it
introduced its line of conventional film in Europe late in the
third quarter and was receiving strong initial demand.
</TEXT>
