<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Weyerhaeuser     10-17 0201</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Weyerhaeuser,0207</SECOND>
<HEAD>Posts 15 Percent Earnings Gain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Weyerhaeuser Co. said Tuesday its
third-quarter earnings rose 15 percent from a year ago but noted
the earnings were affected by some corporate restructuring and a
stock sale.
   For the quarter, the timber company earned $166.8 million or 78
cents per share on sales of $2.57 billion, compared with earnings
of $144.9 million or 69 cents a share on sales of $2.36 billion a
year earlier.
   For the first nine months, Weyerhaeuser's earnings totaled
$469.8 million or $2.21 a share on sales of $7.54 billion, compared
with earnings of $410.3 million or $1.95 a share on sales of $6.95
billion.
   Weyerhaeuser said third-quarter figures include losses of $33
million stemming from its business improvement and refocusing
program, but a gain of $49 million from selling stock in its North
Pacific Paper Co. subsidiary to Jujo Paper of Japan. That had the
effect of adding 5 cents per share to the earnings for the third
quarter.
   Weyerhaeuser has sold or is seeking buyers for a number of
secondary operations, including its nursery supply business, milk
carton operation, Australian remanufacturing and distributing
company, and a small health and beauty aids company.
