<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-89 2015EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Earns-Banks 2ndLd-Writethru f0309 10-17 0829</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Banks, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0309,0850</SECOND>
<HEAD>Earnings Down At Citicorp, Up at Wells; Manufacturers Hanover Posts
Loss</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to UPDATE with Bank of New England report; INSERTS
1 new graf after 6th graf pvs, `Wells Fargo ...,' to ADD the bank's figures;
ADDS 3 grafs with more detail on the bank's earnings, restructuring program.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Citicorp, the nation's largest banking company, said Tuesday
that third-quarter earnings fell 9 percent compared with a year
ago, while No. 7 Manufacturers Hanover Corp. posted a $789 million
loss due to a big addition to its reserve for bad Third World loans.
   Separately, No. 11-ranked Wells Fargo &amp; Co. reported its
earnings rose 17 percent during the quarter, and No. 15 Bank of New
England Corp. said its earnings dropped 41 percent in the period.
   New York-based Citicorp earned $358 million, or 99 cents per
share, in the three months ended Sept. 30, compared with earnings
of $394 million, or $1.13 a share, last year. Combined interest
income and non-interest income gained 11 percent to $3.5 billion.
   Manufacturers Hanover posted a loss of $789 million, or $15.46
per share, compared with a profit of $198 million, or $3.77 per
share, in third quarter 1988. Combined interest and non-interest
revenue declined to $796 million from $949 million in the year
earlier quarter.
   Wells Fargo, based in San Francisco, earned $153.7 million, or
$2.83 a share, in the third quarter, up from $131.7 million, or
$2.36 per share, in 1988.
   Bank of New England earned $42.7 million, or 61 cents a share,
compared with a profit of $72.3 million, or $1.04 a share, in last
year's third quarter.
   Citicorp said it had strong results from many areas, including
the global consumer business and domestic credit-card operation.
   But it said continued uncertainty about Third World debt helped
drag down earnings. It noted that Argentina made no loan payments
this year, vs. $26 million reported in the first three quarters of
last year, while Brazil made no payments in the third quarter after
paying $154 million the previous two quarters.
   Citicorp said its reserve to cover possible losses on Third
World debt was $2.6 billion at the end of the third quarter, or 30
percent of its $8.9 billion in total medium- and long-term loans to
less developed countries.
   For the first nine months of 1989, Citicorp earned $1.3 billion,
or $3.62 cents a share, up 15 percent from $1.1 billion, or $3.17 a
share, in net income for the 1988 period.
   The results include, among other things, a $77 million after-tax
gain from the sale of property in Japan this year and a $55 million
after-tax gain from the sale of the U.S. pension fund management
business last year.
   Manufacturers Hanover's net loss stemmed from the addition of
$950 million to its reserve against possible losses on loans to
developing countries, announced earlier this year. Without the
reserve addition and tax benefits, the company would have had net
income of $91 million.
   The company said the addition boosted its reserve for Third
World loans rose to $2.4 billion, or 36 percent of its total
outstanding medium- and long-term loans to developing countries.
   Manufacturers Hanover said its operating earnings benefited from
an improved net interest margin, better domestic credit quality and
expense control. Results for the third quarter included $213
million in one-time revenue from the sale of assets, down from $578
million in the year-earlier quarter.
   For the first nine months of 1989, Manufacturers Hanover said it
lost $580 million, or $11.82 per share, compared with profit of
$742 million, or $14.28 per share, a year earlier.
   Wells Fargo said its earnings rose in the third quarter largely
from higher net interest income, specifically from an increase in
domestic loans. Net interest income rose to $544 million from $508
million a year ago.
   Non-interest income was $191.9 million, compared with $193.3
million, while non-interest expense was $393.4 million, up form
$392.7 million.
   At the end of the third quarter Wells Fargo said it had no
medium- or long-term loans to less developed countries. Its
provision for overall loan losses rose to $82 million from $75
million.
   During the nine-month period, Wells Fargo's earnings totaled
$442.6 million, or $8.07 a share, vs. $376.6 million, or $6.75 a
share, in 1988.
   Bank of New England said its net interest income totaled $254.7
million, down 10 percent from last year's third quarter.
Non-interest income totaled $114.4 million, compared with $95.2
million in the year-ago period.
   For the first nine months of this year, earnings were $121.6
million, or $1.73 per share, down from $207.7 million, or $3 per
share for the first nine months last year.
   Bank of New England also announced a restructuring that will
include the sale of 53 branches and the consolidation of a number
of departments that will result in the loss of 800 jobs. In
addition, it will close its loan-production offices in Chicago, New
York and Philadelphia.
</TEXT>
