<FIRST>r f BC-Simmon     10-17 0209s-Lockheed</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Simmons-Lockheed,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>Simmons Buys More Lockheed Stock</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While the stock market was dropping Friday, Dallas
billionaire Harold C. Simmons was buying more stock in Lockheed
Corp., increasing his holding in the defense contractor to 10.62
percent.
   Simmons filed documents Monday with the Securities and Exchange
Commission saying companies he controls purchased 122,700 shares of
Lockheed on Friday at prices ranging from $47.12{ to $48 per share.
   The purchases give Simmons 6.74 million shares of the Calabasas,
Calif.-based company, making him its largest individual shareholder.
   Simmons began acquiring stock in the maker of the stealth
fighter in April, sparking speculation he intended to take over the
company. Lockheed responded by creating an employee stock ownership
plan that holds 17 percent of the company's stock, effectively
blocking an unfriendly takeover.
   The latest filing says Simmons had not changed his plans for the
stake. In his original statement he said his purchases were ``for
purposes of investment and in order to acquire a significant equity
interest in the company.''
   Simmons included in the filing a statement refuting a weekend
report he intended to sell his Lockheed stake. Simmons said the
report took out of context statements he had made in jest at the
end of a lengthy interview.
