<FILEID>AP-NR-10-17-89 2156EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Earns-Drugs 1stLd-Writethru f0314 10-17 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Drugs, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0314,0485</SECOND>
<HEAD>Merck, Warner-Lambert Report Higher Third-Quarter Earnings</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead and ADDS 3 grafs to UPDATE with Rohm and Haas earnings.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Three major drug makers announced higher third-quarter earnings
Tuesday, with profits up 25 percent at Merck &amp; Co. Inc., 22 percent
at Warner-Lambert Co. and 24 percent at Eli Lilly &amp; Co. Meanwhile,
Rohm and Haas Co. reported a 35 percent decline in third-quarter
earnings.
   Rahway, N.J.-based Merck said its earnings rose to $390.5
million, or 99 cents a share, from $311.8 million, or 79 cents a
share, a year earlier. Sales rose 9 percent to $1.6 billion from
$1.4 billion.
   For the first nine months of its fiscal year, earnings rose to
$1.1 billion, or $2.85 a share, up from $899 million, or $2.28 a
share, in 1988. Sales were $4.78 billion, up from $4.40 billion.
   ``Sales growth for the first nine months was led by new
products,'' Merck Chairman P. Roy Vagelos said in a news release.
``Strong unit volume gains were registered by our both our domestic
and international operations.''
   Morris Plains, N.J.-based Warner-Lambert said its net earnings
for the quarter rose to $107 million, or $1.58 a share, from $88
million, or $1.29 a share, a year earlier. Sales rose 7 percent to
$1.10 billion from $1.03 billion a year earlier, Warner-Lambert
said.
   For the first nine months of its fiscal year, Warner-Lambert
said its earnings rose to $320.4 million, or $4.73 a share, from
$262.8 million, or $3.86 a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose to
$3.15 billion from $2.91 billion.
   Eli Lilly said profit in its latest quarter rose to $212.4
million, or 73 cents a share, from $171.4 million, or 60 cents a
share, a year earlier. Revenue rose to $1.05 billion from $941
million a year earlier.
   For the first nine months of the year, Lilly said earnings rose
to $714.2 million, or $2.45 a share, from $585.3 million, or $2.04
a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose to $3.39 billion from $3.03
billion.
   Philadelphia-based Rohm and Haas earned $32.6 million, or 49
cents per share, in the third quarter, compared with $49.8 million,
or 75 cents per share, in 1988.
   Sales of $623 million were up 1 percent from last year's
third-quarter sales of $619.8 million, the company said.
   ``The effects of a slowing U.S. economy, capacity limitations
for key product lines and high costs associated with our capital
expenditure program combined to push earnings well below the 1988
level,'' said Chairman J. Lawrence Wilson.
   Profit for the first nine months of 1989 totaled $155 million,
or $2.33 per share, a 17 percent decrease from earnings of $187.8
million, or $2.82 per share, in the same 1988 period. Nine-month
sales totaled $2 billion, a 5 percent increase over the $1.9
billion reported in 1988.
</TEXT>
