<FIRST>u f AM-Markets-Japan 2ndLd-Writethru f0383 10-17 0563</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Markets-Japan, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0383,0580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Share Prices Jump In Tokyo Morning Trading</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Markets Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with close of Tokyo's morning
session, other Asian markets rebounding; Picks up 10th graf pvs, `Some
analysts ...' EDITS to tighten.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices rebounded sharply on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange Tuesday morning, while the U.S. dollar firmed against the
Japanese yen.
   Other stock markets in Asia followed suit, rebounding from
significant losses posted Monday.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which shed
647.33 points Monday in its biggest tumble of the year, regained
most of that in the morning session in Tokyo by rising 618.89
points, or 1.79 percent, to 35,087.38.
   Dealers said the market was encouraged by the rebound Monday on
Wall Street, which saw the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rise
88.12 points following Friday's 190.58-point plunge.
   ``It is just the opposite of Monday's trading pattern,'' said a
dealer with Nikko Securities, a major Japanese brokerage.
   The dealer, who spoke anonymously, said the market was filled
with buy orders. ``There are no sell orders at all.''
   The recovery of the Dow Jones and Nikkei indexes gave the U.S.
dollar a boost. The dollar started trading at 141.97 yen, up 1.22
yen from Monday's close, and firmed to 142.10 yen at the end of the
morning.
   ``The only news is that the stock market has rebounded. There
has been nothing else this morning,'' said Sumio Fukushima, a
dealer with Sumitomo Bank.
   The dollar should remain in a narrow range until the release in
Washington later Tuesday of U.S. trade figures for August, a dealer
with the Bank of Tokyo said.
   Meanwhile, in Hong Kong, the Hang Seng Index rose 4.5 percent in
the first 10 minutes of trading. The index had plunged 6.5 percent
Monday.
   Market indexes in Australia and New Zealand, which fell about 8
percent Monday, were up 3.5 percent and 6.2 percent, respectively,
while the Manila exchange opened 1.11 percent higher, recouping
some of Monday's 5.92 percent drop. Singapore's market rallied 4.4
percent in early trading after plunging 10 percent Monday.
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange, which was the first major foreign
market to open open after the Dow Jones industrial average fell
190.58 points Friday in New York, on Monday weathered its biggest
dive this year without sustained panic selling.
   Some analysts had feared the Friday the 13th slide in New York
would trigger a worldwide crash like in 1987, when Wall Street's
Black Monday, Oct. 19,1987 was followed by Black Tuesday plunges
around the world.
   But on Monday, trading was thin and the capital-rich Tokyo
market's main barometer dropped 1.8 percent _ compared with its
record 15 percent drop on Oct. 20, 1987.
   ``Domestic economic conditions are still favorable,'' Japanese
Finance Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto told reporters, explaining he
did not think the Wall Street turmoil would cause a collapse in
Tokyo.
   The dollar also tumbled in Tokyo, opening at 139.95 yen, sharply
lower than its Friday closes of 144.00 yen in Tokyo and 142.05 yen
in New York, but bounced back to finish at 140.75 yen.
   Other Far East financial markets posted losses ranging from
moderate to large on Monday. But Asian investors did not send share
prices reeling as deeply as they did two years ago after Wall
Street crashed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
